<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 00:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grammys Notebook  </HEADLINE>
    By CYNTHIA L. WEBB Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A band leader for 50 years and 118 albums to his credit,
Latin legend Tito Puente says he has another accomplishment: role model.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm very honored to be here and I hope I continue to be a role model to all
the young Latin people coming up in this profession," Puente said backstage.
</P>
<P>
	   Puente got his fifth Grammy on Wednesday for best traditional tropical Latin
performance for "Mambo Birdland."
</P>
<P>
	   He said the explosion of Latin music chart-toppers has helped bolster his
own career, which has seen 10 Grammy nominations.
</P>
<P>
	   "Well, it doesn't hurt, but I'm not Ricky Martin, I'm not Marc Anthony --
I'm sure not Jennifer Lopez," said Puente, wiggling his behind in an apparent
reference to the actress and her much-hyped derriere.
</P>
<P>
	   Puente also introduced his son backstage, Tito Puente Jr., who has a music
career of his own. His style is different from his dad's classic tunes -- he
plays house music. He towered over his dad, thanks to thick platform shoes.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Blues guitar master B. B. King, his ninth Grammy in hand, said he has
already made plans for a posthumous career.
</P>
<P>
	   "I've had some friends encourage me to retire and they ask me when I would
and my answer is five to 10 years after I am dead," said the 74-year-old
musician.
</P>
<P>
	   King got his first Grammy in 1970. On Wednesday, he won for best traditional
blues album for "Blues on the Bayou."
</P>
<P>
	   He is working on an album with Eric Clapton.
</P>
<P>
	   "What can I tell you -- I just wish I could do more," King said backstage.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Carlos Santana wasn't the only rock elder recognized Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Black Sabbath, a heavy-metal band that came of age in the 1970s, won for
best metal performance for "Iron Man," off the album "Reunion."
</P>
<P>
	   "I didn't think that 31 years ago, I'd be standing up in a suit. I feel more
like an accountant than the guy who plays drums in Black Sabbath," said Bill
Ward, whose only sign of being a rocker was multiple earrings adorning his ear.
</P>
<P>
	   He called the recognition of older artists gratifying.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it's totally cool," Ward said.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Crooner Tony Bennett got his ninth Grammy on Wednesday -- a win that the
prolific singer said inspires him to turn out another hit.
</P>
<P>
	   "Boy, I just feel like going back in the recording studio and doing another
one," Bennett said backstage. He won for best traditional pop vocal performance
for his "Bennett Sings Ellington -- Hot &AMP; Cool."
</P>
<P>
	   He wouldn't reveal what project he's working on next, saying he thinks it
"would be lifted by someone else."
</P>
<P>
	   At 73, Bennett says he has no plans to stop singing.
</P>
<P>
	   "I love what I'm doing ... it's such an adventure," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   "NYPD Blue" star Dennis Franz says his work for the "Dixie Chicks" made him
feel right at home.
</P>
<P>
	   The country trio asked Franz to play a part in their music video --
broadcast during the Grammys -- for the song "Goodbye Earl."
</P>
<P>
	   When the musicians asked the actor to take part, Franz said they told him
"the character in the video -- he is a pretty nasty fella. And I said, 'I've
done that before, so let's go for it."'
</P>
<P>
	   "The Dixie Chicks" won for best country album for "Fly" and best country
performance by a duo or group with vocal for their hit "Ready to Run."
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Rosie O'Donnell, who emceed the show, had fun with the non-musical troubles
of industry stars.
</P>
<P>
	   "Good news everyone, Puff Daddy has left the building," she announced at one
point. "He was in the front row and it's a comfort to me, trust me."
</P>
<P>
	   Puff Daddy, a nickname for the rap artist Sean "Puffy" Combs, was indicted
Wednesday along with a bodyguard on charges of bribing a witness to say he owned
a gun police found as Combs drove from a New York nightclub after a shooting.
Combs also faces gun possession charges in connection with the Dec. 27 shooting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
