<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2nd Death Sentence in Torture Death  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- A jury that took just 20 minutes to convict a
former grocery store worker in an Arlington woman's torture and slaying
sentenced him to die for the crime Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The jury rejected defense attorneys' claims that Michael Wayne Hall's life
should be spared because he is mentally impaired. Hall's videotaped confession,
which jurors saw twice during the trial, contradicted the characterization.
</P>
<P>
	   In the tape made after his arrest in March 1998, Hall, 20, was articulate as
he described in detail how he and Robert Neville Jr. lured Amy Robinson, 19,
into their car and later killed her.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There was no remorse shown at the time -- just laughter. Doesn't that
speak volumes? This is not about Michael Hall's mental ability, but about his
soul,'' prosecutor Christy Jack told jurors.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors said Hall helped Neville, who was convicted in 1998 and
sentenced to die, select the victim and hide the evidence.
</P>
<P>
	   In separate television interviews, Hall and Neville described using the
Robinson for ``target practice,'' shooting her with arrows, a pellet gun and a
rifle, which finally killed her.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
