<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain surges in New York, but still has uphill battle  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A new poll says John McCain is in a dead heat among
Republicans with George W. Bush for New York's GOP-only primary, bringing up
questions of whether the state Republican party can actually deliver the state
for their favored candidate.
<P>
	   "New York is definitely in play for the Republicans," said pollster Lee
Miringoff, head of Marist College's Institute for Public Opinion.
</P>
<P>
	   The Marist poll had Bush favored by 43 percent of Republican voters to 41
percent for McCain. In December, the Texas governor led McCain, 59 percent to 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
	   While Bush retains the support of most of New York's top Republican leaders,
including New York Gov. George Pataki and state GOP Chairman William Powers,
there are those who say GOP leaders are getting nervous.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm not the only one with food-poisoning symptoms in New York state this
morning," said an under-the-weather Jay Severin, a New York-based GOP
consultant. "There's a train coming to New York and the Republican establishment
has only two choices, you can get on it or you get struck by it."
</P>
<P>
	   Even before Tuesday's Michigan and Arizona primaries, there had been signs
of trouble for Bush in New York. On Saturday, U.S. Rep. Peter King of Long
Island switched his allegiance from Bush to McCain. State Assemblymen Joel
Miller of Poughkeepsie and Philip Boyle of Long Island have also joined the
McCain camp in recent days.
</P>
<P>
	   Publicly, state GOP leaders professed little concern Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm not nervous," said state Assembly Minority Leader John Faso, a Bush
backer and Pataki political ally.
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, McCain has very real problems in New York as he prepares for the
state's "Super Tuesday" March 7 primary, where 93 delegates will be at stake.
There are primaries or caucuses that same day in more than a dozen other states,
including California. That can stretch resources thin.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, only previously registered Republicans can vote in New York's GOP
presidential primary, unlike the open primaries of New Hampshire and Michigan
where McCain was boosted by votes from Democrats and independents.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has only eight paid employees in New York and most of those aren't
political professionals.
</P>
<P>
	   "The other people here, while they may be involved in local politics, when
the campaign is over, one of them goes back to work at his engineering firm,
another guy goes back to work in a local government office, another guy goes
back to work doing this, that and the other thing," said Gerry O'Brien, McCain's
New York political director. "We don't have a tremendous number of people to
draw on from the professional side of things."
</P>
<P>
	   That's because Bush has almost the entire New York Republican Party
hierarchy, led by Pataki and Powers, working for him. The state party's
get-out-the-vote machinery is at the ready and most local Republican leaders are
in the Texas governor's corner.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'd say he's well supported by the people who are well supported by
Republicans in this state," said Ellen DiFrancisco, the Bush campaign's
executive director in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, while McCain was able to leave New York's GOP with a black eye by
successfully beating back an attempt to keep him off the primary ballot, the
ballot itself shows off a Bush advantage.
</P>
<P>
	   In New York, primary voters vote for the delegates, not the candidates. The
Bush delegate slates are peopled with the famous names of New York's GOP
establishment.
</P>
<P>
	   For example, one eastern New York congressional district, the Bush delegate
slate includes state Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, Lt. Gov. Mary Donohue
and U.S. Rep. John Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
	   "Republicans walk into a voting booth in a Republican primary, they will see
names they recognize and that they trust," Powers said.
</P>
<P>
	   Not so for McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   "To vote for John McCain, they're going to have to vote for these names, in
a lot of cases, people have never heard of," said state Assemblyman Thomas
Kirwan of Newburgh, one of the few elected Republicans for McCain. "Unless they
know what the deal is, they're going to go in and vote and they're going to vote
for the names they're familiar with."
</P>
<P>
	   To counter that, the McCain camp has launched a voter education effort
utilizing news conferences, phone calls and mailings.
</P>
<P>
	   The stakes for Pataki are high.
</P>
<P>
	   "Governor Pataki has pledged an all out effort to win New York for Governor
Bush and everyone's going to be working on the campaign, from the delegates on
up," DiFrancisco said.
</P>
<P>
	   But Powers admitted some concern.
</P>
<P>
	   "You always have to be worried," he said. "But again, if you look at it, the
entire Republican organization is there, a lot of Republican officials are there
and a lot of them are (prospective) delegates. They'll all want to be out
working in their districts to make sure that they win."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
