<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polls: Bush and McCain competitive in New York  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Two statewide polls show Sen. John McCain poised to
give Texas Gov. George W. Bush a tough test in New York's March 7 presidential
primary.
<P>
	   A CBS News/New York Times poll out today has Bush leading McCain, 43 percent
to 36 percent, with Alan Keyes at 4 percent among enrolled Republican voters.
</P>
<P>
	   Another poll, out Wednesday from Marist College's Institute for Public
Opinion, found Bush supported by 43 percent of Republican voters in New York
with McCain backed by 41 percent, a statistical tie given the poll's margin of
error. Keyes trailed at 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Among those Republicans considered likely to vote in the state's primary, 46
percent said they backed Bush while 43 percent said they favored McCain, also a
statistical tie in the Marist poll. One percent said they backed Keyes while 9
percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
	   A Feb. 8 Marist poll found Bush leading McCain, 46 percent to 35 percent,
among registered Republicans and, 48 percent to 39 percent, among likely GOP
primary voters. A December poll from Marist had Bush leading McCain, 59 percent
to 15 percent among New York Republicans.
</P>
<P>
	   The CBS News/New York Times poll found Al Gore leading Bill Bradley, 59
percent to 28 percent, among Democratic voters in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   The polling news, plus McCain's primary wins Tuesday in Michigan and
Arizona, means "invincibility has been shattered, electability is now on the
table" on the Republican side, according to Marist pollster Lee Mirningoff.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's popularity among New York Republicans has been on the rise since
his strong primary victory over Bush in New Hampshire. That came in the wake of
his highly publicized and successful battle to get on the New York primary
ballot despite the efforts of Bush's New York backers, including Gov. George
Pataki and state GOP Chairman William Powers, to keep the senator from Arizona
off the ballot.
</P>
<P>
	   Marist College's latest telephone survey of 363 registered Republicans was
conducted Sunday through Tuesday of this week and has a margin of error of plus
or minus 5 percentage points. The margin of error for the sample of 201 likely
GOP voters is plus or minus 7 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
	   The CBS News/New York Times telephone poll was conducted Feb. 16-22. The
sample of 374 Republicans carries with it a margin of error of plus or minus 5
percentage points. The margin of error for the sample of 542 Democrats was plus
or minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-24-00 0007 </TRAILER>
