<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Companies Look to Foreign Money  </HEADLINE>
    By TOM KIRCHOFER AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BOSTON (AP) -- With a barrage of advertising and countless storefront
investment centers, mutual fund companies have transformed the way Americans
think about their money.
</P>
<P>
	   Now they want to spread the personal investing movement to the rest of the
world.
</P>
<P>
	   Overseas investors currently represent a tiny fraction of most large retail
investment companies' business, but a number of American firms have big plans
for managing the money of people who live outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's in the international markets, for all the companies, where the growth
opportunities lie," said Maliz Beams, who heads the international retail mutual
fund group at Scudder Kemper Investments. "That's where everyone is putting a
stake in the ground."
</P>
<P>
	   Many investment managers consider Americans to be the world's most
sophisticated personal investors. About 48 percent of American households own
mutual funds, contributing a collective total of $6.45 trillion to world
financial markets. At the heart of the trend is the phasing out of old-fashioned
pension plans which has forced millions of Americans take an interest in
investing through programs such as the 401(k).
</P>
<P>
	   But some investment managers fear the tremendous growth in the American
market for products such as mutual funds might be slowing.
</P>
<P>
	   So now they're looking overseas.
</P>
<P>
	   Some foreign countries still have the old-style retirement plans -- plans
that governments and employers are beginning to realize will be extremely
costly, and in some cases, don't provide enough benefits to support retirees.
</P>
<P>
	   Japan, for example, is moving toward a system similar to the 401(k), in
which workers and their employers both contribute to an investment account.
</P>
<P>
	   South Korea, Taiwan, the United Kingdom, Germany, Spain and Italy are also
popular targets for American money managers.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is a growing understanding that retirement planning is going to be on
the individual level," Beams said. "(People) are leaving the traditional
investment world, the checking and savings accounts, and moving much more
rapidly into mutual funds."
</P>
<P>
	   Fidelity International Limited, the Bermuda-based international arm of
mutual fund giant Fidelity Investments, manages about $110 billion -- about 10
percent of its Boston-based parent's assets.
</P>
<P>
	   "But it could be potentially many times the size of the U.S. market," said
Paul Kafka, an executive director at Fidelity International.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the $127 billion managed by Boston-based Nvest Associates, only $7.2
billion comes from overseas, and most of that is from institutional investors.
Fleet Investment Management has less than $1 billion in overseas money in its
$38 billion mutual fund portfolio.
</P>
<P>
	   "I truly would like to move that over the next five years to about 40
percent of our business," said Fleet's senior managing director and chief
executive officer, Robert Ash.
</P>
<P>
	   Tax codes generally block foreign investors from taking advantage of most
American investment products.
</P>
<P>
	   To get around those hindrances, many firms register their products in
foreign countries and gear them exclusively to foreign residents. But such plans
are frequently tailored for wealthier investors, making average-income people in
other countries an under-served but potentially huge market.
</P>
<P>
	   While its often said in the investment management industry that the United
States is about 10 years ahead of the rest of the world in terms investing
sophistication, Scudder Kemper's Beams said new investment options around the
world will quickly help close that gap.
</P>
<P>
	   "The U.S. really led the way, in terms of mutual funds particularly, but the
second wave of innovation doesn't take as much time," she said. "The jump for
the international markets will be much faster."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0008 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investors May Pick Trading Markets  </HEADLINE>
    By MARCY GORDON AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- You call your broker. You want to buy 50 shares of a hot
new tech stock, but you don't stop there: you also choose the market in which
you believe you can get the best price on your trade.
</P>
<P>
	   The scenario may not be far-fetched, a top securities regulator said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Change has been sweeping the markets, as millions of new investors and
increasing competition from new electronic communications networks have put
pressure on the nation's two biggest exchanges, the New York Stock Exchange and
the Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
	   If the traditional exchanges and the networks, known as ECNs, were linked
nationwide, with a central electronic "order book" showing all stock quotes,
individual investors could choose a specific market for a trade, said Annette
Nazareth, director of market regulation at the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
</P>
<P>
	   "It may lead to that," Nazareth told reporters in a telephone conference
call. "Customers will start to require" their brokers to make trades in a
specific market.
</P>
<P>
	   She noted that some brokers already have started to offer such choices to
their customers.
</P>
<P>
	   Nazareth was discussing a "concept release" which the SEC put out for 60
days of public comment, presenting several possible options for changing how
stocks are traded and quoted. The option likely to arouse the most controversy
is that of a central, nationwide system displaying orders to buy and sell.
</P>
<P>
	   "If the U.S. markets fail to meet investor needs by offering the fairest and
most efficient trading mechanisms possible, an increasingly competitive
international environment will be sure to offer alternatives for investors," the
SEC said in a press release announcing its request for comment.
</P>
<P>
	   The SEC would have to approve any linking of the stock exchanges and the
ECNs, some of which have asked the regulators to put them on the same legal
footing as the traditional exchanges.
</P>
<P>
	   The SEC said it has not determined at this time that it needs to take action
to respond to the sprouting of competing markets. The agency issued the concept
release because it wants "all views to be heard," Nazareth said.
</P>
<P>
	   SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt warned in a November speech that the nation's
stock markets will lose their competitive edge to overseas markets if investors
lose confidence in the ability to get their trades completed at the best prices,
commonly known as best execution.
</P>
<P>
	   "The stakes have never been greater for America's markets," Levitt told
securities industry executives. "We simply cannot afford to let our competitive
edge be dulled."
</P>
<P>
	   Specifically, he criticized the practice of payment for order flow, in which
brokerage firms are paid to route their trades through a particular market.
Levitt said the practice raises conflict-of-interest questions if the brokerage
firms are routing trades to make a profit rather than to get their customers the
best execution.
</P>
<P>
	   Roy Zuckerberg, chairman of the Securities Industry Association and advisory
director at brokerage firm Goldman Sachs Group, has rebuffed suggestions that
Wall Street has dragged its feet in responding to the competitive challenges
brought by new technology and ways of trading.
</P>
<P>
	   SIA spokesman Jim Spellman said Wednesday the group welcomed the SEC's
"effort to address these enormously complex market-structure issues."
</P>
<P>
	   Faced with the competition from ECNs, the New York Stock Exchange and the
electronic Nasdaq market are considering selling stock to the public to raise
money and give themselves greater operating flexibility, a move that would
transform them into for-profit businesses.
</P>
<P>
	   Also reshaping the markets are extended trading hours and an anticipated
switch this year to decimalization -- quoting stocks in dollars and cents,
rather than the 200-year-old tradition of fractions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0009 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
