<DOCNO> APW20000224.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thruway Authority kills plan to raise prices  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A possible toll hike for the New York Thruway has
been abandoned by state officials after heavy criticism from Gov. George Pataki
and state leaders.
<P>
	   The Thruway Authority's three-member board on Wednesday unanimously adopted
a resolution killing its Jan. 27 plan for toll hikes based on increases in a
20-city Construction Cost Index.
</P>
<P>
	   The first-year increase would have been 1.8 percent beginning June 1. The
Thruway's per-mile charge for passenger cars would have gone from 3.1 cents to
3.2 cents with the anticipated toll increase.
</P>
<P>
	   "Continuing to reduce taxes on New Yorkers is the right thing to do to
ensure our future prosperity, raising Thruway tolls is not," said state Senate
Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, a Rensselaer County Republican who had led the
fight against the toll hikes. "Fortunately, this plan has now been rejected."
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno, Pataki, Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver and state Comptroller H. Carl
McCoy had all come out against the toll hikes after the previously unannounced
plan became public. The authority board is appointed by the governor but he said
at the time that he had not been told about the toll-hike plans.
</P>
<P>
	   "A couple of weeks ago, I made it plain that we had not seen a toll hike in
my five and a half years as governor and I do not want to see a toll hike as we
go forward," Pataki said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   As with the Thruway Authority's original plan to raise tolls, word of its
abandoning the plan first came from Bruno. The authority later issued a
statement confirming that.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was an ill-conceived plan," Silver said. "I'm glad that the authority
has seen the light that we pointed out to them a couple of weeks ago."
</P>
<P>
	   Thruway officials had said they needed the extra money to pay for roadway
improvements over the next five years, from lane additions in some urban
stretches to things like a "flyover" at the Thruway's busiest exit, No. 24 in
Albany. The flyover would be a special link between the Thruway and Interstate
87 only for E-Z Pass users.
</P>
<P>
	   It was not immediately known how the Thruway Authority would now pay for
these projects, but Thruway Executive Director John Platt said "we look forward
to working with the governor and Legislature on solutions to these pressing
needs."
</P>
<P>
	   Tolls last increased on the Thruway, the nation's longest toll road, in 1988
by 31 percent. However, since 1994, Thruway Authority operating expenses have
increased by just 1 percent while the number of Thruway employees have been
reduced by 500, Platt said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-24-00 0011 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> An underground fire disrupts phone services in upstate New York  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - A fire in an old subway tunnel melted a section
of fiber-optic cable, disrupting long-distance, Internet and cellular telephone
services for thousands of Frontier Corp. customers in upstate New York.
<P>
	   The fire, apparently started by vagrants early Wednesday, cut off
long-distance service for 12 hours for most Frontier customers in and around
Rochester. Local telephone and 911 calls, which rely on copper wiring, were
unaffected.
</P>
<P>
	   Rochester's 9-mile-long subway, which ran underground for just 1 1/2 miles,
opened in 1927. Ridership peaked at 5 million in 1947, but the growing
popularity of automobiles and the demise of five connecting railroads led to the
last passenger run in 1956.
</P>
<P>
	   Vagrants trying to keep warm were suspected of starting a wood fire that
burned out of control in the disused subway line near the Genesee River, said
Frontier spokesman Tor Constantino. The intense heat managed to burn through the
fire-retardant tubing that encases the fiber-optic line, and about 150 feet of
it had to be replaced.
</P>
<P>
	   "A majority of residential and business customers" of Frontier's
long-distance service lost the ability to make outgoing calls, Constantino said,
adding that he was unable to estimate how many thousands of customers were
affected.
</P>
<P>
	   An unspecified number of Internet users also lost their connection - and
Frontier's reach as an Internet provider extends the breadth of upstate New
York.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, the outage disrupted cell phone service as far away as
Binghamton by knocking out incoming and outgoing calls for people served by Bell
Atlantic Mobile.
</P>
<P>
	   Frontier, a century-old telephone carrier with a nationwide long-distance
network, was bought out last year by Global Crossing Ltd., a Bermuda-based
telecommunications upstart. Founded in 1899, it changed its name from Rochester
Telephone in 1995.
</P>
<P>
	   Frontier sprouted beyond its roots as a local phone monopoly in Rochester -
a metro region of nearly 1 million people - by buying more than a half-dozen
long-distance carriers in the 1990s and becoming one of the nation's top 10
long-distance providers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-24-00 0012 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain surges in New York, but still has uphill battle  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A new poll says John McCain is in a dead heat among
Republicans with George W. Bush for New York's GOP-only primary, bringing up
questions of whether the state Republican party can actually deliver the state
for their favored candidate.
<P>
	   "New York is definitely in play for the Republicans," said pollster Lee
Miringoff, head of Marist College's Institute for Public Opinion.
</P>
<P>
	   The Marist poll had Bush favored by 43 percent of Republican voters to 41
percent for McCain. In December, the Texas governor led McCain, 59 percent to 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
	   While Bush retains the support of most of New York's top Republican leaders,
including New York Gov. George Pataki and state GOP Chairman William Powers,
there are those who say GOP leaders are getting nervous.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm not the only one with food-poisoning symptoms in New York state this
morning," said an under-the-weather Jay Severin, a New York-based GOP
consultant. "There's a train coming to New York and the Republican establishment
has only two choices, you can get on it or you get struck by it."
</P>
<P>
	   Even before Tuesday's Michigan and Arizona primaries, there had been signs
of trouble for Bush in New York. On Saturday, U.S. Rep. Peter King of Long
Island switched his allegiance from Bush to McCain. State Assemblymen Joel
Miller of Poughkeepsie and Philip Boyle of Long Island have also joined the
McCain camp in recent days.
</P>
<P>
	   Publicly, state GOP leaders professed little concern Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm not nervous," said state Assembly Minority Leader John Faso, a Bush
backer and Pataki political ally.
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, McCain has very real problems in New York as he prepares for the
state's "Super Tuesday" March 7 primary, where 93 delegates will be at stake.
There are primaries or caucuses that same day in more than a dozen other states,
including California. That can stretch resources thin.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, only previously registered Republicans can vote in New York's GOP
presidential primary, unlike the open primaries of New Hampshire and Michigan
where McCain was boosted by votes from Democrats and independents.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has only eight paid employees in New York and most of those aren't
political professionals.
</P>
<P>
	   "The other people here, while they may be involved in local politics, when
the campaign is over, one of them goes back to work at his engineering firm,
another guy goes back to work in a local government office, another guy goes
back to work doing this, that and the other thing," said Gerry O'Brien, McCain's
New York political director. "We don't have a tremendous number of people to
draw on from the professional side of things."
</P>
<P>
	   That's because Bush has almost the entire New York Republican Party
hierarchy, led by Pataki and Powers, working for him. The state party's
get-out-the-vote machinery is at the ready and most local Republican leaders are
in the Texas governor's corner.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'd say he's well supported by the people who are well supported by
Republicans in this state," said Ellen DiFrancisco, the Bush campaign's
executive director in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, while McCain was able to leave New York's GOP with a black eye by
successfully beating back an attempt to keep him off the primary ballot, the
ballot itself shows off a Bush advantage.
</P>
<P>
	   In New York, primary voters vote for the delegates, not the candidates. The
Bush delegate slates are peopled with the famous names of New York's GOP
establishment.
</P>
<P>
	   For example, one eastern New York congressional district, the Bush delegate
slate includes state Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, Lt. Gov. Mary Donohue
and U.S. Rep. John Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
	   "Republicans walk into a voting booth in a Republican primary, they will see
names they recognize and that they trust," Powers said.
</P>
<P>
	   Not so for McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   "To vote for John McCain, they're going to have to vote for these names, in
a lot of cases, people have never heard of," said state Assemblyman Thomas
Kirwan of Newburgh, one of the few elected Republicans for McCain. "Unless they
know what the deal is, they're going to go in and vote and they're going to vote
for the names they're familiar with."
</P>
<P>
	   To counter that, the McCain camp has launched a voter education effort
utilizing news conferences, phone calls and mailings.
</P>
<P>
	   The stakes for Pataki are high.
</P>
<P>
	   "Governor Pataki has pledged an all out effort to win New York for Governor
Bush and everyone's going to be working on the campaign, from the delegates on
up," DiFrancisco said.
</P>
<P>
	   But Powers admitted some concern.
</P>
<P>
	   "You always have to be worried," he said. "But again, if you look at it, the
entire Republican organization is there, a lot of Republican officials are there
and a lot of them are (prospective) delegates. They'll all want to be out
working in their districts to make sure that they win."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-24-00 0012 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polls: Bush and McCain competitive in New York  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Two statewide polls show Sen. John McCain poised to
give Texas Gov. George W. Bush a tough test in New York's March 7 presidential
primary.
<P>
	   A CBS News/New York Times poll out today has Bush leading McCain, 43 percent
to 36 percent, with Alan Keyes at 4 percent among enrolled Republican voters.
</P>
<P>
	   Another poll, out Wednesday from Marist College's Institute for Public
Opinion, found Bush supported by 43 percent of Republican voters in New York
with McCain backed by 41 percent, a statistical tie given the poll's margin of
error. Keyes trailed at 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Among those Republicans considered likely to vote in the state's primary, 46
percent said they backed Bush while 43 percent said they favored McCain, also a
statistical tie in the Marist poll. One percent said they backed Keyes while 9
percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
	   A Feb. 8 Marist poll found Bush leading McCain, 46 percent to 35 percent,
among registered Republicans and, 48 percent to 39 percent, among likely GOP
primary voters. A December poll from Marist had Bush leading McCain, 59 percent
to 15 percent among New York Republicans.
</P>
<P>
	   The CBS News/New York Times poll found Al Gore leading Bill Bradley, 59
percent to 28 percent, among Democratic voters in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   The polling news, plus McCain's primary wins Tuesday in Michigan and
Arizona, means "invincibility has been shattered, electability is now on the
table" on the Republican side, according to Marist pollster Lee Mirningoff.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's popularity among New York Republicans has been on the rise since
his strong primary victory over Bush in New Hampshire. That came in the wake of
his highly publicized and successful battle to get on the New York primary
ballot despite the efforts of Bush's New York backers, including Gov. George
Pataki and state GOP Chairman William Powers, to keep the senator from Arizona
off the ballot.
</P>
<P>
	   Marist College's latest telephone survey of 363 registered Republicans was
conducted Sunday through Tuesday of this week and has a margin of error of plus
or minus 5 percentage points. The margin of error for the sample of 201 likely
GOP voters is plus or minus 7 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
	   The CBS News/New York Times telephone poll was conducted Feb. 16-22. The
sample of 374 Republicans carries with it a margin of error of plus or minus 5
percentage points. The margin of error for the sample of 542 Democrats was plus
or minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-24-00 0012 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> An underground fire disrupts phone services in upstate New York  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - A fire in an old subway tunnel melted a section
