<DOCNO> APW20000224.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thruway Authority kills plan to raise prices  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A possible toll hike for the New York Thruway has
been abandoned by state officials after heavy criticism from Gov. George Pataki
and state leaders.
<P>
	   The Thruway Authority's three-member board on Wednesday unanimously adopted
a resolution killing its Jan. 27 plan for toll hikes based on increases in a
20-city Construction Cost Index.
</P>
<P>
	   The first-year increase would have been 1.8 percent beginning June 1. The
Thruway's per-mile charge for passenger cars would have gone from 3.1 cents to
3.2 cents with the anticipated toll increase.
</P>
<P>
	   "Continuing to reduce taxes on New Yorkers is the right thing to do to
ensure our future prosperity, raising Thruway tolls is not," said state Senate
Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, a Rensselaer County Republican who had led the
fight against the toll hikes. "Fortunately, this plan has now been rejected."
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno, Pataki, Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver and state Comptroller H. Carl
McCoy had all come out against the toll hikes after the previously unannounced
plan became public. The authority board is appointed by the governor but he said
at the time that he had not been told about the toll-hike plans.
</P>
<P>
	   "A couple of weeks ago, I made it plain that we had not seen a toll hike in
my five and a half years as governor and I do not want to see a toll hike as we
go forward," Pataki said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   As with the Thruway Authority's original plan to raise tolls, word of its
abandoning the plan first came from Bruno. The authority later issued a
statement confirming that.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was an ill-conceived plan," Silver said. "I'm glad that the authority
has seen the light that we pointed out to them a couple of weeks ago."
</P>
<P>
	   Thruway officials had said they needed the extra money to pay for roadway
improvements over the next five years, from lane additions in some urban
stretches to things like a "flyover" at the Thruway's busiest exit, No. 24 in
Albany. The flyover would be a special link between the Thruway and Interstate
87 only for E-Z Pass users.
</P>
<P>
	   It was not immediately known how the Thruway Authority would now pay for
these projects, but Thruway Executive Director John Platt said "we look forward
to working with the governor and Legislature on solutions to these pressing
needs."
</P>
<P>
	   Tolls last increased on the Thruway, the nation's longest toll road, in 1988
by 31 percent. However, since 1994, Thruway Authority operating expenses have
increased by just 1 percent while the number of Thruway employees have been
reduced by 500, Platt said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-24-00 0013 </TRAILER>
