<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tonya Harding Arrested for Assault  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAMAS, Wash. (AP) -- Former Olympic ice skater Tonya Harding was arrested
after being accused of throwing a hubcap at her live-in boyfriend and repeatedly
punching him in the face.
</P>
<P>
	Harding, 29, was ordered to appear Thursday in Camas Municipal Court.
</P>
<P>
	She was booked Tuesday night for investigation of fourth-degree domestic
violence assault after an altercation that left Darren Silver's face bruised and
bloodied, Camas police said. She was released an hour later.
</P>
<P>
	Police said Harding and Silver, 28, have lived together for about three years.
</P>
<P>
	According to police, Harding and Silver, both of whom appeared intoxicated,
began fighting Tuesday night in a barn they use as a garage behind their house.
Two men inside the barn told officers Harding threw a hubcap at Silver, hitting
him in the face, then began pummeling him with punches.
</P>
<P>
	Police said Harding told officers Silver had held her on the ground and she hit
him to protect herself, a statement police said witness accounts did not back
up.
</P>
<P>
	In a recording of the 911 call released Wednesday by police, a male voice says:
``I want to find out the rules, if we'd both go to jail or not, because my
girlfriend is beating the ... out of me.''
</P>
<P>
	Later, a female voice says: ``I punched him in the face because he came after
me, he put me to the ground.'' In the background, a male voice can be heard
yelling: ``I did not! You are a liar! You are a liar! You are a felon and I have
nothing to hide!''
</P>
<P>
	Harding, who teaches figure skating at a Portland, Ore., mall, was arrested and
ordered to stay away from Silver.
</P>
<P>
	Harding gained national attention in 1994 when she pleaded guilty to covering
up for her former husband and his friends, who hatched a plot to injure
Harding's chief rival, skater Nancy Kerrigan, as Kerrigan practiced for the
national figure skating championship. Harding won the championship and later
competed at the 1994 Lillehammer Olympic games.
</P>
<P>
	Harding was banned from amateur skating for life later that year because of her
role in the attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
