<HEADLINE> Patients May Have Been Exposed  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID HO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Georgetown University Medical Center is trying to contact
nearly 300 former patients to warn them they might have been exposed to HIV and
other infectious diseases by a medical technician accused of siphoning
painkillers with potentially contaminated needles.
</P>
<P>
	   The patients are being advised to seek testing for HIV and other diseases as
a precaution, said hospital spokesman Paul Donovan.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Even though the risk is extremely low we want to take the appropriate
precautions for our patients,'' Donovan said. ``We cannot confirm that anyone
was or was not exposed to infection.''
</P>
<P>
	   The technician, Jeffrey Royal, was caught Feb. 2 siphoning the powerful
synthetic painkiller fentanyl from a patient's intravenous line with a syringe.
He was immediately fired and arrested, Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
	   Royal, 40, was arraigned Tuesday in federal court on a charge of tampering
with consumer products, a felony that carries a maximum sentence of 10 years in
prison and a $250,000 fine, The Washington Post reported in its Thursday
editions.
</P>
<P>
	   The medical center has been working with District of Columbia health
officials and the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta to
notify the patients who may have been exposed.
</P>
<P>
	   The medical center started informing the physicians of the potentially
exposed patients last week and began sending letters to the 294 patients on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Georgetown is offering patients free testing for a full range of infectious
diseases as well free counseling. Patients can call a 24-hour hotline at
1-202-784-0015.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
