<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Superior Court Judge on hot seat for reappointment  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - A Legislative committee is expected to decide
Friday whether to recommend the reappointment a Superior Court judge who has
come under harsh criticism for his handling of a 1995 murder trial.
<P>
	   Judge David Fineberg presided over the trial of John Tyler Fuessenich, when
he was found innocent of murder despite admitting to killing James Irwin Jr. and
dumping his body off a back road in Morris. Fuessenich, who said the killing was
in self-defense, was tried twice on the murder charge. The first trial ended in
1992 with a deadlocked jury.
</P>
<P>
	   Fineberg's critics say the judge displayed a dislike for the prosecutor, Guy
Wolfe III, and the victim's family. They said his demeanor tainted the jury, and
they blasted the judge for setting up a rope in the courtroom that separated the
family from Wolf.
</P>
<P>
	   Irwin's mother, Rosaria Irwin, told members of the Judiciary Committee on
Wednesday that she was ordered by Fineberg not to cry during the trial. Her
daughter, Kathleen O'Toole, said Fineberg did not allow her to sit in the
courtroom during testimony.
</P>
<P>
	   Irwin and O'Toole said Fineberg threatened to dismiss the case if family
members spoke to the media during the trial.
</P>
<P>
	   "Throughout the trial, Judge Fineberg displayed overt hostility toward
myself, my family and the prosecutor," Irwin said. "I feel that the people of
the state of Connecticut need to be protected from individuals such as Judge
Fineberg. In my eyes, the way in which he conducts his trials, exhibiting total
disregard for the law, makes him no different than the people he tried."
</P>
<P>
	   If the Judiciary Committee decides to recommend Fineberg for reappointment
to a second 2-year term the appointment would then go on to a vote before the
entire General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
	   Fineberg presided over the Fuessenich case as a Litchfield Superior Court
judge. He currently sits in Hartford Superior Court and hears civil cases.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1996, he was admonished by the state Judicial Review Council for
threatening Wolfe with contempt of court in front of a jury.
</P>
<P>
	   The Council concluded Fineberg's comment was "an unfavorable judicial
practice."
</P>
<P>
	   Such an admonishment is the least serious action the Council can take
against a judge. State law permits admonishment when there is no legal basis for
removal, suspension, or censure.
</P>
<P>
	   "I made a mistake which I regret, and I assure all of you it will not happen
again," Fineberg said about his threats to Wolfe.
</P>
<P>
	   Fineberg said he wanted the victim's mother and sister out of the courtroom
because they were potential witnesses. He said they may have heard testimony
that would have influenced their own. They were never called to testify, and
Irwin's mother was allowed to observe the entire trial.
</P>
<P>
	   Fineberg explained he had the rope strung up to keep a sense of calm in his
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
	   "I thought I was doing right, but it probably left the wrong message with
the family," Fineberg said. "I regret doing it, and I apologize for doing it."
</P>
<P>
	   Attorney Glenn Coe, who investigated Fineberg's handling of the Fuessenich
trial for the state Judge's Association, said the judge never threatened to
dismiss the case if family members spoke to the press.
</P>
<P>
	   "What I did read in the transcripts was vigorous advocacy by experienced
counsel, a judge open to considering and reconsidering the arguments of counsel,
a judge who carefully read cases ... and a judge who treated the attorneys with
courtesy and respect," Coe said.
</P>
<P>
	   If Fineberg is not reappointed, the 68-year-old judge will lose his $106,558
annual salary and the $70,000-a-year state pension he would start receiving in
two years. Judges are required by law to retire at age 70.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-24-00 0103 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AG report critical of Anderson handling of state loans, lover  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - A Hartford business and civic leader was "dumb
and derelict" in handling state loans for a woman who claimed she was his sex
slave, according to a state investigation.
<P>
	   Attorney General Richard Blumenthal said Wednesday that Arthur Anderson
should reimburse the $200,000 in insurance claims that he funneled to his
mistress, Doris Ford, instead of the state.
</P>
<P>
	   In the late 1980s, Ford borrowed more than $600,000 to buy and renovate four
apartment buildings. The money was loaned through the Capitol Housing Finance
Corp., a creation of the Hartford business community to finance rehabilitation
of low-income housing in the city.
</P>
<P>
	   Anderson's company, Imagineers, was hired by CHFC to administer the loan
program. Anderson resigned last August from his position as the program's
state-appointed chief.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1993 and 1994, two of Ford's four buildings were destroyed by fire,
resulting in more than $200,000 in insurance payoffs. Blumenthal said Anderson
let Ford keep that cash instead of making sure it went to the state and the
CHFC.
</P>
<P>
	   Blumenthal said Ford was continually in default on her CHFC loans.
</P>
<P>
	   Anderson also gave Ford more than $500,000 of his own money between 1994 and
1998 to keep her quiet about their sexual relationship, Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
	   "By his own admission, he was dumb and derelict in his duties," Blumenthal
said. "He failed to protect the state's interests. He was legally responsible
and should be held accountable."
</P>
<P>
	   Blumenthal said Anderson should repay the insurance money and also pay for
the cost of the state's investigation, which began in December 1998 after The
Hartford Courant exposed Anderson's relationship with Ford.
</P>
<P>
	   Ford has sued Anderson in federal court, asking that he be ordered to make
lifetime payments to her because he forced her to be his sex slave and promised
to support her.
</P>
<P>
	   "Anderson allowed a clandestine relationship to interfere with his moral and
legal responsibility to protect state funds," Blumenthal said. "The favoritism
and irregularities were serious and significant, and caused substantial
financial losses to the state."
</P>
<P>
	   Anderson maintains his relationship with Ford did not influence his
decisions. His lawyer, John Droney, said he and Anderson are negotiating a
settlement with the state but have not agreed on a dollar amount.
</P>
<P>
	   "Aside from my unfortunate personal involvement with Doris Ford, I did not
act unethically," Anderson said. "I will accept responsibility for decisions
fairly attributed to me. If I made a mistake that caused financial loss, it was
not because I improperly assisted Doris Ford or anyone else."
</P>
<P>
	   Blumenthal sent a copy of his findings to Chief State's Attorney John
Bailey, but did not recommend that any specific criminal charges be filed
against Anderson.
</P>
<P>
	   Bailey said he will review the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-24-00 0104 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
