<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blues 4, Sharks 1  </HEADLINE>
    By DENNIS GEORGATOS AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Winning away from home is becoming a St. Louis
Blues' trademark.
</P>
<P>
	   Stephane Richer and Chris Pronger each scored goals in the second period as
the Blues broke a tie to beat the San Jose Sharks 4-1 Wednesday night for their
team-record ninth straight victory on the road.
</P>
<P>
	   The streak is one shy of the Buffalo Sabres' NHL record set in 1983-84 and
three better than the Blues' previous club record, achieved just a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Scott Young added an empty-net score after the Sharks pulled their
goaltender in the final minute. Michal Handzus also had a first-period goal for
St. Louis, which improved its overall road record to 21-8-2, best in the league.
Pavol Demitra assisted on two of the goals.
</P>
<P>
	   The Sharks, clinging to the last playoff spot in the Western Conference, had
hoped for a better start to a franchise record-tying nine-game homestand. They
have now lost nine of their last 12 in San Jose and failed to beat the Blues in
five meetings this season, going 0-4-1.
</P>
<P>
	   San Jose also lost defenseman Gary Suter, who left after straining a knee
midway through the second period. Linesman Wayne Bonney also left the game late
in the second period after being struck by a slap shot in the rib cage area.
</P>
<P>
	   Goaltender Roman Turek, who has been in the net for the nine straight road
victories, had 23 saves for his career-high 32nd win of the year.
</P>
<P>
	   San Jose's lone score came on Jeff Friesen's power-play goal at 15:10 of the
second period, tying it at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
	   Turek fended off the Sharks with two key saves in the third, stopping a slap
shot with his glove and dropping to his knees and using his pads to block
another from up close. It was the eighth straight game in which the Blues
haven't allowed a third-period goal.
</P>
<P>
	   Richer scored the go-ahead goal for St. Louis at 6:21 of the second, beating
goaltender Steve Shields on a wraparound after getting a pass from Marty
Reasoner.
</P>
<P>
	   The Blues added their third goal at the end of a 2-on-1 break.
</P>
<P>
	   The streaking Demitra drew the defender to him before passing off to
Pronger, who sent a slap shot up and over Shields' shoulder and into the net.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0106 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defense rests in Louima conspiracy case after biting  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Defense attorneys have rested their case after principal
defendant Charles Schwarz weathered a biting cross-examination on allegations he
took part in the sexual assault on Abner Louima and conspired with others to
cover it up.
<P>
	   Assistant U.S. Attorney Alan Vinegrad pounded the 34-year-old former cop
with questions about the arrest of Louima in a 1997 street riot and what
happened later at Brooklyn's 70th Precinct, where another officer sodomized the
Haitian immigrant with a broken broom handle.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz - accused with two other officers of conspiring to obstruct justice
by concealing his role in the lavatory assault of Louima by fellow officer
Justin Volpe - insisted under Vinegrad's sarcastic, hostile grilling that he was
"never in that bathroom."
</P>
<P>
	   He also denied that scores of phone calls involving him and fellow
defendants Thomas Wiese, 34, and Thomas Bruder, 37, in the days and weeks
following the brutal incident had anything to do with rigging an alibi.
</P>
<P>
	   Defense attorney Ronald Fischetti rested his case after Schwarz stepped down
from four hours on the stand. U.S. District Judge Eugene Nickerson indicated the
case would go to the jury next week.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz, 34, was convicted last year of violating Louima's civil rights by
holding him down during the attack, and faces a possible life sentence. Volpe,
who pleaded guilty in that trial, is serving 30 years.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz said earlier that at the time the assault occurred, he was outside
the 70th Precinct conducting a routine post-arrest search of his patrol car for
items possibly concealed by a prisoner.
</P>
<P>
	   Vinegrad hammered at Schwarz over the phone calls, some of them lasting
hours, which the government has presented as evidence that the three officers
plotted feverishly to concoct a cover story for Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
	   The former cop insisted that while they discussed press coverage and
speculated on where the investigation might be heading, they were not trying to
conjure up an alibi for him. He said he could not recall many details of
conversations from years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier in the day, Schwarz told the Brooklyn federal court jury he would
not expect other cops to lie to protect him, particularly Wiese, his former
patrol partner.
</P>
<P>
	   "I would never do something like that - to ask a man with two children to
put himself in harm's way for me," Schwarz said.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz contended it was relatively rare for police officers to cover up
each other's misdeeds - forming what is often called the "blue wall of silence."
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm not saying it doesn't exist ... but my feeling is that if there's real
criminal misconduct, most cops will not like something like that," he said. "If
you mean is it rampant, I'd say no."
</P>
<P>
	   "And no one has ever done that for you?" asked Vinegrad.
</P>
<P>
	   "No, sir," Schwarz replied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-24-00 0106 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flutie: 'We Would Have Won'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TORONTO (AP) -- Doug Flutie is sure there would have been no Music City
Miracle if he had started the Buffalo Bills' wild-card playoff game against the
Tennessee Titans.
</P>
<P>
	   Flutie remains bitter about the circumstances surrounding his demotion in
favor of Rob Johnson in the Jan. 8 game, and the quarterback let his feelings be
known in an interview with a Canadian television network.
</P>
<P>
	   "I honestly believe that if I would have been playing, we could have, would
have, won," Flutie said in an interview to be aired Saturday night on TSN. "It
probably was the most frustrating, most miserable week I've ever spent in
football. It was hard to understand and difficult to deal with."
</P>
<P>
	   The Titans won 22-16 in the final seconds on a trick play on a kickoff
return.
</P>
<P>
	   Flutie said that in meetings with NFL players since the season ended,
response has been "unanimous that I got shafted."
</P>
<P>
	   "I sort of shook my head and chuckled," Flutie said of his reaction when
Bills coach Wade Phillips told him five days before the game that Johnson would
be starting.
</P>
<P>
	   "I should have known better. I should have expected it. I've been through it
before. Just when you start to feel comfortable and trust people in this
league..."
</P>
<P>
	   As for the recent release of a trio of Bills stars -- Bruce Smith, Thurman
Thomas and Andre Reed -- Flutie called it "a joke."
</P>
<P>
	   "I shake my head, I really do," Flutie said. "They were all necessary in the
eyes of our management, but it's no longer about who the best player is for the
job in terms of personnel. It's not about putting the best product on the
field."
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the pain of being demoted at a crucial time, Flutie said he did want
to ask for a trade.
</P>
<P>
	   "I was frustrated and angry and I thought about trying to force their hands,
but it made no sense," he said. "I know the offense, I know the players. I'm 37.
I don't feel like going anywhere else. I'll get my opportunity."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0106 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alleged ecstasy drug network smashed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - A lengthy investigation by a host of agencies has led to
the dismantling of a multi-million dollar network that smuggled the popular
"club drug" ecstasy into New York and several other states, authorities said.
<P>
	   A total of 61 people were under arrest or being sought, all allegedly part
of an international ring that conducted business in New York, California,
Florida, Massachusetts, Ohio, Pennsylvania and Rhode Island. Authorities said
Wednesday they believe the drugs were smuggled into the United States by six
Israeli nationals.
</P>
<P>
	   The ring, operating out of an apartment in the Forest Hills section of
Queens, allegedly poured 100,000 ecstasy tablets a week into the New York
metropolitan region from the Netherlands and Belgium, said Queens District
Attorney Richard A. Brown. Authorities have seized 300,000 tablets worth an
estimated $7.5 million, and $550,000 in cash, he added.
</P>
<P>
	   "With these arrests we hope to drive home the message that, despite its
name, this drug is a nightmare for users and dealers alike," Brown said.
</P>
<P>
	   Ecstasy is a hybrid of the hallucinogen mescaline and the stimulant
amphetamine chemically known as MDMA. It has been shown in previous studies to
cause brain damage in animals at doses similar to those used by humans.
</P>
<P>
	   The drug, also known as XTC or X, has become the most popular of the
so-called club drugs, said Donnie R. Marshall, acting administrator of the Drug
Enforcement Administration.
</P>
<P>
	   "This case demonstrates that the Netherlands and Belgium have become the
main location for manufacturing and exporting MDMA," Marshall said. "To add to
the globalization of this problem, Israeli and Russian organized crime
syndicates have gained control of the smuggling of MDMA from Europe into the
U.S."
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities began focusing in on the ring after two undercover investigators
learned that an Israeli national living in Forest Hills - identified as Oshri
Amar - was allegedly selling large quantities of ecstasy. Undercover agents
purchased tablets from Amar, and then received court authorization to install
wiretaps on Amar's telephone and other telephones controlled by his alleged
associates, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
	   Over several months, Amar and his associates allegedly engaged in hundreds
of wholesale transactions in several states. They allegedly paid between $1 and
$2 per tablet, and then charged $6 to $8 per pill, Brown said. The tablets
usually sell for $20 to $30 apiece at clubs, he added.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the 61 defendants, 32 were either arrested Wednesday or were being sought
in New York, Pennsylvania and Florida. Amar was one of the defendants being
sought, officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Five defendants were previously arrested. In addition, 24 people were either
arrested or were being sought in the Providence, R.I., area.
</P>
<P>
	   All the defendants were charged with conspiracy to sell and distribute a
controlled substance, and various counts of criminal possession and/or sale of a
controlled substance. Each faces up to 25 years to life in prison if convicted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-24-00 0107 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
