<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Plane's Wheel Gets Stuck  </HEADLINE>
   By LAURIE KELLMAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BREMERTON, Wash. (AP) -- Sen. John McCain's campaign was delayed Wednesday
night after his plane got stuck in the mud for about two hours as it prepared to
fly to Sacramento, Calif.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain and his wife, Cindy, napped part of the time while waiting on board.
Nobody was hurt.
</P>
<P>
	   The pilot of the 727 had been taxing for takeoff and apparently cut short a
left turn, dragging the plane's left rear wheels through a muddy, grassy island
in the runway. The wheels came to rest next to a landing light, a quarter of
their height buried in mud.
</P>
<P>
	   Workers dug out the landing light and put down wooden planks to help the
plane escape.
</P>
<P>
	   After two hours the passengers were asked to leave to lighten the load so
the pilot could fire up the engines and push the plane out of the mud.
</P>
<P>
	   The passengers waited in three buses, and at 9:40 p.m. PST a cheer went up
as the plane roared free of its muddy captivity.
</P>
<P>
	   If the landing gear checked out as undamaged, the plan was for the plane to
fly on to Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain made appearances Wednesday in Spokane, Seattle and Bremerton, a Navy
town about 15 miles west of Seattle on Puget Sound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0108 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Human Remains Found in Andes  </HEADLINE>
   By MIGUEL GIL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRES QUEBRADAS, Argentina (AP) -- Tattered scraps of clothes and a severed
hand eerily mummified by the cold. Human bones and the engine of a British plane
that vanished long ago in a snowstorm in the Andes mountains.
</P>
<P>
	   These are the clues to a story that couldn't be told for more than half a
century -- until now. Two Argentine mountaineers have discovered the 1947 crash
site of a British plane, and a 17-member army expedition has wrapped up an
investigation of the accident.
</P>
<P>
	   For years, the question of what happened to the British Avro Lancastrian was
one of the great aviation mysteries of these perilous peaks so high they are
shrouded in snow and freezing temperatures all year round.
</P>
<P>
	   Operated by the now defunct British South American Airways, the plane was
carrying 11 people -- five crew members and six passengers -- and was headed to
Santiago, Chile, when it disappeared on Aug. 2, 1947. The passengers included
three Britons, a German, a Palestinian and a Swiss.
</P>
<P>
	   In January, two mountaineers climbing the 21,848-foot Tupungato volcano
stumbled upon the site.
</P>
<P>
	   Interviewed earlier this week by the newspaper Clarin, Pablo Reguera and
Fernando Garmendia said they never imagined they would find a Rolls Royce engine
more than 16,000 feet up the rocky slopes -- as if dumped casually on a junk
heap in the sky.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Look at the engine over there,'' Reguera remembers calling out to his
climbing buddy, who took a snapshot of him posing with his ice pick beside the
dented find. As he recounted for Clarin, the two tried to make light of the
disturbing discovery, joking with each other: ``How could anyone have gotten a
car up here?''
</P>
<P>
	   But it clearly was a plane engine, and all around lay the remnants of
disaster: shredded bits and pieces of wings and fuselage, frayed cables and a
portion of a seat with what looked like a parachute attached.
</P>
<P>
	   They also saw the human remains and torn clothing. After completing their
climb, they called the authorities.
</P>
<P>
	   A federal judge, upon hearing the news, ordered the military expedition.
</P>
<P>
	   Four-wheel drive vehicles, mules and mountaineers who could map a tortuous
route up the volcano's rocky slopes were called in. The air force took advantage
of fair weather in the southern hemisphere summer and sent helicopters to the
site.
</P>
<P>
	   After days of work, Army Lt. Col. Ricardo Bustos announced Wednesday that
the army team was concluding its operation and bringing down torsos, bones and
other remains of at least three of the victims.
</P>
<P>
	   Bustos did not identify the victims except to say that the remains from one
woman were found at the site. Busto said the group also had recovered pieces of
the engine, landing gear and parts of the cabin from the debris-strewn slope
16,500 feet up the volcano.
</P>
<P>
	   The group spent several days investigating the site, reachable only by a
difficult climb. One member of the army expedition had to be flown out by
helicopter after suffering breathing problems in the nearly oxygen-bereft
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
	   For years, during the early pioneering days of aviation, the Andes mountain
range was a virtual graveyard for planes.
</P>
<P>
	   The last message from the plane has puzzled aviation investigators for
years. Radio operators in Chile reportedly received a Morse code message reading
``STENDEC'' -- an acronym investigators say has no meaning.
</P>
<P>
	   Following the crash, search teams from England, Chile and Argentina combed
the area by air and on skis but found nothing.
</P>
<P>
	   Theories abounded about the plane's disappearance. Some speculated it had
been sabotaged to kill a British diplomatic messenger reportedly on board.
</P>
<P>
	   But severe weather was believed by many to have been the cause. Records
indicate heavy snow fell for three days when the plane vanished over the South
American mountain chain, and aviation experts said the plane -- a converted
World War II bomber -- did not have deicing capabilities and was unfit to travel
through winter conditions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
