<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conflicting Emotions on Austria  </HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT H. REID Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- The furor over a far-right party in Austria's ruling
coalition has stirred conflicting emotions in Eastern Europe, whose governments
want to join the European Union but are also protective of their own sovereignty
after decades of Soviet domination.
</P>
<P>
	   Adding to the mix is the presence of influential right-wing -- even
far-right -- parties in EU candidate countries such as Slovakia, Hungary and
Romania, whose views on some issues are not dissimilar to those of Joerg
Haider's Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
	   Some prominent Eastern European politicians, including former Polish
president Lech Walesa, have questioned whether the EU displayed a
double-standard in targeting Austria while at the same time treating former
Communists as members of the European family.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am glad Europe is cautious,'' Walesa told a radio station in Gdansk,
Poland, after the 14 other EU members decided to downgrade official contacts
with Austria when the new coalition took power Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
	   But Walesa added: ``We have people here whose links with communism,
communist Poland and its crimes, are much closer and Europe is not protesting.''
</P>
<P>
	   The EU diplomatic measures were imposed because of Haider's opposition to
immigration and past statements sympathetic to aspects of the Nazi regime of
Adolf Hitler.
</P>
<P>
	   Influential figures in Eastern Europe are also concerned about the EU having
imposed collective punishment on a member state because of the choice its people
made in a democratic election.
</P>
<P>
	   In the Oct. 3 balloting, Haider's party finished second with 52 of the 183
parliamentary seats. When coalition talks with the top-finishing Social
Democrats broke down, People's Party leader Wolfgang Schuessel struck a deal
with Haider.
</P>
<P>
	   To conservatives and nationalists in Eastern Europe, the EU move is
reminiscent of the Soviet doctrine that held that Moscow's allies did not have
the right to choose their own political path if it might undermine the rest of
the Soviet Bloc.
</P>
<P>
	   Although the difference between Soviet invasion and EU diplomatic sanctions
is enormous, the comparison is close enough to cause unease among conservative
politicians with fresh and painful memories of Communist oppression.
</P>
<P>
	   Czech parliament speaker Vaclav Klaus said that although he is concerned
about delays in EU membership, ``I have to respect the will of the Austrian
voters, and I cannot accept what is happening in Europe today.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is very interesting that nobody is protesting the participation of
communists in the government of France and nobody is protesting the fact that
the Italian prime minister (Massimo d'Alema) is a former communist,'' Klaus
said. ``For me, it's just another example of the immense asymmetry which exists
in today's Europe.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Freedom Party's inclusion in the Austrian government, along with the
centrist Austrian People's Party, also set off alarm bells in Eastern Europe --
not so much because of alleged Nazi sympathies as because of Haider's longtime
opposition to bringing the former communist countries into the EU.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the Austrian coalition's official commitment to expansion, Haider
has said the entry of new members should be delayed until the gap between wages
in Eastern Europe and in the EU has been significantly narrowed.
</P>
<P>
	   Otherwise, he argues, European companies will pack up and head eastward,
depriving Austrians and other Western Europeans of their jobs.
</P>
<P>
	   Governments in Slovenia, Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic -- the
leading EU candidates -- have all spoken out against any delays in EU expansion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0119 </TRAILER>
