<DOCNO> APW20000224.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerians Flee Smoldering City  </HEADLINE>
   By GILBERT DA COSTA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KADUNA, Nigeria (AP) -- An overwhelming stench filled the morgue at this
smoldering city's main hospital, where about 200 bodies were piled up on slabs,
on the floor, even the ground outside after two days of religious clashes.
</P>
<P>
	   More bodies -- many of them charred -- littered the streets, where smoke
wafted Wednesday from burned buildings and the remnants of bonfires built during
the rioting.
</P>
<P>
	   Hundreds grabbed what belongings they could and set off on foot to escape
the scene of the fighting, which erupted Monday morning during a demonstration
by local Christians against a proposal to bring Islamic law, or sharia, to
Kaduna state.
</P>
<P>
	   Guns, cutlasses and other weapons were used in the clashes, which continued
into Tuesday, said workers sifting through the bodies at the morgue.
</P>
<P>
	   ``People, especially the Christians in my area, were slaughtered like
chickens and goats,'' said Nkechi Nwosu, a Christian, who sought refuge with her
15-year-old son at the Army Referral Hospital. ``I haven't seen anything like
this in the 10 years I have lived in the city.''
</P>
<P>
	   Police played down the death toll and maintained that just 13 bodies had
been recovered.
</P>
<P>
	   There were no reports of fighting Wednesday, but looting continued in some
neighborhoods despite a curfew that kept all residents inside except between 8
a.m. and noon.
</P>
<P>
	   While most stores were closed, residents who decided to stay in the city
raced to those that were open, stocking up on supplies before the curfew went
back into affect. Others gathered at police and military facilities for
protection.
</P>
<P>
	   Hundreds of thousands of people live in Kaduna, one of the largest cities in
northern Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
	   Police reinforcements were brought in from five neighboring states, and
soldiers also fanned out through the city to contain the violence.
</P>
<P>
	   Sharia has become an increasingly divisive issue in Nigeria, a nation of 120
million sharply divided along ethnic, religious and geographic lines -- and
where those divisions regularly flare into bloody battles.
</P>
<P>
	   Last month, sharia officially went into affect in neighboring Zamfara state,
which is overwhelmingly Muslim. Niger state, south of Kaduna, and Sokoto state
to the northwest passed their own sharia bills on Tuesday and Wednesday
respectively.
</P>
<P>
	   A number of other states in Nigeria's largely Muslim north -- including
Kaduna, which is about 40 percent Christian -- are also considering following
suit.
</P>
<P>
	   Sharia supporters across the North have assured non-Muslims they will not be
tried under the Islamic law.
</P>
<P>
	   But such assurances have meant little to Christians, who fear becoming
marginalized or discriminated against. Their fears are fed by the country's
newspapers in the largely Christian south, which have filled pages with dire
warnings of the punishments Christians will face.
</P>
<P>
	   Muslim law prohibits such things as drinking alcohol and also calls for
separate schools and public transportation for men and women. Islamic courts
have been established to hold trials and mete out punishment to Muslims.
</P>
<P>
	   Recently, one man was lashed 80 times in Zamfara state for drinking alcohol.
</P>
<P>
	   An emergency debate in Parliament's lower house degenerated into a shouting
match Wednesday, as Christians and Muslims argued over the constitutionality of
sharia and sought to blame each other for the clashes in Kaduna.
</P>
<P>
	   The House of Representatives finally passed a motion condemning the fighting
and supporting the deployment of soldiers to contain the violence. A hastily
added amendment asked the justice minister to refer the question of sharia to
the Supreme Court for interpretation.
</P>
<P>
	   Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo, elected a year ago after 15 years of
military rule, has remained largely silent on the issue, apparently afraid of
sparking an even larger crisis.
</P>
<P>
	   On Wednesday, his only comment was to condemn the violence as ``not only
criminal but highly unpatriotic.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``What we need most now is love, caring for each other and joining of hands
to rebuild the nation together,'' Obasanjo said in an address on national
television. ``Let us bind our wounds and accept the challenge of the time.''
</P>
<P>
	   Also Wednesday, a prominent Nigerian lawyer and human rights activist filed
a suit asking the Zamfara state high court in Gusau to declare sharia
unconstitutional. No date has been set for the suit, filed by Olisa Agbakoba on
behalf of the Human Rights Law Services group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0123 </TRAILER>
