<HEADLINE> Strong Winds, Rain Pound Calif.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A storm packing tornado-like bursts of wind and driving
rain damaged buildings, snarled highways and was blamed for two fatal traffic
crashes in southern California on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The wind bursts, which authorities compared to the power of tornados, peeled
the roofs off two buildings and uprooted a 65-foot pine tree in Los Angeles,
said Fire Department spokesman Brian Humphrey.
</P>
<P>
	   The California Highway Patrol said there were more than 570 accidents.
</P>
<P>
	   The storm dumped 1.43 inches of rain on Burbank and left up to 8 inches of
fresh snow in Big Bear, which was bracing for an early weekend influx of skiers.
</P>
<P>
	   At the beach near Topanga Canyon north of Los Angeles, lifeguards rescued
two wind surfers from the choppy waters of the Pacific Ocean, while an afternoon
mudslide blocked one lane of Interstate 405 between the San Fernando Valley and
the city's west side.
</P>
<P>
	   Snow that began falling at higher elevations Wednesday night also led to the
closure of Interstate 5, a major link connecting Los Angeles to San Francisco.
The highway was closed in both directions over the mountainous Grapevine pass,
the state Department of Transportation reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
