<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'ER' Reaches Ratings Milestone  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVID BAUDER AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- It went almost unnoticed with all the noise about
millionaires and instant brides, but NBC's "ER" reached a milestone last week
that proved it has a very loyal audience.
</P>
<P>
	   The medical drama's episode a week go, in which Kellie Martin's character
died after being stabbed the previous week, drew the most viewers for any
regular entertainment series since the "Seinfeld" finale in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Some 39 million people watched "ER" last week. That's more than any episode
of "Who Wants to Be a Millionaire" has ever drawn and more than twice the
audience of Fox's special, "Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire."
</P>
<P>
	   NBC was also helped by the crossover editions of "Law &AMP; Order" and "Law &AMP;
Order: Special Victims Unit," which scored the network its best Friday night
ratings since 1991.
</P>
<P>
	   Even with all that good ratings news, ABC still won the week with a
prime-time average of 15 million viewers (9.7 rating, 16 share). The reason?
Three editions of "Who Wants to Be a Millionaire" were the second, third and
fourth most-watched shows of the week.
</P>
<P>
	   ABC is certain to win the February ratings "sweeps" period, but is still
locked in a tight battle with NBC for dominance among the 18-to-49-year-old
audience that advertisers prize.
</P>
<P>
	   Fox's "Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire" drew 16 million viewers and
was particularly a hit among young women. But with the marriage on the rocks
after a week and Fox taking heat for not knowing its bridegroom was accused of
hitting an ex-girlfriend, it's an empty victory for the network.
</P>
<P>
	   NBC was the runner-up in the ratings race with 14 million average viewers
(9.6 rating, 16 share), CBS had 12.6 million viewers (8.7, 14), Fox had 11.2
million (7.3, 12), UPN had 4.1 million (2.7, 4), the WB had 3.7 million (2.7, 4)
and Pax TV had 1 million (0.8, 1).
</P>
<P>
	   The evening news ratings race was nearly a dead heat. ABC's "World News
Tonight" had 11.1 million viewers (8.0 rating, 16 share) and NBC's "Nightly
News" had 11 million viewers (8.0, 16). The "CBS Evening News" had 9.1 million
viewers (6.8, 13).
</P>
<P>
	   A rating point represents 1,008,000 households, or 1 percent of the nation's
estimated 100.8 million TV homes. The share is the percentage of in-use
televisions tuned to a given show.
</P>
<P>
	   For the week of Feb. 14-20, the top 10 shows, their networks and ratings
were "ER," NBC, 25.0; "Who Wants to Be a Millionaire" (Sunday), ABC, 18.1; "Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire" (Thursday), ABC, 18.0; "Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire" (Tuesday), ABC, 17.9; "Friends," NBC, 16.7; "Frasier," NBC, 14.2;
"The Practice," ABC, 13.6; "Law &AMP; Order" special, NBC, 13.2; 'Frasier" special,
NBC, 12.9; "Law &AMP; Order," NBC, 12.8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0132 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaria's Drug Resistance Studied  </HEADLINE>
    By RICK CALLAHAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   A mutation-prone gene in the malaria parasite apparently plays a key role in
the deadly organism's growing resistance to drugs, according to a report in
today's issue of the journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
	   The findings could help researchers design new drugs to combat the
mosquito-borne parasite, which kills more than a million people a year.
</P>
<P>
	   Scientists from the Walter and Eliza Hall Institute of Medical Research in
Melbourne and Australian National University in Canberra studied Plasmodium
falciparum, malaria's deadliest strain, and found that the mutated gene prevents
antimalarial drugs from accumulating within the parasite.
</P>
<P>
	   Somehow, the mutations allow the parasite to either block drugs from
entering or quickly pump them out, said Alan Cowman, chief of the division of
infection and immunity at the Hall Institute.
</P>
<P>
	   "The drugs only kill the parasite if they get concentrated inside it. Now
it's clear that these mutations prevent that accumulation from occurring,"
Cowman said.
</P>
<P>
	   He and colleagues reported that the mutated gene gives the parasites varying
resistance to five drugs.
</P>
<P>
	   The faulty gene, known as pfmdr1, has long been suspected of giving the
parasite resistance to drugs. But studies conflicted over whether it truly plays
any role.
</P>
<P>
	   Now, Cowman said his team has found direct proof that mutations in the gene
give the parasite resistance to the drugs quinine, mefloquinine and halofantrine
and also influence resistance to chloroquine and artemisinin.
</P>
<P>
	   Cowman said it is clear that another, as yet unknown gene plays a role in
giving malaria resistance to chloroquine and artemisinin.
</P>
<P>
	   His team came to its conclusions by genetically splicing the mutated gene
into malaria parasites not naturally resistant to drugs. The team then bred
those parasites and tested them against each drug.
</P>
<P>
	   Donald Krogstad, chairman of tropical medicine at Tulane University in New
Orleans, said the finding that the mutated gene influences resistance to up to
five drugs is worrisome.
</P>
<P>
	   "The bottom line for the public here is that if you get those mutations in
the parasite you're carrying, you've trashed three to four drugs at once, rather
than just one. That's very disturbing," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Malaria is a major drain on the economies of developing nations,
particularly in sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
	   The standard, inexpensive treatment for malaria had been chloroquine, but it
was among the first antimalarials the parasite became resistant to, said William
Rogers, director of preclinical research and development for the Naval Medical
Research Center's malaria program in Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
	   "When it began losing its effectiveness it pushed the cost of treatment up
five- or 10-fold. It's a major, major problem," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0134 </TRAILER>
