<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assisted Suicides Increase in Oregon  </HEADLINE>
   By BRAD CAIN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SALEM, Ore. (AP) -- While 27 terminally ill people used the nation's only
assisted suicide law to end their lives last year, doctors say only one in 10
requests for lethal prescriptions resulted in a suicide.
</P>
<P>
	   The findings were contained in separate studies published in today's New
England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Oregon physicians are responding in a careful and prudent manner when
patients request assisted suicide,'' said Dr. Linda Ganzini, the chief author of
the study about lethal prescription requests and director of geriatric
psychiatry at the Portland VA Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
	   First approved in 1994 and reaffirmed by Oregon voters in 1997, the law
allows a doctor to prescribe a lethal dose of barbiturates to patients who have
less than six months to live.
</P>
<P>
	   Sixteen Oregon residents used the Death with Dignity Act in 1998; most of
the 27 who used it last year were older cancer patients.
</P>
<P>
	   The did so out of a desire to have some control over the way they die,
according to Oregon health officials said reports from doctors.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Although concern about possible abuses persist, our data indicate that
poverty, lack of education or health insurance and poor care at the end of life
were not important factors in patients' requests for assistance with suicide,''
according to the other journal study.
</P>
<P>
	   Opponents of Oregon's law say it is immoral to have doctors assist in
suicides. An effort is under way in Congress to derail it and to prevent other
states from passing similar laws.
</P>
<P>
	   While backers of assisted suicide said the reports show the law is working
as intended, opponents disagreed.
</P>
<P>
	   One critic, Dr. William Breitbart, chief of psychiatry service at Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York, suggested that doctors might withhold
reports on assisted suicides that do not go well.
</P>
<P>
	   Dr. Gregory Hamilton of Physicians for Compassionate Care said the research
fails to mention a case in which a man who intentionally took a lethal dose was
resuscitated by emergency medical crews because his wife didn't want him to die.
Hamilton declined to provide specifics.
</P>
<P>
	   Dr. Katrina Hedberg, the author of the Oregon Health Division's report, said
she had not heard of the case.
</P>
<P>
	   She said the report showed no complications such as vomiting or seizures
among the 27 patients. On average, most of them were unconscious within 10
minutes, and the majority of patients were dead within three hours or less,
Hedberg said.
</P>
<P>
	   Seventeen of the 27 who took lethal drugs last year were cancer patients.
The others had chronic lung disease, AIDS or Lou Gehrig's disease.
</P>
<P>
	   The median age of the those who took their lives was 71; all patients had
health insurance and 21 were in hospice care before death.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The fact is, the patients died peacefully, surrounded by their family
members and friends,'' said George Eighmey, executive director of Compassion in
Dying in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
	   The study focusing on lethal prescription requests found that the small
percentage of Oregon patients who request them actually receive the
prescriptions and end their lives with the medication.
</P>
<P>
	   A survey of more than 2,600 Oregon physicians found that 5 percent of them
had received requests for lethal prescriptions since November 1997 and that only
one in 10 such requests actually resulted in a suicide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0137 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
