<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Council Nears Congo Agreement  </HEADLINE>
   By EDITH M. LEDERER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- In an unheralded African success story, civil war in
the Republic of Congo has ended, but there isn't enough money to help the
hundreds of thousands of people with great humanitarian needs.
</P>
<P>
	   That was the message delivered Wednesday by Bill Paton, the U.N.
humanitarian coordinator in the country, who said he had never seen access open
up so quickly in an African country -- in this case just weeks after a Dec. 29
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
	   ``People are demobilizing. Offensive action and battles really have ceased,
and perhaps as many as half of the opposition militia members, along with
members of the government militia ... are demobilizing and coming out of the
bush,'' he told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
	   The situation, he noted, is in stark contrast to the shaky cease-fire and
intermittent fighting across the Congo River in President Laurent Kabila's
Congo.
</P>
<P>
	   Paton said about half the 810,000 people who fled their homes after fighting
broke out in late 1998 have gone back, many to the capital Brazzaville, and
rural areas that were inaccessible for over a year can suddenly be reached.
</P>
<P>
	   The result, he said, is a tremendous strain on very limited resources.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Basic humanitarian needs remain very, very great,'' Paton said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Last year, these 810,000 people were the least assisted displaced people
or refugees in the world because of security and also frankly a degree of lack
of interest,'' he said. ``Most of these people received no assistance
whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
	   The United Nations appealed for $7 million in non-food assistance for the
Republic of Congo last year but got just $1.2 million, he said. It received $7
million worth of food and is using some of it to help the refugees now.
</P>
<P>
	   This year, the United Nations is appealing for $19.6 million and will likely
ask for additional money because of the demands of the refugees, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have the opportunity to meet humanitarian needs and support efforts to
build a sustainable peace,'' Paton said. ``My concern is really about speed.''
</P>
<P>
	   The international community needs to help reintegrate demobilized soldiers,
provide basic assistance to rebuild communities in the bush that people are
trying to rejoin, improve justice and plan for elections, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The United Nations has been asked to assist with the reintegration of
demobilized militia members and has started a pilot project with 120 men, Paton
said.
</P>
<P>
	   But there are 15,000 demobilized soldiers, and U.N. resources at the moment
consist of a $320,000 grant from Norway which will only pay to find new jobs for
between 500 and 1,000 soldiers, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We'll continue to try to get contributions so we can increase the size of
that group,'' Paton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0212 </TRAILER>
