<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> America's Cup Race 3 Postponed  </HEADLINE>
By BERNIE WILSON-
AP Sports Writer-
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) -- It's time to break out all the criticisms about
sailing.
</P>
<P>
	Watching it is like watching paint dry ... grass grow ... a car rust.
</P>
<P>
	During the next week at the America's Cup, a few more might pop up. The
forecast for the next seven days -- which includes four scheduled races -- is
for more of the light wind that led officials to postpone Race 3 today between
Italy's Luna Rossa and New Zealand's Black Magic, which leads the best-of-9
series 2-0.
</P>
<P>
	It was the second time in six days that racing was called off because the
summer weather was too nice on the unpredictable Hauraki Gulf. There was more
breeze than there was when Saturday's race was called -- the highest was 8 knots
-- but race officials said it was too unstable, finally calling it nearly 2 1/2
hours after the scheduled start.
</P>
<P>
	After a lay day Friday, the third race is now scheduled for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	Hamish Wilcox, weatherman for Prada Challenge, which is backing Luna Rossa,
said the forecast calls for light air for the next seven days, which includes
four scheduled races.
</P>
<P>
	The sailors agree that it's painful to just circle around waiting for the
breeze to fill in.
</P>
<P>
	``Light days are pretty much like you see it on TV -- it's like watching the
grass grow,'' said Black Magic tactician Brad Butterworth, a key member of the
team that routed Dennis Conner off San Diego in 1995 to bring the America's Cup
to Auckland.
</P>
<P>
	Besides pushing back the schedule, the weather delays are spawning a bit of a
controversy. Experts say Luna Rossa performs well in light conditions and that
Black Magic does better in heavier air.
</P>
<P>
	Race director Harold Bennett said the notion that his decision was influenced
by Team New Zealand is ``incorrect.''
</P>
<P>
	Luna Rossa's sailors wanted to sail. Black Magic's didn't. They both had their
reasons.
</P>
<P>
	``We were a little unhappy that we didn't have a race today,'' Luna Rossa
navigator Matteo Plazzi said. ``We felt the conditions were good enough today,
better than a few of the races of the (challenger series).
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to come back from our bad sailing day, and everyone wanted to go
for a race today.''
</P>
<P>
	He was referring to Tuesday's disastrous second race, when the Italians had
every possible bad break happen, including a bloodied crewman and a keel fouled
by debris.
</P>
<P>
	Butterworth said light, shifty winds can be a problem for both teams.
</P>
<P>
	``If there's a big enough difference (in shifts) and big holes, it can become a
bit of luck, and that can be a big problem.''
</P>
<P>
	Butterworth said complaints of a lopsided playing field aren't new.
</P>
<P>
	``Ever since I've been in this game, it's been the challengers' prerogative to
complain,'' he said. ``I just think it's an inherited thing of challengers to
complain. We complained when we were challengers.''
</P>
<P>
	Butterworth said the Kiwis don't mind sailing in light wind, noting that the
conditions were similar off San Diego.
</P>
<P>
	Bennett said the only part of the course with acceptable wind was in the
starting area. ``Prada proved that to us by sailing up and down in it. Up the
course, there was nothing to convince me to do it and be fair with it.
</P>
<P>
	``Basically it was my call,'' Bennett said. ``I wasn't happy with it.''
</P>
<P>
	Some spectators spent the long delay fishing or swimming.
</P>
<P>
	Massimiliano Sirena was back on Luna Rossa two days after having his head
gashed by the pole the Italians were using to try to clear debris from their
keel on the disastrous first leg of Race 2.
</P>
<P>
	Sirena was taken off the boat to receive stitches, but remained on the water to
watch the rest of the race. He stayed at home Wednesday when Luna Rossa went out
to train on an off day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0216 </TRAILER>
