<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nomar Has Big Numbers, Except Salary  </HEADLINE>
    By HOWARD ULMAN AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- Nomar Garciaparra has piled up some impressive
numbers in his three full major league seasons -- 92 homers and a .326 batting
average.
</P>
<P>
	   His salary figures, however, are nothing special. Despite being rookie of
the year, runnerup in the MVP voting and batting champion in the American League
during his career, he was paid less last season than 17 other starting
shortstops.
</P>
<P>
	   He claims that doesn't bother him. The jackpot he wants to hit is a World
Series championship with the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't really look at individual stuff,'' Garciaparra said. ``Hopefully,
I've gotten better to help the team get better and get to our ultimate goal.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Red Sox have gotten closer in each of his three seasons -- missing the
playoffs in his first year, reaching the first round the next year and advancing
to the second round last year.
</P>
<P>
	   Had they beaten the New York Yankees in the AL championship series in 1999,
the Red Sox would have reached the World Series for the first time since 1986.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We didn't lose to a better team. We just didn't play well enough to win at
the time,'' Garciaparra said. ``My goal's the same every year. I try to win the
World Series.''
</P>
<P>
	   Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter has three World Series rings and makes a lot
more money than Garciaparra. Seattle shortstop Alex Rodriguez also draws a
bigger salary and could become baseball's highest-paid player after this season.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If he gets what he gets, I'm happy for him,'' Garciaparra said of Jeter.
``I'm perfectly content with what I got. It was a great thing to do at the time,
and if I look back, I still would have done it the same way. I was able to do
some stuff, take care of some personal things, knowing that the security was
there.''
</P>
<P>
	   Garciaparra is earning $3.3 million in the third year of a five-year
contract worth $23.25 million
</P>
<P>
	   Jeter has a $10 million, one-year deal and is negotiating a record $118.5
million, seven-year contract. Rodriguez is making $4.25 million in the final
year of his contract and could get $200 million over 10 years as a free agent
next fall.
</P>
<P>
	   Garciaparra's .322 career batting average is higher than both of theirs, but
he said he hasn't considered asking to renegotiate his deal after Jeter signs a
long-term contract.
</P>
<P>
	   ``That doesn't even cross my mind,'' said Garciaparra, who went through his
first full-squad workout Wednesday. ``I don't even know what he's making.''
</P>
<P>
	   Garciaparra's contract has salaries of $6.85 million in 2001 and $8.6
million in 2002, then gives the Red Sox option to keep him at $10.5 million in
2003 and $11.5 million in 2004, with a $1 million buyout in the unlikely event
they let him go.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1997, Garciaparra hit .306 and led the AL with 209 hits and 11 triples.
The next year he hit .323 and was runnerup for the MVP award. Last year, he led
the AL with a .357 average.
</P>
<P>
	   Third baseman John Valentin said he hasn't seen much change in Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think he's buying a little bit more dinners now, but he's really the
same Nomar. He's down to earth, a fan favorite, and well deserved,'' Valentin
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Garciaparra went through the playoffs with a wrist bruised when it was hit
by a pitch from Baltimore's Al Reyes on Sept. 25. He played nine of the 10
playoff games, sitting out only Game 3 in the AL division series against
Cleveland with Boston trailing 2-0.
</P>
<P>
	   ``That was the hardest thing I've ever had to do in my life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   But he's healthy now and ready to continue his role as the offensive leader
-- if not the financial leader -- on the Red Sox, who had 17 players making more
than him last season.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm totally content with what I got,'' Garciaparra said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
