<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Primary Attacks Form Rich Harvest  </HEADLINE>
   By CALVIN WOODWARD Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The talk of bigotry, desperation and lack of principle
swirling around the presidential candidates these days is all geared to seizing
the moment. But it will have a shelf life lasting into the fall.
</P>
<P>
	   Come summer and the national conventions, each party will unite around the
proposition that its nominee is a swell fellow after all. Come the fall
campaign, strategists will stand ready to remind voters of all the nasty things
said when Democrats and Republicans went after their own.
</P>
<P>
	   Perhaps not since George Bush slammed Ronald Reagan's ``voodoo economics''
in the 1980 campaign and Democrats didn't let anyone forget it have the
opportunities been so rich to exploit intraparty warfare.
</P>
<P>
	   Essentially, said Paul Begala, a mastermind of Bill Clinton's campaign in
1992, ``My friends in the Democratic Party don't need to make any negative ads
in the fall. All they need to do is to run a VCR on today's news coverage.''
</P>
<P>
	   That coverage shows Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain trading biting
charges about religion-tinged tactics used by the other man's supporters. It
also shows an angry Bill Bradley painting Democratic rival Al Gore as a man
without convictions who has trouble telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The campaigns are a lot more bitter and personal than party loyalists
would want,'' said Begala, now a pundit. ``It is going to hurt both sides.''
</P>
<P>
	   GOP consultant Scott Reed, who managed Republican Bob Dole's 1996
presidential campaign, said Bradley's theme of attacking Gore's veracity will
echo in the fall if the vice president wins the nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's helpful that he's warming it up, but Republicans were going to use it
anyway,'' he said. ``It's right out of the RNC (Republican National Committee)
playbook.''
</P>
<P>
	   On the GOP side, the McCain campaign phoned Roman Catholic voters in
Michigan to ensure they knew Bush spoke at a South Carolina school viewed as
anti-Catholic.
</P>
<P>
	   To help Bush, apparently on his own, a message recorded by Christian
Coalition founder Pat Robertson describing a McCain co-chairman as a ``vicious
bigot'' who is against Christian conservatives also was telephoned to potential
voters.
</P>
<P>
	   Begala can see it now: if Bush wins the nomination, a Democratic ad or
brochure featuring sharp criticisms leveled by McCain; if McCain wins, a similar
encapsulation of what Bush once said about his GOP rival.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They're going to star in the negative Democratic ads in the fall,'' Begala
predicted.
</P>
<P>
	   Charlie Black, a top Republican strategist backing Bush, said GOP ads might
show more finesse than simply splashing Bradley's words on the screen, if Gore
wins the nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   But one way or another, he suggested, Republicans will attempt to reinforce
vulnerabilities that Bradley is helping to expose in Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We might use Bradley,'' he said. ``But if I had to spend the rest of the
afternoon mapping out the campaign, there is plenty of Gore footage to use.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We might do better to put Gore on TV talking about 'no controlling legal
authority,''' he said, referring to the vice president's clumsy defense of 1996
fund-raising practices.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley accused Gore on Wednesday of showing ``followership,'' not
leadership. He speaks derisively of the ``Gore dance,'' and a new campaign ad
asks: ``When it comes right down to it, what does Al Gore really stand for?''
Gore says his opponent is desperate.
</P>
<P>
	   Because Clinton was unopposed in 1996, Republicans had few
Democrat-to-Democrat attacks to throw in his face.
</P>
<P>
	   And in 1992, the Democratic primary fight won by Clinton was courteous by
the standards of this race, Begala said.
</P>
<P>
	   When Gennifer Flowers made her explosive allegations during the 1992 New
Hampshire campaign that she'd been Clinton's lover, his Democratic opponents
tiptoed.
</P>
<P>
	   This time, transcendent character flaws of a different sort are being openly
alleged by candidates and quickly earmarked by the opposition.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush's visit to Bob Jones University, which also forbids interracial dating
among students, won't be forgotten. And Republican researchers are fattening
their Gore files by the hour.
</P>
<P>
	   All for the autumn day when the candidates who lose in the spring rise again
in unintended service to the other side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0243 </TRAILER>
