<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 02:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley: workers, women and children should benefit more from boom  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - America should take the lead in opening markets around
the world, says Bill Bradley. But the Democratic presidential candidate wants
the government to pay the price for any American jobs lost in the process.
<P>
	   Speaking to students at Columbia University on Wednesday, he proposed that
workers who lose jobs as a result of foreign trade agreements be offered
financial help.
</P>
<P>
	   "Despite our success, far too many Americans are on the outside looking in,"
said the former senator from New Jersey, who is battling Vice President Al Gore
for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley said America cannot sustain its booming economy unless it fortifies
a basic pillar of its success: working families.
</P>
<P>
	   The so-called Earnings Insurance Program linked to trade agreements would
reimburse half a worker's lost wages for three years, up to a maximum of $10,000
per year. Bradley estimates the program would cost no more than $200 million a
year, once an agreement takes effect.
</P>
<P>
	   Speaking under a mammoth American flag, he faced a friendly audience of
mostly students who greeted him with warm applause and a standing ovation. Then
he laid out his economic vision.
</P>
<P>
	   For the first time in a half century, he said, the country's economy has
broken free of the post-Depression and World War II economic legacy.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley accused Gore of offering an economic policy that would harm the
country rather than prolong its prosperity. He said the vice president would
pursue national debt reduction even if the economy were slow, the kind of
management Bradley believes once contributed to the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
	   However, he praised America's "spectacular" economic performance under the
Clinton administration and said the pro-growth policies should remain in place.
</P>
<P>
	   "But the base of economic revival must be broadened. Prosperity is
inclusive, not exclusive," Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
	   He cited such statistics as the 13.5 million children living in poverty, the
44 million citizens without health insurance and the income gap between men and
women.
</P>
<P>
	   "Workers and families are at the top of my economic agenda," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   And, the candidate said, attention must be paid to future workers.
</P>
<P>
	   For them, Bradley proposed a $100 million pilot program to teach children
below the poverty level how to use computers in this information-driven age.
Each family would get a $400 "Infostamp," and the computer industry would be
challenged to create a package of hardware, software and Internet access for
that price.
</P>
<P>
	   "We will not have true prosperity until all our citizens share in the
prosperity of our economic growth," Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
	   To finance the new economic agenda, he said, the nation now has a powerful
tool - fiscal surplus.
</P>
<P>
	   His speech, sponsored by the Columbia University Economic Society, marked
Bradley's third straight day on the New York campaign trail as the March 7
"Super Tuesday" primaries - including the New York vote - draw near.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday night, the former New York Knicks star debated Gore at the Apollo
Theatre; on Tuesday he campaigned on Long Island. The New York primary is
considered key to his presidential bid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-24-00 0249 </TRAILER>
