<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 02:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley: Gore Stole My Ideas  </HEADLINE>
   By LAURENCE ARNOLD Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The campaign trail can be a lonely place, but Bill
Bradley wishes it was even lonelier. Every time he proposes an idea, he
complains, Al Gore suggests the same thing.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Sometimes I think I should be humming 'Me and My Shadow,''' Bradley said
recently.
</P>
<P>
	   It happened again Wednesday, when the vice president proposed a Medicare
coverage plan resembling what Bradley put on the table last year.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is yet another example of the 'co-opt Kid' at work,'' Bradley
groused.
</P>
<P>
	   It has become a common refrain from the underdog's camp: Bradley says he
breaks new ground on an issue, only to find Gore close behind.
</P>
<P>
	   During a debate Monday in New York, Bradley criticized Gore for capping the
prescription drug benefit in his health care plan. Gore revised his proposal
Wednesday to lift the cap.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley strategist Anita Dunn said Gore again ``acknowledged that he dares
to follow where Bill Bradley has boldly led.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gore also has aped Bradley's schedule by rushing out announcements on the
eve of Bradley's own long-planned pronouncements on the same subjects.
</P>
<P>
	   By drawing attention now to the trend, Bradley hopes to underscore his
latest line of attack, which is that Gore has no core beliefs of his own. ``He
claims these issues are priorities for him, but priorities come from
convictions, not through polls,'' Bradley told New Yorkers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore aides said the revised prescription plan was based on recent
projections of bigger budget surpluses. A spokesman said the vice president has
no shortage of original proposals.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's typical of Bradley to try to take credit for every idea under the
sun,'' said Gore spokesman Doug Hattaway. ``But the fact is, these are big
issues that a lot of candidates are talking about. I don't think voters are
keeping a scorecard on who is proposing them first.''
</P>
<P>
	   Though concerned that ``co-opt kid'' might sound like the lament of a
challenger trailing badly in the polls, Bradley partisans say the evidence of
the pattern is -- as one put it -- ``uncanny.''
</P>
<P>
	   -- Earlier this month, Bradley criticized President Clinton for nominating
Bradley Smith, a Republican who opposes overhauling the campaign finance system,
to the board of the Federal Election Commission, and questioned why Gore had not
protested Clinton's decision. Gore criticized the nomination four days later,
saying he was unaware of it.
</P>
<P>
	   -- Last April, Bradley condemned the flying of the Confederate flag over the
South Carolina Statehouse. As recently as Jan. 7, a Gore spokeswoman said he
``supports the right of the people of South Carolina'' to remove it. In
mid-January, Gore said the flag should be removed from public buildings because
it divides Americans.
</P>
<P>
	   -- In a September interview with The Advocate, Bradley called for abolishing
the Clinton administration's ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy on gays in the
military. Gore earlier had said he would implement the policy ``with more
compassion.'' In December, he said he would end it, too.
</P>
<P>
	   -- Bradley also told The Advocate he opposes as ``divisive'' an
anti-gay-marriage ballot initiative in California. Gore previously had said he
would ``have to educate myself'' about it. But hours after Bradley's interview
was released, Gore's campaign said Gore opposed it, too. ``Consider him
educated,'' a spokeswoman said then.
</P>
<P>
	   -- In June, Bradley unveiled a gun-control agenda that included a proposed
ban on cheap ``Saturday night specials'' and a mandatory photo ID card for
handgun owners. In July, Gore unveiled a gun-control plan that included photo
gun licenses and a ban on Saturday night specials.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore aides said the plan includes elements not in Bradley's -- such as
stricter penalties for dealers who sell guns illegally -- and is part of a
larger crime-fighting plan unmatched by Bradley.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore aides also say Bradley takes credit for thinking up initiatives already
offered by the Clinton-Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley is hardly the first politician to claim theft of ideas.
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans for years have complained that Clinton has co-opted their
issues, taking credit for welfare reform and balanced budgets that the GOP had
championed for years.
</P>
<P>
	   Republican Bob Dole tried pressing the case in his unsuccessful 1996
campaign against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
	   As Dole put it then, ``If everything he's for we're already for, why
shouldn't we be there instead of him?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0254 </TRAILER>
