<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Roundup  </HEADLINE>
    By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Just three games into his stint with the Philadelphia 76ers, Toni Kukoc has
already reached a career high.
</P>
<P>
	   Kukoc grabbed 14 rebounds, more than he ever grabbed playing alongside on
the Chicago Bulls, as the 76ers defeated the Los Angeles Clippers 94-78
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's still too early to compare roles, but I'm glad guys are looking for
me," said Kukoc, whose 18 points were his most since joining Philadelphia in a
three-team trade last week.
</P>
<P>
	   The 76ers opened a double-digit lead in the first quarter and held it most
of the way, although the Clippers closed to 68-60 with 31 seconds left in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
	   A jumper by Kukoc restored the double-digit lead, and Philadelphia then
pulled away by scoring the first eight points of the fourth quarter. Allen
Iverson capped the run with a steal and dunk.
</P>
<P>
	   In other NBA games, the Los Angeles Lakers defeated Cleveland 116-98,
Toronto beat New York 99-88, Golden State downed Milwaukee 91-86, Miami beat New
Jersey 99-85, Indiana topped Detroit 118-111 and Atlanta defeated Sacramento
100-94.
</P>
<P>
	   Iverson scored 22 points and Tyrone Hill had 15 for the 76ers, who bounced
back from a loss Sunday night to the Lakers. In that game, Iverson had his
next-to-last shot rejected by Kobe Bryant instead of passing to Kukoc, who was
wide open in the corner.
</P>
<P>
	   In this game, Kukoc took another step toward getting acquainted with his new
teammates.
</P>
<P>
	   "He's a highly gifted player," coach Larry Brown said. "I hope he's getting
more comfortable."
</P>
<P>
	   Lamar Odom had 20 points and nine rebounds for the Clippers. Derek Anderson
had 19 points and Maurice Taylor 18 for Los Angeles, which has lost 26 of 29
games.
</P>
<P>
	   Bryant scored 21 points and Robert Horry 20 as the Lakers completed a sweep
of their six-game Eastern Conference road trip and won their ninth straight
overall.
</P>
<P>
	   Los Angeles is now tied for the best record in the NBA with Portland at
43-11.
</P>
<P>
	   Cleveland's Shawn Kemp finished the night by tearing off his jersey and
tossing it into the stands. He was ejected late in the fourth quarter for
throwing towels on the court after he fouled out.
</P>
<P>
	   Kemp, who scored 23 points, showered quickly and left Gund Arena without
speaking to reporters. He has been the subject of numerous rumors approaching
today's 3 p.m. EST trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
	   The Cavaliers came back from a 13-point first-half deficit to take a couple
of brief leads in the third quarter. But Bryant's 3-pointer with 1:30 left in
the quarter put Los Angeles up for good at 79-76, and the Lakers pulled away as
Shaquille O'Neal scored 11 of his 19 points in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
	   Vince Carter had 33 points, nine rebounds and nine assists as Toronto
snapped a three-game losing streak and ruined Patrick Ewing's move into 15th
place on the NBA's career scoring list.
</P>
<P>
	   Carter scored 15 points in the third quarter and Toronto's final seven of
the game to give the Raptors their second victory over the Knicks in nine days.
</P>
<P>
	   Doug Christie added 22 points and Tracy McGrady had 16 for the Raptors, who
ended New York's five-game home winning streak.
</P>
<P>
	   Donyell Marshall had a career-high 37 points and a season-high 21 rebounds
as Golden State, playing without its top three scorers, won at Milwaukee
</P>
<P>
	   Erick Dampier added 12 points and 10 rebounds for the Warriors, who
improbably won for the third time in four games despite playing without injured
Antawn Jamison, Chris Mills and Larry Hughes, a last-minute scratch because of a
sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
	   Marshall's dominant performance, which included 21 second-half points and
eight offensive rebounds, gave Milwaukee a six-game homecourt losing streak. The
Bucks have lost seven of eight games overall.
</P>
<P>
	   Alonzo Mourning came back from a broken nose and hit his first 13 shots,
scoring a season-high 43 points.
</P>
<P>
	   Mourning, injured Monday when he was struck by Michael Curry's elbow in a
loss at Detroit, finished 13-of-14 from the field and made 17 of 24 free throws.
He added 16 rebounds in 33 minutes.
</P>
<P>
	   The Heat, coming off a 1-3 road trip, won their seventh straight home game.
Miami earned its first victory over the Nets in three games this season.
</P>
<P>
	   Rik Smits returned to the Indiana lineup with a season-high 29 points as the
Pacers won at Detroit.
</P>
<P>
	   Indiana got Smits back after he missed three games with a sore back. Reggie
Miller and Jalen Rose each scored 23 points and Austin Croshere had 18 as the
Pacers won for the sixth time in seven games. Mark Jackson had six points and 14
assists.
</P>
<P>
	   Grant Hill led Detroit with 24 points and Lindsey Hunter had 20, but the
Pistons lost for the fourth time in five games.
</P>
<P>
	   Isaiah Rider scored 33 points in Atlanta's win at Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
	   The Hawks won for the fourth straight time at Arco Arena, and they are 11-1
against the Kings in the past seven seasons.
</P>
<P>
	   Jim Jackson had 17 points, 12 rebounds and six assists for the Hawks.
</P>
<P>
	   Chris Webber had 28 points and 20 rebounds for the Kings, who have lost
three straight and six of seven.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
