<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 02:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spurs' Elliott Closer to Return  </HEADLINE>
    By KELLEY SHANNON AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Sean Elliott, bidding to make an unprecedented comeback
after a kidney transplant, hopes to be playing for the San Antonio Spurs in the
next three weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   Elliott said Wednesday he needs more weeks like this one, with back-to-back
practices, as he returns to game shape.
</P>
<P>
	   "Tuesday's practice was a monster," said Elliott, who went through grueling
drills that day with the reserves. Elliott practiced again Wednesday with the
full team before the Spurs left for a three-game road trip to Charlotte, Chicago
and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
	   No exact timetable for his return has been set by the 32-year-old forward or
coach Gregg Popovich. Popovich wouldn't say Wednesday what kind of progress
Elliott is making or when he might return.
</P>
<P>
	   "I can't on a day-to-day basis say he improved X percent," Popovich said.
"We're going to wait until the beginning of March, evaluate him again, and then
we'll give everybody an idea of where he's at."
</P>
<P>
	   Elliott said he doesn't care which game marks his return and joked that
cheering from the fans won't be the only thing motivating him when he makes his
comeback.
</P>
<P>
	   "What motivates me is I don't want to embarrass myself when I run out onto
the floor," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Elliott resumed full practices with the team in early February.
</P>
<P>
	   He had to sign a waiver releasing the Spurs from liability should he be
injured during his comeback. He is making $6.2 million this season and is to
make $5 million next season, the last year of his contract.
</P>
<P>
	   Elliott received a kidney from his brother, Noel, on Aug. 16. Elliott had
focal segmental glomerular sclerosis, which prevents the kidneys from properly
filtering waste from the blood. Without the transplant, he soon would have been
forced to undergo kidney dialysis.
</P>
<P>
	   If he resumes his NBA career, he would be the first pro athlete to return a
sport after a kidney transplant.
</P>
<P>
	   Elliott made some key plays last year in helping San Antonio win its first
NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
	   Nearly falling out of bounds, he hit a game-winning 3-point shot during the
Western Conference finals against Portland. Elliott averaged 11.9 points in the
playoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0257 </TRAILER>
