<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teen-ager convicted of murdering stepfather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WATURBURY, Conn. (AP) - An 18-year-old Watertown man has been convicted
of murder in the stabbing of his stepfather, a killing he claimed came in self
defense as he tried to protect himself from being beaten.
<P>
	   Patrick Collins, who was 16 at the time of the stabbing, faces up to 60
years in prison when he is sentenced on April 28.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutor Maureen Keegan had argued that Collins easily could have fled
from the January 1998 fight with James DiVirgilio, 41, instead of stabbing him
to death with an 8-inch kitchen knife.
</P>
<P>
	   Collins' lawyer, Karen Diebolt, argued that Collins was defending himself
after DiVirgilio, who was high on a mix of cocaine and alcohol, began repeatedly
punching Collins over a $150 stereo the youth bought on his mother's credit card
with her permission.
</P>
<P>
	   Many of Collins' family and friends burst into sobs after the verdict was
read. Collins, 18, then stood with his hands in his pockets and his head bowed
as each of the 12 jurors stood and called out "guilty" as they were polled by
the court.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm devastated," Diebolt said outside the courtroom. "We obviously thought
he was not guilty because this was self-defense. If I couldn't convince 12
people of that, I thought the compromise would be manslaughter. I never expected
straight murder."
</P>
<P>
	   Keegan said the verdict showed jurors did not believe Collins' account of
the events leading up to the stabbing.
</P>
<P>
	   "The crime scene totally conflicted with the version that Patrick Collins
gave," Keegan said. "The victim was unarmed and there were no signs of
struggle."
</P>
<P>
	   Relatives of DiVirgilio sat quietly together in the courtroom after the
verdict. Neither they nor Collins' relatives would comment Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-24-00 0300 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 03:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Thursday, Feb. 24, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Serbs Threaten Protests in Kosovo
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serbs in this ethnically divided city
are threatening protests and more unrest in response to plans by NATO-led
peacekeepers to begin resettling ethnic Albanians on the Serb-controlled north
bank of the Ibar River. The plans announced Wednesday by the peacekeeping
command involve moving ethnic Albanians back to homes in three high-rise
apartment buildings. U.N. officials said ethnic Albanians would begin
registering Friday and relocations would begin next week.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
States Have $7B of Unspent Welfare
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A coalition of anti-poverty groups said states are
hoarding $7 billion in unspent federal funds earmarked to help poor Americans
and called on governors to see to it that the money is used to assist low-income
families. Seventeen states each have accumulated more than $100 million in
unspent federal funds from 1997 to 1999. Other states have tens of millions of
dollars they haven't spent, a study by the National Campaign for Jobs and Income
showed. California had the most, with $1.6 billion. New York had the second
highest amount -- $1.1 billion -- and Ohio was third, with nearly $734 million.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Egypt Awaits, Prepares for Pope
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Under scenes depicting Christ's life and his family's
sojourn in Egypt, workers raced to prepare for Pope John Paul II on his own
journey to retrace some of the most epic passages from the Bible. The three-day
visit, scheduled to begin Thursday, has taken on dual dimensions: a highly
personal pilgrimage for the elderly pontiff and also an opportunity to promote
closer dialogue with Muslims and try to overcome old rifts with Orthodox
Christians. "We never could have imagined that we would have the pope under our
roof," said Samir Yassa, who designed the cathedral where John Paul plans to
meet Friday with Orthodox and Coptic clergymen in a display of their shared
roots.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Student Faces Gov't. Hacking Charges
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BOSTON (AP) -- A computer science student has been accused of a "coast to
coast" hacking spree of military and government networks that prosecutors said
gave him control of a NASA computer system. Ikenna Iffih, 28, a student at
Northeastern University's College of Computer Science, was charged Wednesday
with three counts related to hacking that carry up to 10 years in prison and a
fine of $250,000. "All in all, the defendant used his home computer to leave a
trail of cybercrime from coast to coast," U.S. Attorney Donald Stern said in a
statement.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Santana Wins Record-Tying 8 Grammys
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Carlos Santana, who first gained fame a generation ago
with a searing guitar performance at Woodstock, capped a triumphant comeback
Wednesday with a record-tying eight Grammy Awards. The 52-year-old guitarist's
multi-platinum "Supernatural" won album of the year. His first No. 1 single,
"Smooth," capped a sweep of the major Grammys by winning song and record of the
year. Santana tied Michael Jackson's 1983 record of most Grammys on a single
night. "Music is the vehicle for the magic of healing," he said upon accepting
the album of the year trophy, "and the music of 'Supernatural' was a sign and
designed to bring unity and harmony."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nigerians Flee Smoldering City
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   KADUNA, Nigeria (AP) -- Charred bodies and burned-out cars littered the
streets of the north-central Nigerian city of Kaduna on Wednesday, as hundreds
of residents fled the scene of two days of religious clashes that left at least
200 dead. An overwhelming stench filled the morgue at the main hospital, where
dozens of bodies were piled up on slabs, on the floor, and even the ground
outside.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Close Higher
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- On the Tokyo Stock Exchange Thursday, the Nikkei closed up
51.89 points at 19,571.44. On Wall Street Wednesday, the Dow closed down 79.11
points while the Nasdaq rose 168.21.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
D-Backs: AL Move May Be Inevitable
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- There is a growing feeling among the Arizona
Diamondbacks that a move to the American League next season might be inevitable.
The defending NL West champions will have to be dragged kicking and screaming to
the other league, but they know they have no choice if that's what the other
owners decide to do. "It was a last-minute addition and I didn't like it, but we
had no choice," Diamondbacks owner Jerry Colangelo said as he watched the team's
first full-squad workout Wednesday. "I wasn't happy at the time and I'm not any
happier today."
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0301 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 03:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Puffy Combs Hit With More Charges  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Bribery charges have been added to gun possession counts
against rapper Sean "Puffy" Combs following a nightclub shooting in which three
people were wounded.
</P>
<P>
	   Combs and bodyguard Anthony Jones were indicted Wednesday, accused of
offering $50,000 and a diamond ring to the driver of the sport utility vehicle
in which the three were riding the night of the shooting. Combs' girlfriend,
Jennifer Lopez, also was in the vehicle early Dec. 27.
</P>
<P>
	   Combs allegedly offered the ring -- a birthday present from Lopez -- as a
bribe to Wardel Fenderson, 41, between Dec. 27 and Dec. 30, Manhattan District
Attorney Robert Morgenthau said.
</P>
<P>
	   Both Combs and Lopez were up for Grammy Awards presented Wednesday night in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
	   "I am outraged by this new charge," Combs said in a statement Wednesday. "I
am not guilty. From the outset I have firmly believed that the Manhattan
district attorney's office has unfairly targeted me for baseless charges."
</P>
<P>
	   Benjamin Brafman, Combs' attorney, also refuted the latest charges and
criticized the timing of their release.
</P>
<P>
	   "If this indictment was in fact timed to embarrass Mr. Combs on the evening
of the Grammy awards, I would be terribly disappointed in the Manhattan district
attorney," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Combs, Fenderson and Jones were arrested after one of Combs' proteges
allegedly shot three people inside Club New York. The gunman, Jamal "Shyne"
Barrow, 19, was arrested separately and charged with three counts of attempted
murder.
</P>
<P>
	   Combs pleaded innocent to the weapons charges earlier this month. The
bribery charge carries a maximum penalty of seven years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0301 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
