<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 03:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Looks At Education Accounts  </HEADLINE>
   By JIM ABRAMS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Trying once more to put their stamp on the education
debate, Senate Republicans again are pushing an educational IRA plan that
President Clinton has vetoed twice in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill taken up by the Senate Wednesday would allow parents to place as
much as $2,000 per year, per child, in educational savings accounts. The
tax-free interest could be used for expenses, including transportation and
tutors, associated with any school -- public, private or parochial -- from
kindergarten through the 12th grade. The education IRAs would expire at the end
of 2003.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill, costing $7.7 billion over 10 years, would also make savings in
prepaid tuition plans tax free and expand tax breaks for employer-provided
educational assistance.
</P>
<P>
	   Democrat Robert Torricelli of New Jersey is a co-sponsor. He said about 10
of the Senate's 45 Democrats would support it, but the driving force is
Republicans who contend that the key to improving education is to give local
schools and parents more control over education dollars.
</P>
<P>
	   Democrats say education money should go to hiring more teachers and building
and repairing schoolhouses.
</P>
<P>
	   The GOP majority ``again seeks to divert critical resources needed in our
public schools,'' said Education Secretary Richard Riley. ``Once again it is a
distraction from meaningful progress in education.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton vetoed a similar bill in 1998, saying more affluent families would
be the main beneficiaries and that it would encourage people to abandon public
schools. Republicans tried again in 1999, inserting the bill in their 10-year
$792 billion comprehensive tax cut plan that Clinton vetoed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are going to keep bringing this up, keep bringing it to the public
attention, keep sending it to the president,'' said Sen. Paul Coverdell of
Georgia, the chief Republican sponsor.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This bill fails to address the serious needs of public schools. It fails
to meet the needs of the nation's children, and it fails to make much-needed
investments in America's future,'' said Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
	   The National Education Association, in a letter to senators, also urged
rejection of the bill, saying it ignores the problems of public schools and
``would divert billions of dollars to tax breaks for private school ESAs.''
</P>
<P>
	   But Torricelli said it was the president who laid the foundation for
education savings accounts when he pushed the current program that allows
parents to contribute up to $500 a year with tax-deductible earnings available
for college expenses such as tuition and books.
</P>
<P>
	   He and Coverdell argued that it would lead to an education spending infusion
of $12 billion and that the main beneficiaries would be middle-class families
with children in public schools.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Every segment of education in America will be a winner: public education,
private education, home schooling, you name it,'' Coverdell said. ``These
accounts will infuse new resources for which the federal government will not
have to appropriate a dime.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   The bill number is S. 1134.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0314 </TRAILER>
