<HEADLINE> Clinton To Revive Economic Theme  </HEADLINE>
   By ANNE GEARAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Using the nation's vastly improved bottom line as a
backdrop, President Clinton is reprising the economic theme of a speech he gave
while running for president eight years ago, when his unofficial campaign motto
was ``It's the economy, stupid.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton was returning to the Wharton School of Business at the University of
Pennsylvania today to sum up improvements in almost all corners of the economy
since he gave a previous speech there in 1992.
</P>
<P>
	   Also today, the White House was announcing a national summit of economic
thinkers and decision-makers to be held at the White House on April 5.
</P>
<P>
	   The 1992 Wharton speech was a showcase for Clinton's ideas on what seemed
like a national malaise -- seemingly permanent deficits, stubborn rates of
unemployment and otherwise lackluster economic measures, even though the nation
was actually coming out of a recession that year.
</P>
<P>
	   These days, Clinton frequently tells audiences that voters took a chance on
him in 1992 with the hope that he would improve their pocketbooks, and Clinton
claims he has done just that for most of America.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He went to Wharton in 1992 to talk about his ideas for turning the economy
around, new ideas for economic stewardship in this country,'' White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Lockhart said that today's speech will recount the Clinton-Gore record ``and
also look to the future about what the proper role for government is in
providing stewardship for the economy, particularly in the areas of research and
science.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton regards the fields of science and technology as the most dynamic
economic arenas in America, and one that played a relatively small role in
national economic thinking eight years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
