<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 03:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clintons Owe $4.3M in Legal Fees  </HEADLINE>
   By PETE YOST Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clintons' legal defense fund might stay in business
after the president leaves office to help cover $4.3 million in outstanding
legal bills.
</P>
<P>
	   The fund's trustees held out the possibility of continuing their work next
year, while reporting that donations fell substantially in the last six months
of 1999 -- $800,000 compared with $2.4 million in the first part of the year.
</P>
<P>
	   Seventeen donors gave the $10,000 maximum, accounting for nearly a quarter
of the $800,000 in contributions.
</P>
<P>
	   Defense fund donations so far this year are $400,000, giving the trustees
some reason to believe the Clintons will not have to deal with the bills, said
Anthony Essaye, the fund's executive director.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We will continue to ask Americans to contribute to the Trust in the hopes
that the president and first lady can leave the White House ... largely free of
... debt,'' Essaye said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
	   Essaye said that if the Clintons still have substantial legal bills next
January, the trustees will have to decide whether the fund should stay in
business.
</P>
<P>
	   While saying at one point that ``in all probability it will not'' continue,
Essaye later in the news conference said that it ``might stay in business''
after next January if the debt remains substantial.
</P>
<P>
	   The Clintons' have run up $10.7 million in legal bills since the Whitewater
investigation began in 1993. Lawyers for the president and first lady have been
paid $5.9 million, with $500,000 more collected and on the way.
</P>
<P>
	   One person connected to the Monica Lewinsky scandal, major Democratic
contributor Walter Kaye, was among the latest $10,000 contributors. Kaye helped
place Ms. Lewinsky in the White House intern program. Also giving $10,000 each
were film executive Lew Wasserman and Miramax Films co-chairman Harvey
Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
	   Wasserman and Weinstein also gave the fund $10,000 apiece in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton has said he might be entitled to government reimbursement for his
legal expenses, but ``his instinct'' is not to seek it.
</P>
<P>
	   The Clintons' legal bills stem from various criminal investigations of their
activities, as well as the sexual harassment suit against the president by
former Arkansas state employee Paula Jones.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the Independent Counsel statute, subjects of criminal investigations
who are not indicted may seek reimbursement of reasonable attorneys fees from
the special panel of judges that appoints the prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
	   But the reimbursement question regarding Clinton is murky because he was
impeached by the House on perjury and obstruction charges, then acquitted by the
Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0348 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 03:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Santana Wins Record-Tying 8 Grammys  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVID GERMAIN AP Entertainment Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The comeback of Carlos Santana is triumphantly complete.
</P>
<P>
	   The guitar great who had just one minor Grammy to his credit in a 30-year
career won eight on Wednesday, tying the record set by Michael Jackson in 1983
for most trophies in one night. Santana's awards included the top honors, record
and album of the year.
</P>
<P>
	   Santana brought grace, humility and spirituality to a show full of glitz and
glamor. The 52-year-old musician known best for his breathtaking guitar work
said he set out to make "Supernatural" a radio-friendly record to spread a
message of hope.
</P>
<P>
	   "If I can do it, people from the ghettos, the barrio, the shantytowns can do
it," the Mexican-born Santana said. "I know, because I came from there."
</P>
<P>
	   Other top winners at the 42nd annual Grammys included the soul trio TLC, who
won two Grammys -- for best rhythm 'n' blues for their frank put-down of men,
"No Scrubs," and best R&AMP;B album for "Fanmail." "No Scrubs" was also named best
R&AMP;B song.
</P>
<P>
	   Eminem won two awards, for best rap solo performance and best rap album.
</P>
<P>
	   Country's leading ladies, the Dixie Chicks and Shania Twain, won two Grammys
apiece. George Jones, who had a near-fatal traffic wreck last year, won best
male country vocal for "Choices."
</P>
<P>
	   Tony Bennett, now 73 and enjoying his own commercial resurgence, took the
Grammy for traditional pop vocal for his tribute to Duke Ellington.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is my ninth Grammy, and boy, I just feel like going back in the
recording studio and coming up with another one," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Christina Aguilera staged a mild upset for best new performer over fellow
teen queen Britney Spears. Aguilera said she was so sure someone else would win
that she did not prepare a speech.
</P>
<P>
	   "I was expecting it to go to somebody actually who had more singles out this
year, so this is totally, totally unexpected," Aguilera said.
</P>
<P>
	   Sting scored his own upset for male pop vocal with "Brand New Day," beating
out younger, Latin-influenced singers Marc Anthony and Ricky Martin. Sting also
won for pop album.
</P>
<P>
	   Santana's wins were clearly no upsets. He was the favorite of the audience,
which gave him standing ovations and cheered each time his name was mentioned as
a nominee.
</P>
<P>
	   "This validates that together, we can heal this planet," he said. "There's
so much gossip and sensationalism, it's nice to demonstrate to people that
dignity and class can do as well."
</P>
<P>
	   Santana's triumph was reminiscent of the Grammys two years ago, when rock
veterans Bob Dylan and John Fogerty won top awards. Neither Dylan nor Fogerty,
leader of Creedence Clearwater Revival, had won Grammys in their prime years in
the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite continued critical acclaim for Santana, recent records have sold
modestly compared to multi-platinum 1970s albums as "Santana" and "Abraxas." A
deeply spiritual man who is a longtime devotee of Indian guru Sri Chinmoy,
Santana's first words upon winning album of the year were a Hebrew prayer, which
translates to: "Holy, holy, holy is the Lord of Hosts."
</P>
<P>
	   Santana's other honors included best rock album, pop collaboration with
vocals, rock instrumental and pop performance by a duo or group with vocals.
With nearly 6 million copies sold, "Supernatural" is the best-selling album for
Santana, whose career caught fire after Woodstock in 1969.
</P>
<P>
	   Much of the credit for the album's success goes to Santana's musical guests,
including fellow guitar veteran Eric Clapton and younger musicians such as
Lauryn Hill, Dave Matthews, Everlast, Wyclef Jean and Rob Thomas, who co-wrote
and sang on "Smooth," which won record of the year.
</P>
<P>
	   Thomas said the collaborations helped introduce Santana's music to younger
listeners.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's not that I think Carlos had a comeback," Thomas said. "He was just
opened up to a few more layers, more ages of people."
</P>
<P>
	   Santana heaped praise on his collaborators, thanking Everlast for "writing
that incredible spiritual song, 'Put Your Lights On,"' and Thomas for the
"wonderful lyrics and performance" on "Smooth."
</P>
<P>
	   The guitarist also honored producer Clive Davis, who released "Supernatural"
on his Arista label and first signed Santana to Columbia Records in the late
1960s. Santana took the stage side-by-side with Davis to accept the top album
Grammy.
</P>
<P>
	   Santana's success and staying power in the business are a lesson for
up-and-coming performers, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Anytime an artist breaks through, they wonder how long they can last," said
Davis, embroiled in a power struggle with Arista's owner, BMG. "This album shows
that if the music is great, not only will it last, but it can soar."
</P>
<P>
	   With "Supernatural" as his latest steppingstone, Santana said he hopes to
make good on such goals as playing in China and Cuba and performing for Nelson
Mandela and Desmond Tutu in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
	   And true to the success and eclectic lineup of "Supernatural," he said he
hopes to record with such musicians as Ry Cooder and Alice Coltrane, "but do it
in a way so you can still hear the song on the radio."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0357 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 03:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grammys Favor '70s Icons  </HEADLINE>
    By BETH HARRIS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- You're never too old to win your first Grammy. Just ask
'70s icons Cher, Barry White and Black Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
	   Youngsters like Britney Spears, Ricky Martin, Marc Anthony and the
Backstreet Boys -- who had some of 1999's best-selling albums -- will have to
wait another year to grab a Grammy.
</P>
<P>
	   Cher, 53, won best dance recording at Wednesday night's ceremonies for
"Believe," the biggest hit of a career that began in the 1960s with then-husband
Sonny Bono.
</P>
<P>
	   White, the soulful love god known for the '70s hit "Can't Get Enough of Your
Love, Babe," earned male rhythm and blues vocal and traditional R&AMP;B vocal
trophies for the appropriately titled "Staying Power."
</P>
<P>
	   White, 55, triumphed over such younger competition as R. Kelly, Maxwell and
Tyrese in the R&AMP;B vocal category.
</P>
<P>
	   Black Sabbath, formerly fronted by Ozzy Osborne and known for such metal
classics "Paranoid," was honored for best metal performance with "Iron Man."
Drummer Bill Ward said it was gratifying to see artists from the Woodstock
generation, including the night's top winner, Carlos Santana, doing so well.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it's totally cool," he said. "I didn't think that 31 years ago, I'd
be standing up in a suit. I feel more like an accountant than the guy who plays
drums in Black Sabbath."
</P>
<P>
	   Santana, the 52-year-old guitarist who shot to fame at Woodstock in 1969,
picked up eight Grammys, tying Michael Jackson's record for the most in one
night.
</P>
<P>
	   Clive Davis, who launched the careers of Santana, Whitney Houston, Sarah
McLachlan and Bruce Springsteen, lauded Santana for his cross-generational
impact.
</P>
<P>
	   "You're an inspiration to every young musician throughout the globe because
when they break in they don't know how long a career can not only last, but how
long it can soar," Davis said. "And to those established musicians who've been
No. 1, how to get back after years."
</P>
<P>
	   Country veterans George Jones and June Carter Cash, whose health travails
have received almost as much ink as their music in recent years, received their
first Grammys since 1970.
</P>
<P>
	   Jones, the 68-year-old who was nearly killed in a car wreck last year, won
male country vocal for "Choices."
</P>
<P>
	   Cash, the 70-year-old wife of Johnny Cash, picked up her third career Grammy
for "Press On" in the traditional folk album category.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, Spears, Latin heartthrobs Martin and Anthony, R&AMP;B singer Brandy,
all-boy groups Backstreet Boys and 'N Sync and rapper Kid Rock were allo shut
out.
</P>
<P>
	   But there was Christina Aguilera, the 19-year-old singer who earned her
first Grammy, for best new artist. She defeated fellow teen diva Spears, who
commanded greater attention for her sales and sex appeal.
</P>
<P>
	   Aguilera said she hoped to follow in the footsteps of her idol, Mariah
Carey, who won best new artist in 1990. Carey sings, writes and produces much of
her own material.
</P>
<P>
	   "I want more writing credibility on the next album," Aguilera said. "It's
really wanting to be seen as a vocalist, because that's where my heart is and
trying to take pop a little bit deeper than it is now. I wish it wasn't just
about image."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0359 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 04:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grammys Notebook  </HEADLINE>
    By CYNTHIA L. WEBB Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Sure, Erykah Badu can sing, but she also made her mark
with a sleek outfit and her signature -- and symbolic -- headwrap.
</P>
<P>
	   In a performance with jazz musicians George Benson and Diana Krall at
Wednesday night's Grammys, she wore a yellow turban-like hat, a kelly green
shirt, striped skirt and red pumps.
</P>
<P>
	   "The headwrap is political," said the singer, who turns 29 on Saturday.
"This headwrap is a symbol for every group of people who has their own set of
rules.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's beautiful and I enjoy wearing it and I enjoy people complimenting me
(on it)," she said, saying it's an "ego thing" and represents "strength."
</P>
<P>
	   She and The Roots won a Grammy for their hit "You Got Me."
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Erykah Badu wasn't the only one with a striking wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
	   Actress and singer Jennifer Lopez, appearing onstage with "X-Files" star
David Duchovny to announce the award for best R&AMP;B album, sported a dress that
left virtually nothing to the imagination.
</P>
<P>
	   The long sleeve, green-and-blue dress had two wide V's in the front: one
plunging down to her midriff and one coming up with a sequined pin holding it
together below her waist.
</P>
<P>
	   The ensemble prompted emcee Rosie O'Donnell to joke after a commercial
break: "You know, it's always great to see Jennifer Lopez in a classy
understated number like that. She wonders why people make fun of her body."
</P>
<P>
	   O'Donnell also got in a gibe at Sean "Puffy" Combs, Lopez's boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
	   "Good news everyone, Puff Daddy has left the building," she announced at one
point. "He was in the front row and it's a comfort to me, trust me."
</P>
<P>
	   The rapper faces gun possession and bribery charges following a Dec. 27
shooting at a New York nightclub that wounded three people. He has said he is
innocent.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   The biggest standing ovation of the night didn't go to big winner Carlos
Santana -- it went to five young musicians.
</P>
<P>
	   Michael Greene, president of the National Academy of Recording Arts and
Sciences, said he searched for two years to get the right group of kids together
and, in the end, had to choose from "thousands of tapes."
</P>
<P>
	   "I wasn't necessarily looking for the flashiest kids," Greene said. "The
kids were really heartfelt and super musicians."
</P>
<P>
	   The winners: Matthew Brewer, 16, a bass player from Rio Rancho, N.M.; Rachel
Lee, 11, of Scarsdale, N.Y., a classical violinist; Eldar Djangirov, 13, a jazz
pianist originally from Kyrgyzstan and now living in Kansas City, Mo; Tony
Royster, Jr., 15, of Hiensville, Ga., on drums; and Julian Lage, 12, a guitarist
from Santa Rosa, Calif.
</P>
<P>
	   The group practiced together for two days, performing the Thelonious Monk
piece "Straight, No Chaser."
</P>
<P>
	   The group had some tips for young aspiring artists.
</P>
<P>
	   "Just try to keep learning," Lage said. "Try different stuff and don't limit
yourself to anything."
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   The Grammys returned to an arena setting for only the second time in the
show's 42-year history. The 20,000-seat Staples Center in downtown Los Angeles
has nearly four times the capacity of the Shrine Auditorium, where last year's
show was held.
</P>
<P>
	   The move allowed the 14,000-member National Academy of Recording Arts &AMP;
Sciences to invite more industry representatives.
</P>
<P>
	   Diana Krall, whose "When I Look in Your Eyes" won for jazz vocal
performance, said intimacy wasn't lost in the larger setting.
</P>
<P>
	   "I liked it, especially when you look down and see Tony Bennett in the front
row. That's nice," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Tito Puente, a Latin band leader for 50 years with 118 albums to his credit,
says he has another accomplishment: role model.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm very honored to be here and I hope I continue to be a role model to all
the young Latin people coming up in this profession," Puente said backstage.
</P>
<P>
	   Puente's fifth Grammy was for best traditional tropical Latin performance
for "Mambo Birdland."
</P>
<P>
	   He said the explosion of Latin music chart-toppers has helped bolster his
own career, which has seen 10 Grammy nominations.
</P>
<P>
	   "Well, it doesn't hurt, but I'm not Ricky Martin, I'm not Marc Anthony --
I'm sure not Jennifer Lopez," said Puente, wiggling his behind in an apparent
reference to the actress and her much-hyped derriere.
</P>
<P>
	   Puente also introduced his son backstage, Tito Puente Jr., who has a music
career of his own. His style is different from his dad's classic tunes -- he
plays house music.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Blues guitar master B. B. King, his ninth Grammy in hand, said he has
already made plans for a posthumous career.
</P>
<P>
	   "I've had some friends encourage me to retire and they ask me when I would
and my answer is five to 10 years after I am dead," said the 74-year-old
musician.
</P>
<P>
	   King got his first Grammy in 1970. On Wednesday, he won for best traditional
blues album for "Blues on the Bayou." He is working on an album with Eric
Clapton.
</P>
<P>
	   "What can I tell you -- I just wish I could do more," King said.
</P>
<P>
	   Another nine-time winner, 73-year-old singer Tony Bennett, says he has no
plans to stop singing.
</P>
<P>
	   "I love what I'm doing ... it's such an adventure," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bennett won for best traditional pop vocal performance for his "Bennett
Sings Ellington -- Hot &AMP; Cool."
</P>
<P>
	   He wouldn't reveal what project he's working on next, saying he thinks it
"would be lifted by someone else."
</P>
</TEXT>
