<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 04:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clintons Host Lavish State Dinner  </HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN GALVIN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- It began with a stumbling queen but ended in a song. In
between, President Clinton toasted the king of Spain for defending democracy,
and Washington power-brokers mingled with Hollywood stars at the first state
dinner of the year.
</P>
<P>
	   The lavish affair for 170 guests, which featured a performance by tenor
Placido Domingo, was the highlight of Hillary Rodham Clinton's first return to a
public schedule in the White House since launching her Senate political campaign
in New York on Feb. 6.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Mrs. Clinton has always taken an active role in the planning for state
dinners, and despite her busy schedule in New York she was able to be involved
in all aspects of the usual preparations for the Spain dinner,'' spokeswoman
Toby Graff said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Clintons greeted King Juan Carlos and Queen Sofia on the South Lawn of
the White House on Wednesday morning in an official ceremony punctuated by
reminders of the threat terrorism poses to freedom.
</P>
<P>
	   The king condemned a car bombing Tuesday that killed two people in the
Basque capital of Vitoria, accusing Basque separatists blamed for the attack of
trying to ``impose their totalitarian ideas by force'' at the expense of human
life.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton praised Juan Carlos for his ``stand against the forces of terror and
the enemies of freedom,'' particularly for his stand against an armed militia
that stormed the Spanish parliament in a coup attempt on Feb. 23, 1981.
</P>
<P>
	   The president expressed his condolences to the families of the bombing
victims and said that ``in a democracy we must settle our differences with
dialogue, not destruction.''
</P>
<P>
	   Wednesday's evening's state dinner began on a slightly awkward note when the
queen stumbled in her long black and gray gown as she scaled the North Portico
steps to meet the Clintons. She reached out with her hands to save herself from
a bad fall, and the president reached down and grabbed her shoulders to help her
recover.
</P>
<P>
	   Guests were seated around 17 tables in the State Dining Room and the Red
Room that were bedecked with white orchids, Virginia roses and slender tapers in
golden candelabras.
</P>
<P>
	   Among those attending were actors Dennis Quaid and Meg Ryan, Diane Keaton
and Whoopie Goldberg, several lawmakers and Cabinet officials and Vice President
Al Gore's daughter Karenna Gore Schiff, who studied in Spain, and her husband,
Dr. Andrew Schiff.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the rigors of campaigning, Mrs. Clinton was at the White House to
choose the place settings and set the menu, which included for dessert a topiary
of white chocolate styled like a crate filled with sherbet oranges, lemons and
limes.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Clinton chose the Eisenhower china, white with wide rims of gold, to
accompany champagne-colored brocade tablecloths. The menu featured the sort of
full-flavored dishes best appreciated on a chilly night: lobster and Maine
shrimp served with risotto and chorizo; grilled rack of lamb with blood orange
and rosemary sauce.
</P>
<P>
	   The wine served with the main course was a robust pinot noir from the Artesa
vineyard near Santa Barbara, Calif.; with dessert the royals were treated to a
Gloria Ferrer Royal Cuvee brut, which was developed in honor of their visit to
California's Napa Valley in 1983.
</P>
<P>
	   The evening was topped off with five songs from zarzuelas to Leonard
Berstein's ``Tonight,'' sung by Domingo, who won a Grammy on Wednesday while he
waited to perform in the East Room, and soprano Ana Maria Martinez.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 0442 </TRAILER>
