<HEADLINE> Dow Down 90.52; Nasdaq Up 53.84  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in early trading today, with the
technology-dominated Nasdaq composite index extending its move into record
territory. Blue chips continued their decline.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first hour of trading, the Nasdaq was up 53.84 at 4,604.17 after
rising more than 168 points Wednesday to 4,550.33, a new closing high.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 90.52 today at 10,135.21, adding
to Wednesday's 79-point drop. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 4.85 at
1,355.84.
</P>
<P>
	   Technology stocks, which have become largely immune to concerns about rising
interest rates, once again rallied at the expense of old-line blue chip stocks,
including retailers and banks. Investors are increasingly more attracted by the
younger high-tech firms' promise of higher profit gains.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a narrow margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 147.6 million shares, up from Wednesday's
pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index rose 5.06 to 554.97.
</P>
<P>
	   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.3 percent. In afternoon
trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.5 percent, Britain's Financial Times-Stock
Exchange 100 was up 0.2 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 1.7 percent.
</P>
