<DOCNO> APW20000224.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Off 214.93; Nasdaq Off 50.70  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chip stocks were plummeting today, pushing the Dow
industrial average briefly below 10,000, a drop of almost 15 percent from the
record set last month. The technology-dominated Nasdaq composite index also
shifted downward as investors took profits from Thursday's record-shattering
run.
</P>
<P>
	   At midmorning on Wall Street,The Dow Jones industrial average was down
214.93 at 10,010.80, adding to Wednesday's 79-point drop. The Dow had dropped as
low as 9,993.35 this morning.
</P>
<P>
	   The last time the Dow traded below 10,000 was Oct. 18, and its last close
below 10,000 was April 6, 1999, when it stood at 9,963.49. It reached a record
11,722.98 on Jan. 14.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nasdaq was down 50.70 at 4,499.63 after rising a record 168.21 points
Wednesday to 4,550.33, a new closing high.
</P>
<P>
	   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 25.33 at 1,3355.36.
</P>
<P>
	   Fears of higher interest rates once again was blamed for undercutting
stocks.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is like 'Groundhog Day,' we know this story we've seen it almost every
day," said Arthur Hogan, chief market analyst at Jeffries &AMP; Co. He referred to
the movie where the main character keeps living Groundhog Day over and over
again.
</P>
<P>
	   In the past week, policy-makers from the Federal Reserve have sent clear
messages that they intend to raise rates to cool off inflationary pressures in
the robust U.S. economy. Such moves could hurt corporate profits and slow
consumer buying.
</P>
<P>
	   Technology stocks, which have become largely immune to concerns about rising
interest rates, have spent much of 2000 rallying at the expense of old-line blue
chip stocks, including retailers and banks. Investors are increasingly more
attracted by the younger high-tech firms' promise of higher profit gains.
</P>
<P>
	   Leading the Dow lower, was Wal-Mart, off 3 1/4 to 43 5/8, and Home Depot,
off 1 1/2 to 53 1/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a narrow margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 360.6 million shares, up from Wednesday's
pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index was down 1.27 to 548.54.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1133 </TRAILER>
