<DOCNO> APW20000224.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Justice Dept. Reviews Deutch Case  </HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department is reviewing former CIA Director
John Deutch's misuse of classified information on a home computer and how the
case was handled, Attorney General Janet Reno said today.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The department is looking at the whole matter, reviewing the whole matter
to see whether there is any basis for further action,'' Reno told her weekly
news conference. She said the goal is ``to determine whether there is any action
that the Department of Justice should take.''
</P>
<P>
	   Deutch has apologized to a Senate committee for moving classified data to an
unprotected computer in his home that was occasionally connected to the
Internet. Now a private consultant, he was stripped of his CIA security
clearances as a result. The CIA inspector general also criticized top CIA
officials for not quickly referring the incident to the Justice Department for
possible criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
	   Last spring after a yearlong review of the 1996 episode, the Justice
Department's criminal division declined to prosecute Deutch for mishandling
classified information. The division found the lapses were sloppy rather than
nefarious and referred the case to the CIA inspector general for administrative
discipline.
</P>
<P>
	   Reno and her aides declined today to specify what questions were being
reviewed. They said only that the entire matter was under scrutiny when asked
whether the Deutch criminal investigation could be reopened or whether there was
any obstruction of justice of top CIA officials.
</P>
<P>
	   One Justice official, requesting anonymity, said two criminal division
lawyers are handling the review. The review is more comprehensive than the one
the Justice Department announced three weeks ago, this official said. At that
time, Justice lawyers were said to be taking a look at the CIA inspector
general's report, but, based on information then available, there were no plans
to reopen the Deutch investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   Justice officials also said earlier this month that material in the
inspector general's report and emerging from congressional hearings into the
Deutch episode was already known to the criminal division when it declined to
prosecute last year.
</P>
<P>
	   Meantime, Senate Intelligence Committee chairman Richard Shelby, R-Ala., is
determined to proceed with his inquiry despite public and private apologies from
Deutch.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There is no excuse for this kind of behavior,'' Sen. Richard Shelby said
this week after Deutch appeared before his panel.
</P>
<P>
	   In his first public comments on his computer practices, Deutch told
reporters after Tuesday's closed-door session he erred in doing classified work
on unsecured home computers connected to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
	   Shelby said his panel will recall Deutch and wants to hear from present
senior CIA officials, including Director George Tenet, on why it took so long to
strip Deutch of his security clearances or to notify the Justice Department and
Congress that an investigation was under way.
</P>
<P>
	   Deutch left the CIA in December 1996. Tenet had his predecessor's security
clearances removed last August. Deutch, a former deputy defense secretary, also
held onto a Pentagon security clearance but gave it up this month.
</P>
<P>
	   The CIA inspector general's report says Tenet ``should have involved himself
more forcefully to ensure a proper resolution of the matter.''
</P>
<P>
	   In a statement, CIA spokesman Bill Harlow said Tenet considers Deutch's
mishandling of classified information ``inexcusable.'' The inspector general's
report ``paints a picture of individuals struggling with the challenge of
conducting a sensitive security investigation of the agency's former director.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``We could have and should have done better,'' Harlow added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1138 </TRAILER>
