<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 12:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NTSB Recommends Changes to Boats  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID A. LIEB Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The National Transportation Safety Board
recommended today that backup floation devices be installed in amphibious boats
to prevent the kind of rapid flooding that sank a tourist boat last year.
</P>
<P>
	   The Miss Majestic, a type of boat called a ``duck'' because it travels on
both land and water, plunged to the bottom of Lake Hamilton in a matter of
minutes May 1 after taking on water. Thirteen passengers drowned.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. Coast Guard in December concluded that a dislodged drive-shaft seal
allowed water to flood the hull. The boat's bilge pump failed to work.
</P>
<P>
	   The NTSB said boat operators should not rely on the pumps only, recommending
the installation of backup flotation devices -- watertight bulkheads, buoyant
materials inside the hull or flotation attachments on the outside of the boat.
</P>
<P>
	   Amphibious boats sink easily because they have no backup flotation, NTSB
Chairman Jim Hall said in a letter asking the industry to respond to the
recommendations within 90 days.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Consequently, the safety board concludes that the potential exists for
another life-threatening accident similar to the sinking of the Miss Majestic,
unless the vulnerability to flooding and sinking is addressed,'' the letter
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The boat that sank in Arkansas was a vintage World War II vessel designed
for military purposes, then converted to take tourists through the Hot Springs
area.
</P>
<P>
	   Nationwide, more than 250 amphibious passenger boats are in service. Most
are ducks and the rest are similar models.
</P>
<P>
	   At least 18 amphibious boats had accidents -- six involving some degree of
flooding -- between March 6, 1991, and May 1, 1999, according to Coast Guard
data. None was fatal.
</P>
<P>
	   The safety board said it has learned of at least nine other incidents
involving significant flooding that were not reported to the Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
	   Amphibious boats have several flooding threats. The safety board said water
can leak in through a failed hull fitting, missing plug or a hull that is
cracked by running aground. Also, the road travel and repeated entry and exit
from water can wear on the vessel's hull and loosen mechanical joints and
connections.
</P>
<P>
	   Because the boats have open interiors and a low amount of space between the
stern and the water, it doesn't take long for the boats to flood and sink, the
NTSB said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1212 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Targets Russian Aid to Iran  </HEADLINE>
   By JIM ABRAMS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate today unanimously passed a bill that singles
out Russia for possible sanctions if it supplies Iran with weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
	   Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota said senators want to
send ``as strong a message'' as possible about the transfer of dangerous weapons
and materials. The vote was 98-0.
</P>
<P>
	   The House passed a very similar bill last September by 419-0, and is
expected to quickly adapt the Senate version and send it on to the president.
The White House last year threatened to veto the House bill, saying it would
weaken the U.S. ability to persuade the international community to halt weapons
transfers to Iran.
</P>
<P>
	   But Democratic leaders said the administration, while still opposed, is now
satisfied the bill would give the president enough flexibility to deal with
different circumstances, and would not recommend a veto.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the legislation, the president would be required to submit reports to
Congress every six months to identify countries such as Russia, China and North
Korea providing Iran with materiel to promote its missile and weapons systems.
</P>
<P>
	   The president would have the option of cutting off arms sales or economic
aid to nations helping Iran's weapons programs. He could waive sanctions for
national security reasons.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill also would bar the United States from making payments to the
Russian space agency for helping build the International Space Station until the
president determines that Russia is actively opposing proliferation in Iran.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton vetoed legislation in 1998 that, unlike the current bill, would have
required sanctions against those helping Iran build missiles.
</P>
<P>
	   Heading off a possible veto override, Vice President Al Gore shortly
thereafter announced sanctions on seven Russian entities suspected of
transferring weapons technology to Iran. In 1999 three more Russian groups were
added to the list.
</P>
<P>
	   Legislators said the administrative action, while needed, did not go far
enough and that the growing influence of reformists in Iran's government did not
obviate the threat posed by Iran's weapons program.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The danger is still there, and those who are in charge of nuclear
proliferation in Iran have a very strong grip on what's being done,'' said
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill ``sends a message to our friends in Russia about the intensity of
our concern about their part in helping Iran develop weapons of mass
destruction,'' said Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., a chief sponsor.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   The bill is H.R. 1883.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1226 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 166.39; Nasdaq Up 7.68  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chip stocks were tumbling today, pushing the Dow
industrial average briefly below 10,000, a drop of almost 15 percent from the
record set last month. Meanwhile, the technology-dominated Nasdaq composite
index shook off early losses and added to its gains from Wednesday's
record-shattering run.
</P>
<P>
	   At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 166.39 at
10,059.43, adding to Wednesday's 79-point drop. The Dow had dropped as low as
9,993.35 this morning.
</P>
<P>
	   The last time the Dow traded below 10,000 was Oct. 18, and its last close
below 10,000 was April 6, 1999, when it stood at 9,963.49. It reached a record
11,722.98 on Jan. 14.
</P>
<P>
	   "No one should underestimate the psychology of moving below 10,000," said
Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer at First Albany Corp. "When the Dow
dropping moves from the business page to the front page it will scare some
investors ... and could lead to more selling."
</P>
<P>
	   The Nasdaq was up 7.68 at 4,554.62 after rising a record 168.21 points
Wednesday to 4,550.33, a new closing high. The Nasdaq had been down about 50
points earlier in the session due to profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
	   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 18.94 at 1,340.75.
</P>
<P>
	   Fears of higher interest rates once again were blamed for undercutting
stocks.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is like 'Groundhog Day.' We know this story. We've seen it almost
every day," said Arthur Hogan, chief market analyst at Jeffries &AMP; Co. He
referred to the movie where the main character keeps living Groundhog Day over
and over again.
</P>
<P>
	   In the past week, policy-makers from the Federal Reserve have sent clear
messages that they intend to raise rates to cool off inflationary pressures in
the robust U.S. economy. Such moves could hurt corporate profits and slow
consumer buying.
</P>
<P>
	   Technology stocks, which have become largely immune to concerns about rising
interest rates, have spent much of 2000 rallying at the expense of old-line blue
chip stocks, including retailers and banks. Investors are increasingly more
attracted by the younger high-tech firms' promise of higher profit gains.
</P>
<P>
	   Leading the Dow lower, was Wal-Mart, off 2 1/4 to 44 3/4, and Johnson &AMP;
Johnson, off 3 1/2 to 72 3/4.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 2 to 1 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 525.8 million shares at midday, up from
Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index was down 0.46 to 549.45.
</P>
</TEXT>
