<DOCNO> APW20000224.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Confirms 2 Federal Judges  </HEADLINE>
   By JANELLE CARTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate confirmed two federal judges today, the latest
effort in ending a Republican block on all Clinton administration nominations.
</P>
<P>
	   By a 98-0 vote the Senate confirmed George B. Daniels as a district judge
for Southern New York and Kermit Bye as a judge of the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals.
</P>
<P>
	   It was only the second time in as many weeks that Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss., has allowed action on judicial nominations. Two other
nominations were confirmed earlier this month. At that time, Lott said the
Senate should not go all year without confirming any nominations, saying, ``Some
of these are good men and women.''
</P>
<P>
	   The nominations had been delayed because of a standoff between the Clinton
administration and Senate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans accused President Clinton of violating an agreement on making
temporary recess appointments, a method of bypassing the Senate confirmation
process.
</P>
<P>
	   To show their disapproval, Republicans put ``holds'' on all judicial
nominees. Under Senate tradition, a single senator can block further floor
action on a nominee as long as the majority leader agrees.
</P>
<P>
	   Democrats have accused Republicans of playing politics by blocking worthy
judicial nominations. They also complained that nearly 10 percent of all federal
judgeships are vacant.
</P>
<P>
	   Bye, 62, a Fargo, N.D. lawyer, was nominated last April to fill a seat on
the 8th Circuit left vacant by the death of his friend and former law partner,
John D. Kelly. Kelly died last year a few days before his formal swearing-in
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
	   Daniels is a state Supreme Court justice from New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
