<HEADLINE> Judge Halts Strike at Union Pacific  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- A federal judge issued a temporary restraining order
Thursday on a union strike at Union Pacific Railroad just hours after it hit
selected points across the Midwest and West.
</P>
<P>
	   The railroad argued the strike over the closing of a facility in Wyoming was
illegal. Arguments were set for Monday in U.S. District Court in Omaha.
</P>
<P>
	   The strike by the Brotherhood of Maintenance of Way began at 6 a.m., Union
Pacific spokesman Mark Davis said. Omaha District Judge Joseph Bataillon signed
the restraining order four hours later.
</P>
<P>
	   "Within the next few hours operations will return to normal with minimum
train delays across the area," Davis said.
</P>
<P>
	   The shop in Laramie, Wyo., employs 37 people and makes 40-foot section of
track for construction and repairs, Davis said. Union Pacific wants to close the
shop to buy such track from another source and save overhead on the plant.
</P>
<P>
	   Workers at the shop would have the opportunity to find work at the railroad,
Davis said, but not in Laramie.
</P>
<P>
	   Union spokesman Dave Tanner said the railroad acted unilaterally to close
the shop and threatened the workers' livelihood.
</P>
<P>
	   The strike was at locations along original Union Pacific rail lines,
including all sites in Nebraska, most track in Kansas and some locations in
Colorado, Wyoming, Utah, Idaho, north into the Pacific Northwest and southwest
to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
	   About 4,080 people belong to the union across the railroad's system. Davis
said he did not know how many employees were directly affected by the strike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
