</P>
<P>
	   Durable Goods Orders Fall in Jan.
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Slackening demand for airplanes and
electronics caused orders for big-ticket goods to dip last month,
but the fall isn't a big setback for U.S. manufacturers, which
continue to possess a lot of momentum, economists said. Orders to
U.S. factories for durable goods -- items expected to last at least
three years -- slipped 1.3 percent in January to a seasonally
adjusted $214.8 billion, the Commerce Department said today. Even
with the decline, overall durable-goods orders last month were
still 6.5 percent higher than January 1999. ``The real story is
that American manufacturing interests are sustaining the momentum
of a freight train going full bore,'' said KeyCorp economist Ken
Mayland.
</P>
<P>
	   Jobless Claims Fall by 7,000
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- New claims for unemployment insurance fell by
7,000 to 278,000, according to figures announced this morning by
the Labor Department.
</P>
<P>
	   Gulf Nations OK Oil Production Hike
</P>
<P>
	   DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Gulf oil ministers have
agreed to increase production to stabilize international markets --
where the price of oil is near an nine-year high. They will meet
next month with other OPEC members to agree on a new production
goal. Officials indicated today that most ministers at a meeting
Wednesday in Saudi Arabia agreed to increase production, but have
not agreed on how much. A senior United Arab Emirates oil official
said a production increase will be gradual and will be in the range
of 1.5 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
	   Judge Halts Strike at Union Pacific
</P>
<P>
	   OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- A federal judge issued a temporary
restraining order today on a union strike at Union Pacific Railroad
just hours after it hit selected points across the Midwest and
West. The railroad argued the strike over the closing of a facility
in Wyoming was illegal. Arguments were set for Monday in U.S.
District Court in Omaha.
</P>
<P>
	   Softbank Set To Buy Failed Bank
</P>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese Internet powerhouse Softbank Corp. is
adding the banking business to a global portfolio that includes
investments in companies such as Yahoo! Inc., and joint ventures
with the Nasdaq Stock Market to set up computerized stock markets
in Asia and Europe. In its biggest deal yet, Softbank is leading a
consortium that today received exclusive negotiation rights to
purchase the failed, now government-controlled Nippon Credit Bank.
Analysts say the purchase is a plus for Softbank's
Internet-centered strategy. Both Internet use and electronic
commerce, such as online stock trading, are expected to grow
rapidly in Japan.
</P>
<P>
	   Dutch Publisher Plans Web Strategy
</P>
<P>
	   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- Anglo-Dutch publishing giant Reed
Elsevier announced a plan today to invest $1.2 billion to bring its
traditional operations online and boost earnings growth. The
company also reported today that pretax profit fell 8.2 percent
last year. Elsevier said it will pump $400 million into online
activities each year over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
	   Gap Beats 4Q Earnings Expectations
</P>
<P>
	   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Fourth-quarter earnings at Gap Inc. beat
expectations, helped by the retail company's rapid expansion.
</P>
<P>
	   For the three months ended Jan. 29, 2000, the company said
Thursday that its earnings were up 32 percent to $414 million, or
47 cents per share, from $314 million or 35 cents a share during
the same period last year. Analysts had predicted fourth-quarter
earnings of 45 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
	   Sweden Rejects Saab's Recall Appeal
</P>
<P>
	   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- The government today rejected an appeal
by Saab Automobile against a five-year-old order to recall more
than 50,000 cars in Sweden but a final decision was still months
away. The government's ruling comes five years after the luxury
automaker first appealed an order to recall cars manufactured from
1989-1991 in the 900i and 9000i series. the recall was ordered
after National Protection Agency tests showed the cars exceeded
Sweden's exhaust limits by more than 100 percent because of failing
carbon canisters.
</P>
<P>
	   Telecom Co. Expands in New Zealand
</P>
<P>
	   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) -- Australian telecommunications
company Telstra Corp. said today it would merge its New Zealand
operations with a local telecommunications company, Saturn
Communications, in a deal that will expand its reach in New
Zealand. The move poses the biggest threat yet to New Zealand's
Telecom Corp. since the government sold it a decade ago. It came
just one day after the government unveiled a regulatory review of
the telecommunications market, amid ongoing claims of
anticompetitive behavior by market-dominant Telecom.
</P>
<P>
	   Greece To Apply for Euro Currency
</P>
<P>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Greece will submit its official
application to join European economic and monetary union on March
9, Finance Minister Yannos Papantoniou said today. The application
will come one month before early elections, set for April 9. Greece
was the only nation that wanted to enter the single currency bloc
but failed to meet the fiscal standards. Entry into the euro, EU's
single currency group, has been the cornerstone of Socialist
Premier Costas Simitis' policies. Tight fiscal policies have
brought inflation below 3 percent and tackled the debt that once
crippled the EU's poorest nation. Now, EU leaders have signaled
that Greece will likely be accepted into the euro zone.
</P>
<P>
	   Survey: Japan Shoppers Use Internet
</P>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan may have been slow to go online, but the
nation's shoppers have quickly taken to the convenience of
e-commerce, a survey published today showed. In a November survey
of Japanese Internet users by a Tokyo-based market research
company, 1,476 of 2,645 respondents, or 56 percent, said they made
at least one purchase on line in the last 12 months. That was up
from 38 percent in February 1999 and 25 percent in February 1997,
InfoCom Research Inc. said. Around 40 percent of the e-shoppers in
the November 1999 survey said they made four or more purchases, and
30 percent spent at least $450.
</P>
