<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clemency Reform Bill Passed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Concerned about the process used to offer clemency to 16
Puerto Rican nationalists, a Senate committee approved a bill Thursday that
gives victims more input.
</P>
<P>
	   The Judiciary Committee passed the Pardon Attorney Reform and Integrity Act
by a voice vote. A companion measure sponsored by Rep. Vito Fosella, R-N.Y., is
pending in the House.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Its aims are simple: To make sure future presidents will have available to
them relevant facts when weighing decisions involving executive clemency, and to
notify victims of important events in the process,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch,
R-Utah, the committee's chairman.
</P>
<P>
	   The measure requires the U.S. Pardon Attorney to solicit input from crime
victims and to keep them apprised of key events in the clemency process. It
would also mandate that law enforcement agencies be notified when a clemency
procedure was initiated and would seek their input as well.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill does not affect the president's ability to exercise pardon power,
Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think future presidents will appreciate the reforms this bill will bring
... and so will victims and the American public in general,'' Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
	   The legislation grew out of a controversy last August when President Clinton
offered clemency to 16 Puerto Rican separatists affiliated with the FALN, or
Armed Forces of National Liberation, the group held responsible for a wave of
bombings in the late 1970s and early 1980s. Fourteen accepted the offer, which
was conditioned on the prisoners renouncing violence.
</P>
<P>
	   Victims of the bombings complained they were left out of the clemency
process even as advocates of the Puerto Rican prisoners attended meetings with
high-level administration officials.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   EDITORS -- The bills are S. 2042 and H.R. 3626.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1524 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
