<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.-E.U. Deal on Tax Breaks Urged  </HEADLINE>
   By CURT ANDERSON AP Tax Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seeking to avoid a new trade war with Europe, U.S.
corporations and members of Congress urged the Clinton administration Thursday
to negotiate a quick solution to a World Trade Organization decision that
outlaws billions of dollars in U.S. export tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
	   The United States has until Oct. 1 to comply with the WTO decision that its
Foreign Sales Corporation program is an illegal trade subsidy as claimed by the
European Union. After that date, the EU could retaliate with higher tariffs or
other trade sanctions.
</P>
<P>
	   Although Congress could change tax laws to comply, few people familiar with
the case believe there's enough time in an election year to accomplish such a
costly and delicate task on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is very difficult to do anything legislatively in a presidential
year,'' said Kimberly Pinter, corporate finance and tax director at the National
Association of Manufacturers. ``As soon as you engage 535 additional people, it
makes the issue much more complicated than it would be at the negotiated
level.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Foreign Sales Corporation program, created in 1984, allows about 6,000
U.S. companies including Boeing, General Motors, United Technologies and
Microsoft to reduce income taxes by 15 percent by creating export subsidiaries
in tax havens such as the Virgin Islands and Barbados. Its intent is to offset
an EU tax rebate given to its companies for goods sold overseas.
</P>
<P>
	   The Clinton administration estimates the value of the U.S. tax break at $4.1
billion in fiscal 2001; the Europeans peg the subsidy at $17.5 billion over five
years.
</P>
<P>
	   Even though the decision marks the biggest U.S. trade loss ever at the WTO,
no immediate impact is expected on U.S. companies or the economy. But if the
program were to disappear, company officials say the United States could lose a
competitive edge that would eventually result in higher prices, fewer jobs and
lower profits.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This decision drops a brick onto one end of the well-balanced scale that
has governed global trade for nearly two decades,'' said Ruth Harkin, head of
United Technologies' office in Washington. ``It gives European exporters a huge
leg up to enjoy large tax exemptions unavailable to U.S. and other companies.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Europeans, of course, take a different view. Pascal Lemy, the European
Commission's trade commissioner, said the Foreign Sales Corporation program
creates ``a major negative effect'' on international trade by unfairly assisting
in some $250 billion in U.S. exports.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We think that WTO members should be free to decide their own tax systems.
But each member must do so fairly and in line with the rules,'' Lemy said.
</P>
<P>
	   Like much of corporate America, key members of Congress urged President
Clinton to negotiate a settlement with the EU. Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa,
said the issue should be a top priority at the Group of Eight economic summit
meeting this June in Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
	   There were also concerns Thursday that the decision could undermine support
for the WTO in Congress. In remarks to a group of business leaders, Clinton said
``nobody agrees with the WTO all the time'' but that ``having a system of rules
is nonetheless profoundly important.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``What's the alternative?'' added Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.
``To go back to the bad old days of building walls and not having communication
and trading partnerships we have around the world? We need that framework.''
</P>
<P>
	   Top Clinton administration officials expressed disappointment and
disagreement with the WTO ruling, but said they would seek a ``constructive
solution'' with the EU within the trade body's decision. They noted that the
U.S. has won 23 of 25 WTO cases and is involved with the EU in disputes
involving bananas, beef growth hormones and aerospace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1534 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
