<HEADLINE> HSoybeans Rebound; Grains Follow  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean prices rebounded Thursday after a big selloff the
previous day on the Chicago Board of Trade, pulling grains higher with them.
</P>
<P>
	   Soybeans initially headed lower for a second straight day, falling further
beneath the $5-a-bushel level. But they wound up 1 percent higher, helped back
up by rumors China was buying U.S. and South American soybeans
</P>
<P>
	   The steep dive in the U.S. stock market also likely contributed to the
strong day for soybeans and grains, traders said.
</P>
<P>
	   Corn prices also climbed in a technical correction from Wednesday's decline.
South Korea's first purchase of U.S. wheat in weeks underpinned the mild rally.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat was little changed, finishing on an upswing in response to the rally
in soybeans. Prices were pressured by forecasts indicating that rains may
continue in central growing regions into March.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat for March delivery was unchanged at $2.54 3/4 a bushel; March corn
rose 1 cent to $2.16 1/4 a bushel; May oats rose 1 1/4 cent to $1.09 a bushel;
March soybeans rose 4 3/4 cents to $5.04 1/2 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
	   Beef and pork futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   April live cattle rose .62 cent to 70.97 cents a pound; March feeder cattle
rose .32 cent to 82.92 cents a pound; April lean hogs rose .85 cent to 57.05
cents a pound; March pork bellies rose .95 cent to 88.95 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
