<HEADLINE> Spanish King Reminds US of Its Roots  </HEADLINE>
   By PAULINE JELINEK Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- King Juan Carlos of Spain used the launching of an
Internet history project Thursday to say America doesn't appreciate its Hispanic
roots.
</P>
<P>
	   But the ``ever-growing'' U.S. Hispanic community, he said, will one day make
sure it does.
</P>
<P>
	   With the click of a mouse, the king kicked off a bilingual project by the
National Library of Spain and U.S. Library of Congress to share historic
materials on the settling of America.
</P>
<P>
	   And with a quote from President John Kennedy, he said Spain's contribution
to that effort is sometimes forgotten.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Unfortunately, too many Americans think that America was discovered in
1620, when the pilgrims came,'' the king said, speaking in Spanish quoting a
1961 Kennedy speech -- ``and they forget the immense adventure of the 16th
century ... in the South and Southwestern part of the United States'' -- once
part of the old Spanish Empire.
</P>
<P>
	   Speaking at the Library of Congress on the last day of his and Queen Sofia's
three-day visit to the U.S., the king said he hoped the project would bring
about ``a new awareness of Spain's historic role in creating and forming the
personality of the American nation.''
</P>
<P>
	   The agreement calls for the two institutions to create a ``virtual
electronic library'' of rare material on history and culture of both countries.
A site on the World Wide Web will include digital copies of books, manuscripts,
maps and other materials.
</P>
<P>
	   The king posted the first item on the as yet unfinished site, a copy of a
1562 map of the Western Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
	   The first permanent settlement in what is now U.S. territory was St.
Augustine, Fla., founded in 1565 by Spaniard Pedro Menendez de Aviles.
</P>
<P>
	   The king said the growing Hispanic community in the United States ``will
ensure that the enormous colonizing task undertaken by its ancestors ... is
given due recognition by fellow Americans.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Eds: The World Wide Web site is
www.loc.gov/rr/hispanic/frontier/splash.html.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1542 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0166 </DOCNO>
