<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Train With Pets Ready To Roll  </HEADLINE>
   By CLAR NI CHONGHAILE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PARIS (AP) -- Continental cats and dogs can at last look forward to taking
the train to chase pigeons in London's Trafalgar Square, without that blissful
image being tarnished by the thought of six lonely months in a quarantine
kennel.
</P>
<P>
	   For a modest $46, they can now travel with their owners on the Eurotunnel
train under the English Channel, thanks to the British government's lifting of
its stringent 100-year-old quarantine laws last year. The move allows pets --
cats and dogs only -- from 21 Western Europe nations to enter Britain without
spending six months in quarantine.
</P>
<P>
	   The first train carrying four-legged tourists will leave Calais, in northern
France, on Monday morning, Eurotunnel said in a statement on Thursday. The trip,
which costs human passengers $330 to $550 per car, lasts 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's the easiest way to travel with pets because you don't have to leave
them alone, and have them freak out on sea for example,'' said Eurotunnel
spokesman Jeremy Close.
</P>
<P>
	   ``An awful lot of people have reserved. It makes sense because a lot of
British people have second homes in France or want to come back with their
animals,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
	   The rule change is also a relief for British dogs, who will no longer have
to spend long summer months in France dreading quarantine exile on their return
home.
</P>
<P>
	   But free-spirited continental pets hoping for a last-minute weekend break,
beware! The trip requires preparation.
</P>
<P>
	   Dogs and cats, like other travelers, need their own special passports -- but
theirs are signed and stamped by a veterinarian.
</P>
<P>
	   To get the passport, they must have a chip implanted to verify their
identity and must have had both a rabies vaccination and blood tests a month
afterward to prove it worked. They also must have been treated for ticks and
tapeworm 24 to 48 hours before arrival.
</P>
<P>
	   Britain's Passports for Pets plan was announced last March, and officials
believe that when fully operational 300,000 pets could be on the move each year.
The program is likely to be extended to the United States, Canada and the
Caribbean in 2001.
</P>
<P>
	   But dogs and cats taking the train will have to be on their best behavior.
</P>
<P>
	   There will be no gamboling around the train, looking for other pioneer pet
travelers. The animals must remain in their owners' vehicles during the journey.
Small dogs and cats will be confined to cages. Dogs must travel with a collar
and leash. Toilets will be provided.
</P>
<P>
	   And for pet lovers worried about how their animals will react to high-speed
travel, Eurotunnel offers advice on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
	   It recommends against tranquilizers because of the unpredictable nature of a
pet's reaction. And for a perfect journey, it suggests feeding pets a light meal
two hours before the trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1545 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0168 </DOCNO>
