<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Gets Aid After Flooding  </HEADLINE>
   By MIKE COHEN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   XAI-XAI, Mozambique (AP) -- With many roads and bridges washed out, an air
relief operation accelerated Thursday for victims of flooding that has killed 70
in Mozambique and submerged much of the country in muddy water.
</P>
<P>
	   Rainstorms, meanwhile, persisted in neighboring areas of southern Africa,
exacting a deadly toll.
</P>
<P>
	   In South Africa's Northern Province, 10 people have died since Wednesday
night when their water-soaked houses collapsed, and two others drowned when they
were swept away by fast-running rivers.
</P>
<P>
	   In Zimbabwe, torrential rain forced 250,000 people to evacuate their homes.
Five people have died. Others marooned by floodwaters had to fend off venomous
snakes that also fled to high ground.
</P>
<P>
	   Record levels of rainfall began drenching southern Africa at the beginning
of February. Cyclone Eline, which surged ashore Tuesday with heavy rains and
winds howling at more than 100 miles an hour, added to the misery.
</P>
<P>
	   On Thursday, a French C160 military cargo plane ferried loads of aid to
outlying depots in Mozambique for further distribution to victims by
helicopters. Two private helicopters from South Africa arrived Thursday in
Mozambique's capital of Maputo to assist five South African Air Force
helicopters with food drops.
</P>
<P>
	   The helicopters also have plucked more than 3,000 people from rising
floodwaters, including from trees and rooftops.
</P>
<P>
	   Since the air operation began, 270 tons of food and medical supplies have
been delivered, said South African Air Force Maj. Louis Kirsten.
</P>
<P>
	   From the air, it appeared an inland sea had settled over much of Mozambique,
with water punctuated by the tops of trees, islands of high-lying ground and the
roofs of huts.
</P>
<P>
	   In the low-lying countryside there was virtually no sign of life. Most
people had left for higher ground.
</P>
<P>
	   The area surrounding Xai-Xai, a town about 125 miles north of Maputo, was
hit hard when the nearby Limpopo River overflowed. Residents tried Thursday to
extract their cars from the muck.
</P>
<P>
	   The World Health Organization warned that more than 800,000 Mozambicans are
at risk from epidemics -- particularly cholera and malaria -- because of the
flooding.
</P>
<P>
	   Mozambique's government and the United Nations have appealed for
international aid. Portugal, Mozambique's colonial ruler until 1975, responded
with a donation of $2 million.
</P>
<P>
	   Officials said the flooding in Mozambique left more than 200,000 people
homeless and more than 300,000 needing food aid. The storms knocked out power
supplies and washed away scores of roads and bridges.
</P>
<P>
	   Rogerio Manguete, an official with the Mozambican disaster management
services, said the economy had been set back by years.
</P>
<P>
	   Zimbabwe's government appealed for tents, clothing, blankets, water
purification aids, and food to supplement distribution of its own strategic corn
reserves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1548 </TRAILER>
