<HEADLINE> Health Center Funding Boost Urged  </HEADLINE>
   By LIBBY QUAID Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal funds for health care clinics that annually treat
millions uninsured Americans would grow by more than $2.7 billion over five
years under an effort announced Thursday by a bipartisan group of senators.
</P>
<P>
	   The lawmakers are pressing to double funds for community health centers,
whose providers treat 11 million people each year, more than one-third of whom
lack health insurance.
</P>
<P>
	   Supporters held a Capitol Hill news conference to announce the effort, which
they say has a much better chance of passage in this election year than broader
health care proposals being pushed in Congress and on the presidential campaign
trail.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It specifically targets the people and communities with the largest health
care access problems,'' said Sen. Christopher Bond, R-Mo. and a bill sponsor.
``And it takes advantage of successful private organizations instead of relying
on a government takeover of health care.''
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C. and another sponsor, said the program saves
money: ``It costs four times as much for regular treatment and five to six times
as much in the emergency room,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The centers deliver primary care and preventive treatment to patients in
hundreds of under-served urban and rural areas nationwide. Among those patients
is Denise Hall, a single mother of two from Washington, D.C., who does not have
health insurance for herself or her youngest son. She goes to the Bethlehem
Health Center, part of Washington's Unity Health Care, for help.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Even when I have no money to pay for treatment, they will see me
regardless of my ability to pay or my insurance status,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bond and Hollings have nine co-sponsors, including Sens. Orrin Hatch,
R-Utah; Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.; and Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
