<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worker Walkouts Hit Low in 1999  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of major strikes by American workers hit a
record low of 17 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year's big labor disputes idled about 73,000 workers for an average of
16 days each, the Labor Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The agency's Bureau of Labor Statistics has been keeping a count since 1947
of strikes involving 1,000 or more workers and lasting at least one shift. The
previous record low of 29 strikes was set in 1997. In 1998, there were 34
walkouts involving 387,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
	   Of last year's strikes, 12 were in the private sector and the rest involved
teachers and other education workers employed by state and local governments.
</P>
<P>
	   The largest strikes involved 12,000 workers at casinos in Atlantic City,
N.J., and 11,000 teachers each in Detroit and Washington state.
</P>
<P>
	   The longest was at Newport News Shipbuilding and Dry Dock Company in
Virginia, where 8,000 employees represented by the United Steelworkers struck
for 117 days.
</P>
<P>
	   Strike activity by unions has generally been declining since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
	   Union membership has decreased during most of that period, and companies'
successes at replacing striking workers has caused unions to resort to other
tactics, including publicity campaigns targeted at consumers.
</P>
<P>
	   Labor Secretary Alexis Herman said the booming economy also was a factor
last year. "Unionized workers are benefitting from our historic expansion and
enjoying real wage gains," she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
