<HEADLINE> Argentina President Faces Tough Test  </HEADLINE>
   By CAMILLA GALLAGHER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- New President Fernando de la Rua faced one
of his toughest political tests to date Thursday as Argentina's lower house took
up a controversial labor reform bill amid a noisy Buenos Aires street protest.
</P>
<P>
	   The 2 1/2-month-old administration won over mainline labor unions with its
proposals to revamp labor laws many see as too rigid. But dissenting truckers
and other workers went ahead with a protest anyway.
</P>
<P>
	   A crowd the Interior Ministry estimated at 18,000 people massed in the
capital, beating drums, setting off firecrackers and waving colorful union
banners.
</P>
<P>
	   De la Rua officials said they were not worried by the afternoon
demonstration. Many of the 3,000 uniformed officers watched the traffic-snarling
protest from behind mesh barricades, but did not intervene.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'd find it difficult to believe that the labor reform will be thwarted,''
said Economy Minister Jose Luis Machinea. He predicted victory for the labor
proposal, which is intended to stir job growth and increase competition in the
labor market.
</P>
<P>
	   With Argentina beset by a recession and a jobless rate of 13.8 percent, the
president has worked to cut a troublesome fiscal deficit and has passed
unpopular new tax proposals.
</P>
<P>
	   The government's proposed labor bill calls for a host of changes, including
extending the probationary period of new hires and lowering employer-paid
payroll contributions for new workers. With such measures, the government
intends to boost wage flexibility and promote the creation of steady jobs.
</P>
<P>
	   International observers -- including the International Monetary Fund, which
holds the key to a $7.4 billion standby loan for Argentina -- believe the
proposed reforms would improve Argentina's labor market. Union critics claim,
however, that the measures will hurt workers without boosting the economy.
</P>
<P>
	   Rodolfo Daer, the head of the Confederacion General de Trabajo, Argentina's
main union federation, scrapped plans for a demonstration Thursday. But Daer's
sudden decision caused a split within the federation. Hugo Moyano, the head of
the truckers union, seized the CGT headquarters Wednesday and led hard-liners
during Thursday's work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
	   During the protest, Moyano raised his fist on a podium packed with union
dissenters and shouted down the reform package. Confetti flew and drums banged
as scores of union banners fluttered on tall poles. Police watched silently amid
the horn-honking chaos.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is a direct provocation against working people,'' Moyano said of the
reform package, which he called a move to chip away at worker protections. The
crowd roared back its approval.
</P>
<P>
	   The proposal's fate in the lower house represents a major test for the
president. If endorsed, the measure would go on to the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1607 </TRAILER>
