<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. OKs Troop Commitment for Congo  </HEADLINE>
   By EDITH M. LEDERER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Half a year after six nations and three rebel groups
signed a cease-fire on Congo, the U.N. Security Council on Thursday authorized a
5,500-strong observer force to monitor its implementation and lay the groundwork
for possible deployment of a peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
	   The former combatants are already pressing for the United Nations to send
peacekeepers, but the Security Council first wants the opposing sides to honor
the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
	   The 15-member council unanimously agreed to the U.S.-drafted resolution to
send 500 military observers, supported by 5,037 security troops and logistics
personnel. The group will verify that all parties are observing last summer's
cease-fire aimed at ending a 1 1/2-year war in Congo that has destabilized
central Africa.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke has said the United States will not
provide troops but may provide logistical support.
</P>
<P>
	   Many council members recognize that sending such a small mission to a
country a quarter the size of the United States with few roads and poor
communications may not be militarily effective but can be politically important.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Security Council has taken a critical step to help the Congo come to a
peace that its people so desperately need,'' said Holbrooke, who devoted his
presidency of the council last month to African issues. ``The time has now
arrived to act.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Congo observer mission, expected to cost around $500 million for the
first 12 months, is the fourth major U.N. peacekeeping operation approved by the
Security Council in eight months. It had already agreed to send 4,800 civilian
police to Kosovo, 11,100 peacekeepers to Sierra Leone, and 10,800 peacekeepers
and civilian police to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
	   The war in Congo has been called Africa's first world war. Russia's U.N.
ambassador, Sergey Lavrov, on Thursday described it as ``the largest conflict in
modern Africa.'' It has not ended despite the cease-fire agreement -- a point
reiterated by speaker after speaker.
</P>
<P>
	   Congo is backed by Angola, Zimbabwe and Namibia. The rebels who took up arms
to oust President Laurent Kabila from power in August 1998 are supported by
Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
	   As recently as Wednesday, at a one-day summit in Lusaka, Zambia, the key
players renewed their commitment to implement the cease-fire quickly.
</P>
<P>
	   But Britain's Deputy Ambassador Stewart Eldon told the council ``the
situation on the ground does not look promising.'' He warned that increasing
ethnic tensions in the Kivu region in rebel-held eastern Congo threatened the
entire population and risked ``a humanitarian catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``The fighting must stop now,'' he said. ``International humanitarian law
must be respected.''
</P>
<P>
	   Under the resolution, deployment would be in phases and subject to
Secretary-General Kofi Annan's determination that the troops are safely able to
do their jobs. A senior U.N. official said the first observers could be deployed
within three weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   Possible troop contributors include Pakistan, Jordan, Senegal and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
	   Lavrov underscored the council's general agreement that the United Nations
will not take measures to force the parties to a peace, or to force guerrillas
to disarm.
</P>
<P>
	   The situation in Congo is so complicated, he said, ``that it would not only
be naive but dangerous to rely on its settlement by external forces.''
</P>
<P>
	   Participants at the Lusaka summit welcomed the expected deployment of U.N.
observers and urged the Security Council to quickly deploy peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
	   But the draft resolution gives no timetable for even considering a
peacekeeping force, saying only that Annan should make recommendations for
further deployment based on progress in implementing the cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
	   Holbrooke stressed that support for the U.N. observer mission did not
constitute ``prior approval'' for a peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
	   Namibia's U.N. ambassador, Martin Andjaba, noting that it took the council
almost four months to adopt the resolution, called for speedy deployment of the
military observers and expressed hope that peacekeepers would soon follow.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Over the years, the U.N. has brought peace to so many countries including
my own,'' Andjaba said. ``Expectations of the suffering masses in the (Congo)
for peace in their country are therefore high and rightly so. We should not let
them down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
