<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gulf Nations OK Oil Production Hike  </HEADLINE>
   By TAREK AL-ISSAWI Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Persian Gulf oil ministers have agreed
to increase production of crude to stabilize prices around the world, but have
not decided how much -- leaving it unclear whether consumers will find relief at
the gas pumps.
</P>
<P>
	   A senior United Arab Emirates oil official said Thursday that Gulf Arab oil
ministers who met the day before in Saudi Arabia agreed to a production
increase. Such a move could bring down oil prices, which have been hovering near
a nine-year high.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Figures were discussed and more discussions will be held before a specific
figure is agreed upon,'' the official said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
	   The official said a production increase will be gradual and will be in the
range of 1.5 million barrels a day, or 6 percent above current levels.
</P>
<P>
	   ``After that, it's the market's call,'' he said, refusing to speculate to
what extent that would bring prices down from the $30 a barrel where they have
been hovering.
</P>
<P>
	   Other Gulf officials cited different figures, but all those who met
Wednesday in the Saudi capital, Riyadh, agreed a production increase is needed.
Some officials said the ministers now favor an increase of between 2 million and
2.5 million barrels per day -- about 8 to 10 percent -- to reach a price of
between $20 and $25 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
	   Not all oil-producing nations agree, however. Kuwait has championed the
cause of maintaining current production cuts beyond their scheduled expiration
on March 31. And Iran, the second-largest producer in the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries, has come out against a rise in output.
</P>
<P>
	   Kuwaiti Oil Minister Sheik Saud Al Sabah declined to say Thursday if Kuwait
had agreed to increase its production, saying the question would be decided at
OPEC's meeting in late March.
</P>
<P>
	   Oil analyst James A. Placke, director of Middle East research at Cambridge
Energy Research Associates, said the market would welcome a production increase.
</P>
<P>
	   ``An increase is appropriate and indeed necessary,'' Placke said. ``If there
is no adjustment, there will be a supply shortage, beyond what we've seen.''
</P>
<P>
	   It is difficult to peg specific increases in output to falls in oil price
because prices depend on many factors, including market perceptions and the
behavior of countries like Iraq.
</P>
<P>
	   Some analysts have said an increase of at least 2 million barrels a day is
needed to stabilize markets and make a sufficient impact on stocks of oil. A
smaller increase could actually raise prices because it may be seen as an
indication that producers are not serious about stabilizing prices. Gasoline
prices in the United States are averaging about $1.41 per gallon, about five
cents shy of the all-time peak of $1.46 in November 1990.
</P>
<P>
	   In the past two weeks, some oil producers within and outside OPEC, such as
Mexico, have called for OPEC to increase production beyond the current 22.976
million barrels a day set by an agreement.
</P>
<P>
	   At a Gulf meeting last year, OPEC members Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Qatar and
the United Arab Emirates and non-OPEC members Oman and Bahrain agreed to cut
production to raise prices. Oil was then at its lowest prices in decades, but
the cutback helped drive the price to its current high level.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, who arrived in Kuwait on Thursday and
flies to Saudi Arabia on Friday, said Washington does not want to manipulate
markets or dictate prices.
</P>
<P>
	   While a price of $10 a barrel was ``much too low,'' $30 a barrel is too
high, Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What we want to see is stability in the oil market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Crude oil for April delivery gained 53 cents to $29.92 per barrel on the New
York Mercantile Exchange Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1627 </TRAILER>
