<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pope Begins Egypt Pilgrimage  </HEADLINE>
   By VICTOR L. SIMPSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Denouncing violence in the name of religion as ``an
offense against God,'' Pope John Paul II called for tolerance on Thursday as he
began a visit to Egypt, where clashes between Muslims and Christians recently
left 23 people dead.
</P>
<P>
	   In beginning his pilgrimage to retrace some of the epic passages from the
Bible, John Paul became the first Roman Catholic pope to visit predominantly
Islamic Egypt.
</P>
<P>
	   The pontiff's three-day Egypt trip also gave him an opportunity to promote
closer dialogue with Muslims and to try to overcome old rifts with Orthodox
Christians.
</P>
<P>
	   The pope raised the issue of tolerance among religious groups, speaking in
general terms, as is his custom.
</P>
<P>
	   John Paul said his planned visit to Mount Sinai on Saturday, where tradition
says God gave Moses the Ten Commandments, ``will be a moment of intense prayer
for peace and for interreligious dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``To do harm, to promote violence and conflict in the name of religion is a
terrible contradiction and a great offense against God,'' the pope said shortly
after arriving at Cairo's international airport. ``But past and present history
give us many examples of such a misuse of religion.''
</P>
<P>
	   John Paul, dressed in white robes embroidered in gold, had earlier emerged
from his plane under cloudy skies and slowly made his way down red-carpeted
steps to the airport's tarmac.
</P>
<P>
	   President Hosni Mubarak greeted John Paul with a handshake at the foot of
the stairs. Those who came to welcome the pope included Muslim and Christian
religious leaders from across the region.
</P>
<P>
	   Twenty-three people were killed in southern Egypt in January during clashes
between Muslims and Coptic Christians, the largest religious minority in
predominantly Muslim Egypt. Most of those who died were Copts.
</P>
<P>
	   In greeting the pope, Mubarak denounced all forms of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Today the Egyptian people stand together, united by their submission to
the will of God and inspired by the spirit of both Christianity and Islam,''
Mubarak said in English.
</P>
<P>
	   The pope, also speaking in English, thanked Mubarak for making his visit
possible.
</P>
<P>
	   ``For many years I have been looking forward to celebrating the 2,000th
anniversary of the birth of Jesus Christ by visiting and praying at the places
specially linked to God's intervention in history,'' the pope said.
</P>
<P>
	   Few ordinary Egyptians greeted the pope at the airport, and only small
groups of people turned out to welcome the pope along his motorcade route.
</P>
<P>
	   With the flags of Egypt and the Vatican waving in the background, Mubarak
escorted the pope, who leaned on a cane, away from the plane. A band played the
processional from Verdi's ``Aida,'' an opera associated with Egypt.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He is really old,'' said Nancy Tawfik, 10, a Catholic school student,
after she presented John Paul with a basket of Egyptian earth to bless.
</P>
<P>
	   The hands of the 79-year-old pope trembled Thursday as he gripped the podium
while reading his speech. The shaking and slurred speech are symptoms of
Parkinson's disease, a progressive neurological disorder.
</P>
<P>
	   But the pope held up well, shaking the hands of dozens of well-wishers
during his meetings with Coptic Orthodox Pope Shenouda III and Sheik Mohammed
Sayed Tantawi, one of the most influential Muslim clerics in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
	   Tantawi drew applause when he told the pope: ``We are very happy you are so
close to the Palestinian people.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Vatican said earlier this month that Israel's control of Jerusalem was
``morally and legally unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
	   After their 10-minute meeting, the pope and Tantawi both emphasized the need
for dialogue between people of different cultures and religions.
</P>
<P>
	   Tantawi also announced he would visit the Vatican this fall. It would be his
first such trip to the center of Roman Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
	   The pope's spokesman, Joaquin Navarro-Valls, said peace in the Middle East
``is important in the pope's thoughts'' but that the ``first consideration is
the pope's personal pilgrimage'' to Biblical sites.
</P>
<P>
	   The pope previously visited Cairo in 1963, while archbishop of Krakow,
Poland, with a group of prelates en route to the Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
	   On Saturday, the pope is scheduled to travel to the St. Catherine monastery,
a nearly 1,500-year-old Greek Orthodox outpost in the shadow of Mount Sinai.
</P>
<P>
	   The monastery visit presents the pope with another chance to further his
desire to close the nearly 1,000-year split between the Vatican and Orthodox
churches, which separated following disputes over papal authority.
</P>
<P>
	   Next month, John Paul plans to visit Bethlehem and Jerusalem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
