<HEADLINE> Study Looks at Health of Hispanics  </HEADLINE>
    By KAREN GULLO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Puerto Ricans are in poorer health than other Hispanics
living in the United States, a government study finds.
</P>
<P>
	   Puerto Ricans reported being sick more often than Mexican-Americans,
Cuban-Americans and others of Hispanic descent and had more doctor visits,
hospital stays and sick days off from work and school than other Hispanics, a
four-year study by the National Center for Health Statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
	   The study, being released Friday, is the government's first ever effort to
look at health differences among Hispanic groups after the explosive growth in
the nation's Hispanic population in the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
	   Nearly 30 million people of Hispanic origin reside in the United States,
representing 11 percent of the population. That's up 36 percent from 1990.
</P>
<P>
	   Other studies have shown that as a group Hispanics lag in many areas of
health. Diabetes, AIDS and depression are major health problems for Hispanics.
They also are more likely to lack health insurance; recent studies have shown
that a fourth of the 44 million people without insurance are Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
	   This latest study is evidence that there is variance among subgroups of the
culture that require more study, said Anjum Hajat, the report's author.
</P>
<P>
	   "Often the medical literature just lump together all Hispanic groups," said
Hajat.
</P>
<P>
	   The report, which looked at data from a national health survey of all
Americans collected from 1992 through 1995, focuses on the largest Hispanic
subgroups: Mexicans, who make up 63 percent of all Hispanics, Puerto Ricans,
which represent 11 percent and Cubans, which comprise 4 percent. Another 22
percent of people of Hispanic origins other than those three were grouped
together.
</P>
<P>
	   The report found:
</P>
<P>
	   -- Eighteen percent of Puerto Ricans reported being in fair or poor health,
compared with 16 percent of Mexicans, 14 percent of Cubans and 12 percent of
other Hispanic groups.
</P>
<P>
	   -- Eighty-three percent of Puerto Ricans reported seeing a doctor in the
past year, compared to 78 percent of Cubans, 77 percent of other Hispanics and
69 percent of Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
	   -- Puerto Ricans reported being sick more than the other groups.
</P>
<P>
	   Hispanic health experts warned that the study, which isolated Hispanics'
data out of a general study of Americans' health, could mask important health
information about Hispanics and reinforce stereotypes that Hispanics, because
they tend to have lower incomes than other Americans, are in poorer health.
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, Hispanics live longer than whites and Hispanic women have lower
rates of breast cancer but more cervical cancer than non-Hispanic women,
according to the National Coalition of Hispanic Health and Human Services
Organizations, a Washington-based advocacy organization.
</P>
<P>
	   "The kind of data used is missing the bigger issues," said Jane Delgado,
president.
</P>
<P>
	   The study was based on interviews with 36,924 Mexican-Americans, 6,922
Puerto Ricans living in the United States, 3,008 Cuban-Americans and 13,865
people of other Hispanic origin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1655 </TRAILER>
