<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Investigate Auto Defect Deaths  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal safety agency is studying the engineering of air
bag systems on some older model Hyundai Accent cars because seven children have
been killed by the deploying devices in crashes.
</P>
<P>
	   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration also is investigating
some General Motors cars after more than 200 complaints that the shoulder belts
jam and do not retract, according to a monthly report released Thursday by the
agency.
</P>
<P>
	   The agency has upgraded the investigation into Accent cars from model years
1995 through 1997 to study how the air bag systems work and determine whether
the rate of air bag deaths is worse than in other vehicles.
</P>
<P>
	   There are about 170,000 of the cars on the road from those model years.
There have been seven child deaths in low- or moderate-speed crashes involving
the cars, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
	   Two infants also were killed while riding in rear-facing infant seats. But
those deaths were not part of the investigation because safety officials have
repeatedly said, and auto warning labels indicate, that infants in rear-facing
infant seats should never be placed in front of air bags. The seats position
infant heads too close to the bags when they inflate.
</P>
<P>
	   Hyundai spokesman Mike Hanson said in a company statement that the children
killed were either unbelted or improperly belted. ``Hyundai has clearly and
consistently warned its customers that children should always be placed in the
rear seats of cars equipped with air bags,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
	   Air bags have been blamed for the deaths of at least 150 people -- mostly
unbelted children or small adults -- in low-speed accidents they otherwise
should have survived, according to NHTSA data.
</P>
<P>
	   In the case of GM seat belts, the report said 207 consumers complained about
front shoulder belt webbing jamming on Buick Park Avenue cars from model years
1997 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   There are about 171,000 of the cars on the road.
</P>
<P>
	   GM has made several modifications to the seat belt system, including using
stronger belt webbing that was less susceptible to twisting and narrowing the
belt webbing guide slot, the report said. Since last summer, GM has had a repair
kit available for the front shoulder belts.
</P>
<P>
	   However, NHTSA investigators said they were concerned that dealers appear
unable to address many consumer complaints about the problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
