<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NTSB Recommends Changes to Boats  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID A. LIEB Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The National Transportation Safety Board
recommended today that backup floation devices be installed in amphibious boats
to prevent the kind of rapid flooding that sank a tourist boat last year.
</P>
<P>
	   The Miss Majestic plunged to the bottom of Lake Hamilton in a matter of
minutes May 1 after taking on water. Thirteen passengers drowned.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. Coast Guard in December concluded that a dislodged drive-shaft seal
allowed water to flood the hull. The boat's bilge pump failed to work.
</P>
<P>
	   The NTSB said boat operators should not rely on the pumps only, recommending
the installation of backup flotation devices -- watertight bulkheads, buoyant
materials inside the hull or flotation attachments on the outside of the boat.
</P>
<P>
	   Amphibious boats sink easily because they have no backup flotation, NTSB
Chairman Jim Hall said in a letter asking the industry to respond to the
recommendations within 90 days.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Consequently, the safety board concludes that the potential exists for
another life-threatening accident similar to the sinking of the Miss Majestic,
unless the vulnerability to flooding and sinking is addressed,'' the letter
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The boat that sank in Arkansas was a Duck, originally known as a DUKW. It
was a vintage World War II vessel designed for military purposes, then converted
to take tourists through the Hot Springs area.
</P>
<P>
	   Nationwide, more than 250 amphibious passenger boats are in service. Most
are ducks and the rest are similar models.
</P>
<P>
	   At least 18 amphibious boats had accidents -- six involving some degree of
flooding -- between March 6, 1991, and May 1, 1999, according to Coast Guard
data. None was fatal.
</P>
<P>
	   The safety board said it has learned of at least nine other incidents
involving significant flooding that were not reported to the Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
	   Amphibious boats have several flooding threats. The safety board said water
can leak in through a failed hull fitting, missing plug or a hull that is
cracked by running aground. Also, the road travel and repeated entry and exit
from water can wear on the vessel's hull and loosen mechanical joints and
connections.
</P>
<P>
	   Because the boats have open interiors and a low amount of space between the
stern and the water, it doesn't take long for the boats to flood and sink, the
NTSB said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1706 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Justice Dept. Reviews Deutch Case  </HEADLINE>
   By TOM RAUM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department, which earlier declined to bring
criminal charges against former CIA Director John Deutch for home computer
security breaches, is taking a new look ``to see whether there is any basis for
further action,'' Attorney General Janet Reno said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Reno said the inquiry would cover both Deutch's conduct and the CIA's
follow-up.
</P>
<P>
	   Top members of the Senate Intelligence Committee welcomed Reno's new
interest but said they would move ahead with their own inquiry.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's sad she didn't take a closer look at it earlier, because something is
wrong and we're going to get to the bottom of it,'' said the committee chairman,
Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the committee, which heard from Deutch earlier in this week, is
turning more attention to why it took the CIA 18 months to notify congressional
oversight committees after the agency discovered in December 1996 that Deutch
had mishandled classified material.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is inexplicable to me and to others on the committee,'' Shelby said,
suggesting ``possibly a cover-up.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``There are a lot of unanswered questions,'' said Sen. Richard Bryan of
Nevada, the committee's vice chairman and senior Democrat.
</P>
<P>
	   Reno discussed the review in response to questions at her weekly news
conference.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The department is looking at the whole matter, reviewing the whole matter
to see whether there is any basis for further action,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Deutch, CIA director from May 1995 to December 1996, stored and processed
hundreds of files of highly classified material on unprotected home computers
that he and family members also used to connect the Internet, according to an
internal CIA investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   Now a professor at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Deutch was
stripped of his security clearances by CIA director George Tenet in August. As a
former deputy defense secretary, Deutch also had Pentagon clearances, but he
voluntarily gave them up this month.
</P>
<P>
	   Deutch has apologized, both in private testimony to the Senate Intelligence
Committee and in a brief appearance Tuesday before reporters.
</P>
<P>
	   Last spring, after a yearlong review of the 1996 episode, the Justice
Department's criminal division declined to prosecute Deutch for mishandling
classified information. The division found the lapses were sloppy rather than
nefarious, and referred the case to the CIA inspector general for administrative
discipline.
</P>
<P>
	   Reno and her aides declined to specify what questions were being reviewed.
They said only that the entire matter was under scrutiny, when asked whether the
Deutch criminal investigation could be reopened or whether there was any
obstruction of justice of top CIA officials.
</P>
<P>
	   One Justice official, requesting anonymity, said two criminal division
lawyers are handling the review.
</P>
<P>
	   It is more comprehensive than the one the Justice Department announced three
weeks ago, this official said. At that time, Justice lawyers were said to be
taking a look at the CIA inspector general's report, but, based on information
then available, there were no plans to reopen the Deutch investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   Justice officials said then that they had not seen anything in the inspector
general report or during congressional hearings that they had not already known
when they decided last spring not to prosecute Deutch.
</P>
<P>
	   The Senate committee has been moving ahead with its own probe.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to hearing from Deutch, the committee has questioned CIA
Inspector General Brit Snider and FBI and CIA security officials.
</P>
<P>
	   Former CIA general counsel Michael O'Neil has been invited to testify on
March 1.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Neil, who left the agency in 1997, at first declined to turn over computer
storage cards from Deutch's computers and delayed notifying the Justice
Department of the matter, according to an unclassified version of an internal
CIA inspector general's report released earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
	   The panel also intends to call Nora Slatkin, the CIA's former executive
director and now an official with Citicorp.
</P>
<P>
	   The CIA's inspector general report found that her actions delayed ``a prompt
and thorough investigation'' of the Deutch case.
</P>
<P>
	   Shelby, in an interview, said he does not know if any laws were broken but
said Deutch ``violated some of the most sacred rules, if not the laws.''
</P>
<P>
	   He said his committee's investigation thus far suggests that Tenet and his
top deputies were frozen in inaction ``because of the friendship, the
relationship they had with Dr. Deutch.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Associated Press Writer Michael J. Sniffen contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
