<HEADLINE> Labor Leaders Resign From Panel  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WASHINGTON (AP) -- AFL-CIO President John Sweeney and other labor leaders
resigned Thursday from a private panel that President Clinton appointed as
advisers on trade.
</P>
<P>
	   In a letter to U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky, Sweeney
complained that business leaders and their interests have outweighed labor and
consumer representatives on the president's Advisory Committee for Trade Policy
and Negotiations.
</P>
<P>
	   "This imbalance has contributed to a corresponding imbalance in U.S. trade
policy," Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
	   Barshefsky had touted the labor leader's support for a resolution by the
panel supporting Clinton's overall trade agenda last fall.
</P>
<P>
	   Sweeney's resignation follows a Jan. 25 announcement by the advisory panel's
chairman, Proctor &AMP; Gamble chairman John E. Pepper, that the only meeting this
year would be to consider a resolution in support of the administration's
campaign to get permanent normal trade status for China.
</P>
<P>
	   The AFL-CIO has launched a major advertising and lobbying campaign against
the China initiative.
</P>
<P>
	   Resigning from the ACTPN along with Sweeney were Jay Mazur, president of
UNITE!, a New York Union, and Lenore Miller, president emeritus of the Retail,
Wholesale and Department Store Union.
</P>
<P>
	   That leaves no labor representatives on the panel, which currently includes
27 corporate members, one environmental group and one consumer
organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
