<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USDA: Farm Income To Rebound  </HEADLINE>
    By PHILIP BRASHER AP Farm Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Food prices will rise by about 2 percent a year over the
next decade, less than the overall cost of living, and farm income will start to
rebound in 2002 as global demand picks up, the government said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Competition among restaurants will keep the cost of eating away from home
from increasing more than about 2.2 percent a year, while prices at the
supermarket should rise about 2.1 percent annually, the Agriculture Department
said in its latest long-term economic projections. The overall rate of inflation
is expected to be 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   "American consumers will be blessed again in 2000 with an abundant,
affordable food supply," said Keith Collins, USDA's chief economist.
</P>
<P>
	   While prices are rising for beef and pork, reflecting tighter supplies,
dairy products and citrus are likely to be cheaper this year. Fresh vegetables
also should be plentiful, based on this winter's acreage, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Over the decade, USDA foresees some price cuts for meat and poultry and
continued sharp swings from year to year in dairy products. The largest price
increases are expected in fruits and vegetables, as much as 3.5 percent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
	   For farmers, the good news depends on a projected increase in U.S.
agricultural exports. The Asian economic crisis sent grain prices plummeting two
years ago as exports dropped, and they have yet to recover.
</P>
<P>
	   "Global economies are improving," Collins said. "World economic growth in
2000 is forecast to exceed 3 percent, a rate not seen since 1997."
</P>
<P>
	   Net farm income reached $48 billion last year, largely because of a record
$22.7 billion in direct government payments. Farm earnings are expected to fall
to $40.4 billion this year and then to $34.4 billion in 2001 before turning back
up in 2002.
</P>
<P>
	   The projections don't account for the possibility that Congress will approve
another multibillion package of farm assistance this year. The Clinton
administration is proposing at least $3 billion in additional spending that
wasn't included in the forecast.
</P>
<P>
	   Cash receipts from crops and livestock are expected to fall to $189.9
billion this year from last year's $191.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. wheat production could fall 200 million bushels because of lower
plantings this winter and a lingering drought on the Plains, Collins said. That
won't do much to increase wheat prices, however. Wheat stocks are expected to be
the largest they've been since 1988, and Europe could have a record crop.
</P>
<P>
	   "Overall conditions in the farm economy are similar to last year," Collins
said. "Markets for major commodities, particularly crops, are very weak, but an
overall farm economic crisis has not materialized," largely due to government
programs.
</P>
<P>
	   Farm exports are expected to increase slightly this year, from $49 billion
to $49.5 billion, because of higher sales of cotton and livestock. In 2001,
exports are projected to jump to $51.2 billion and then rise to $75.9 billion by
the end of the decade. The largest gains are expected to come in sales of wheat,
corn and cotton.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. exports could be much stronger, depending how much China winds up
buying, the department's report said.
</P>
<P>
	   USDA is predicting that sales of farm products to China could triple to $3
billion annually if China enters the World Trade Organization. Tariffs on beef
alone could drop from 45 percent to 12 percent under an agreement by China to
lower its trade barriers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1717 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Up; Silver, Cocoa Down  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVE CARPENTER AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Crude oil prices pushed 2 percent higher Thursday as new evidence of
tightening U.S. inventories caused investors to shrug off OPEC's talk of raising
production, figuring it won't be enough to replenish supplies quickly.
</P>
<P>
	   Other energy commodities also rose.
</P>
<P>
	   In other markets, silver slipped to a one-month low and cocoa fell.
</P>
<P>
	   Oil futures blasted briefly back over $30 a barrel on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, resuming their relentless year-long rise upward in the wake
of a brief pause that ended early this week.
</P>
<P>
	   West Texas intermediate crude for April delivery settled at $29.97 a barrel,
up 58 cents, after rising as high as $30.15.
</P>
<P>
	   The 11-month-old agreement on lowered output by world oil producers that has
sent prices skyward ever since is increasingly expected to be revised when it
expires March 31. By how much remains a topic of intense speculation.
</P>
<P>
	   While the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries won't make a final
decision until its March 27 meeting, a consensus for hiking production appeared
evident when Gulf oil ministers -- including key OPEC members -- met Wednesday
in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
	   A senior United Arab Emirates oil official said Thursday a production
increase will be gradual and will be in the range of 1.5 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
	   But that's only an estimate. And with the possibility of shortages looming,
market watchers think even that figure won't be enough to get world supplies
back above dangerously low levels quickly.
</P>
<P>
	   "The market is worried that they (producers) are not being more
demonstrative. Until we get some solid numbers, people are nervous on the long
side," said Phil Flynn, senior market analyst for Alaron Trading Corp. in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's no guarantee that what they add is going to be enough," Flynn said.
</P>
<P>
	   The 1.5 million barrels daily would add some 6 percent to world production;
analysts say an output increase closer to 9 percent is needed.
</P>
<P>
	   The Department of Energy reported Thursday that U.S. crude inventories fell
300,000 barrels last week -- a larger drop than expected. Domestic stocks are
nearly 40 million barrels, which the DOE said is a four-year low.
</P>
<P>
	   Oil prices also were pushed higher by government figures showing that
gasoline stocks slipped 2.9 million barrels last week, or 1.5 percent, to 285.5
million barrels. That drop exceeded the 432,000-barrel decline reported a day
earlier by the American Petroleum Institute.
</P>
<P>
	   Among other energy commodities, March heating oil rose 1.89 cent to 78.02
cents a gallon, March unleaded gasoline rose .43 cent to 85.05 cents a gallon
and March natural gas rose 1.9 cents to $2.549 per 1,000 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
	   In London, April Brent crude from the North Sea rose 31 cents to $27.37 a
barrel on the International Petroleum Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   In other trading, on the Comex division of the New York Merc, silver was the
hardest-hit metal in an across-the-board drop. A 5.5 million-ounce jump in Comex
warehouse stocks and rumors that they may increase by as much as another 30
million ounces over the next week buoyed the price.
</P>
<P>
	   March silver fell 9 cents to $5.166 an ounce.
</P>
<P>
	   A few blocks away on New York's Coffee, Sugar &AMP; Cocoa Exchange, cocoa
declined on evidence that West African harvests, the world's biggest crops, are
even larger than anticipated. New-crop arrivals at ports in No. 1 producer Ivory
Coast are exceeding expectations.
</P>
<P>
	   May cocoa settled down $15 at $791 per ton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1726 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
