<DOCNO> APW20000224.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Engineers Corps Denies Budget Scheme  </HEADLINE>
   By ALAN FRAM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Amid new accusations that the Army Corps of Engineers
skewed data to justify higher spending for its water projects, the agency's top
officer told Congress Thursday that there are no ``rogue officers'' scheming to
bloat the Corps' budget.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite assurances by Lt. Gen. Joe N. Ballard, the Corps' chief of
engineers, that officials use ``a very open process'' to review proposed
projects, members of a Senate subcommittee warned that the agency's credibility
had been battered and said they would not stand for falsified reports.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What we're talking about here is the integrity of the Corps,'' said Sen.
George Voinovich, R-Ohio, chairman of a Senate transportation and infrastructure
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
	   The hearing came as Environmental Defense, a pro-environment group, released
what it said were internal Corps documents.
</P>
<P>
	   One memorandum on a $1 billion plan to expand locks on the Mississippi and
Illinois rivers said a preliminary study of the project was ``wrong'' and that
the Corps should not issue a ``limp-wristed'' recommendation that the work be
stretched out to 2025.
</P>
<P>
	   Environmental Defense also released a slide show that officials from Corps
headquarters showed to staff in field offices, detailing a plan to expand the
agency's current $4 billion civil works budget to $6.2 billion by 2005.
</P>
<P>
	   Both documents were described in Thursday's editions of The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
	   After the hearing, Army Secretary Louis Caldera announced that the National
Academy of Sciences, a congressionally chartered private group, would review the
Corps' study of the Mississippi and Illinois river project. The Army has already
begun investigating other allegations against the Corps.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I want to assure you that we take these charges seriously and that we are
addressing them on both the specifics of the issues raised as well as the more
fundamental issues of oversight and control of the civil works program,''
Caldera said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   At the hearing, Joseph W. Westphal, an assistant secretary for the Army who
oversees some of the Corps' work, said he had not been aware of the slide
presentation. He said the agency has ``a very grassroots level for making
policy'' in which recommendations for various projects usually come from local
offices, not headquarters.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm not in a position from my office in the Pentagon to know everything
going on out in the field,'' Westphal told the senators.
</P>
<P>
	   Ballard, sitting beside Westphal at the witness table, said he had not shown
the presentation to his civilian superior yet because it had not been completed.
</P>
<P>
	   Ballard said criticism of the agency creates an impression that ``a bunch of
rogue officers plotted to take over this program. That simply is not true.''
</P>
<P>
	   He said the proposal to increase the agency's budget was aimed at letting it
handle its huge backlog of unfinished water projects, not start new ones. And he
said agency officials cannot get projects approved without the approval of
Congress and the White House.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It just doesn't happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, Corps projects are extremely popular on Capitol Hill, where
lawmakers compete with each other annually to try to win construction for their
home districts.
</P>
<P>
	   Even so, Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., chairman of the Environment and Public
Works committee, said poor communication between the Corps' military and
civilian leaders ``obviously is unacceptable and we need to straighten it out.''
</P>
<P>
	   He added, ``We want to make sure we don't lose this trust you have built up
over the years with the public.''
</P>
<P>
	   And Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., said reports on the Corps by The Washington Post
have left the impression that the shipping industry has been ``hotwiring''
projects to get them approved and ``have really taken a toll on your
credibility.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Corps, which dredges rivers and builds and maintains locks and dams, has
been under fire in recent weeks for allegedly falsifying its justifications for
some projects. Some of the criticism has come from within the Corps itself.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier this month, a sworn affidavit by a Corps economist accused it of
altering a $50 million study of locks on the Mississippi and Illinois rivers to
justify their expansion in order to speed barge traffic.
</P>
<P>
	   Corps officials have denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1731 </TRAILER>
