</P>
<P>
	   Marriott, Investors Reach Agreement
</P>
<P>
	   SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Thousands of investors suing Marriott over
limited partnerships formed in the 1980s have reached a tentative
settlement under which the hotel giant would buy back 120 Courtyard
by Marriott inns for $372 million. The agreement disclosed in court
today also calls for Marriott International Inc. and Host Marriott
Corp. each to pay $31 million to end lawsuits involving certain
limited partnerships aside from the Courtyard by Marriott deals.
Lawyers for both sides characterized the deal as a ``win-win''
situation providing liquidity for investors and value in the form
of hotels for Marriott. It still must receive the formal approval
of investors and the court.
</P>
<P>
	   Ford Relocating Luxury Brands
</P>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. will consolidate the North
American headquarters of its luxury brands in a new California
office, the company said today. The new offices of the Premier
Automotive Group will house the Jaguar, Volvo, Aston Martin,
Lincoln and Mercury brands. About 200 workers will be relocated
from New Jersey, where Volvo, Jaguar and Aston Martin have their
headquarters now.
</P>
<P>
	   Gulf Nations OK Oil Production Hike
</P>
<P>
	   DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Gulf oil ministers have
agreed to increase output to stabilize international markets --
where the price of oil is near an nine-year high. Officials
indicated today that most ministers at a meeting in Saudi Arabia
agreed to increase production, but have not agreed on how much. A
senior United Arab Emirates oil official said a production increase
will be gradual and in the range of 1.5 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
	   Concerns About Rising Gas Prices
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Already facing sticker shock at the gas pumps,
motorists likely will experience more price jolts this spring and
summer, energy experts said today. With crude oil prices high and
supplies low, refiners are not producing as much gasoline as
normal, a recipe for costlier fill-ups in the months ahead. the
Energy Department said prices could flare in the summer, a heavy
driving time, and the American Automobile Association warned of
possible short supplies then.
</P>
<P>
	   Panel Hears Day-Trading Dangers
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Day-trading firms accept people as customers
who shouldn't be trading and improperly raid customers' accounts to
make loans to other investors to keep them trading, Senate
investigators have found. Alyce Wenzel told a congressional hearing
today that before her son Scott Webb was shot and killed by a
fellow day trader in Atlanta in July, she was unaware he had
borrowed $30,000 from another investor. ``All his money was
borrowed to begin with,'' Wenzel testified before the investigative
subcommittee of the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee. Also
today, the National Association of Securities Dealers, a
self-policing brokers' group, announced that it had disciplined
eight day-trading firms or individuals running them, for alleged
misuse of customer funds, improper loans and misleading
advertising.
</P>
<P>
	   Worker Walkouts Hit Low in 1999
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of major strikes by American
workers hit a record low of 17 in 1999. Last year's big labor
disputes idled about 73,000 workers for an average of 16 days each,
the Labor Department said today. The agency's Bureau of Labor
Statistics has been keeping a count since 1947 of strikes involving
1,000 or more workers and lasting at least one shift. The previous
record low of 29 strikes was set in 1997. In 1998, there were 34
walkouts involving 387,000 workers. The largest strikes involved
12,000 workers at casinos in Atlantic City, N.J., and 11,000
teachers each in Detroit and Washington state.
</P>
<P>
	   Judge Halts Strike at Union Pacific
</P>
<P>
	   OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- A federal judge issued a temporary
restraining order today on a union strike at Union Pacific Railroad
just hours after it hit selected points across the Midwest and
West. The railroad argued the strike over the closing of a facility
in Wyoming was illegal. Arguments were set for Monday in U.S.
District Court in Omaha.
</P>
<P>
	   MSNBC To Run a Silicon Valley Summit
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- MSNBC is bringing together leaders of the
Internet economy for a televised ``Summit in Silicon Valley'' on
Sunday. The two-hour discussion, scheduled for 8 p.m. ET, features
leaders of America Online, Amazon.com, Cisco, eBay, Yahoo!,
Priceline.com, Gateway and others. A top Microsoft executive is
also expected. Issues of personal privacy and who sets the rules
for Internet commerce and taxation will be discussed. Tom Brokaw is
the moderator and a panel of journalists will also ask questions.
</P>
<P>
	   J.C. Penney To Close 45 Stores
</P>
<P>
	   PLANO, Texas (AP) -- J.C. Penney Co. Inc. plans to close about 45
department stores and 289 Eckerd drug stores in an effort to turn
the troubled retailer around. Company officials said today that
most of the closures will occur by midyear, but they declined to
say which of its 1,150 department stores and 2,900 Eckerds will
close or how many jobs will be lost. The Plano-based store and
catalog retailer also announced that it lost $12 million in the
quarter ended Jan. 29. The 8-cents-per-share loss compared with a
gain of $207 million, or 77 cents a share, in the same period a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   Gap Beats 4Q Earnings Expectations
</P>
<P>
	   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Fourth-quarter earnings at Gap Inc. beat
expectations, helped by the retail company's rapid expansion. For
the three months ended Jan. 29, 2000, the company said today that
its earnings were up 32 percent to $414 million, or 47 cents per
share, from $314 million or 35 cents a share during the same period
last year. Analysts had predicted fourth-quarter earnings of 45
cents a share.
