<HEADLINE> Senate Targets Russian Aid to Iran  </HEADLINE>
   By JIM ABRAMS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Following suit with the House, the Senate on Thursday
voted unanimously to step up efforts to stop Russia and other countries from
supplying Iran with weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
	   Supporters said the bill was necessary despite the ascendance of reformers
in the Tehran government. ``Fresh breezes of change are blowing through Iran,''
said Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn. But he said those changes have not reached
the highest levels of government ``who unfortunately have made Iran a pariah
state.''
</P>
<P>
	   The 98-0 Senate vote followed a 419-0 House vote last September on a
slightly different version. The House is expected to adopt the Senate bill and
send it to the president.
</P>
<P>
	   The White House threatened to veto the House bill, saying it complicated
international nonproliferation efforts, but congressional sources said the
administration was satisfied with changes in the Senate bill giving the
president more flexibility in imposing sanctions.
</P>
<P>
	   David Leavy, a spokesman for the National Security Council, said the issue
was at the top of the U.S.-Russia agenda and ``we believe we have all the tools
we need to address the problem of proliferation to Iran. Therefore, additional
legislation is not necessary.''
</P>
<P>
	   Asked if the president would sign the Senate bill, Leavy said, ``We'll see
where the legislative process takes us.''
</P>
<P>
	   The legislation, unlike a previous bill that President Clinton did veto in
1998, does not require the president to impose sanctions against Russia and
others that supply missiles or weapons to Iran.
</P>
<P>
	   It directs the president to submit reports to Congress every six months
identifying foreign persons or countries that transfer weapons material or
technology to Iran and authorizes him to impose sanctions if he so chooses.
</P>
<P>
	   It does make payments to the Russian space agency in conjunction with work
on the International Space Station contingent upon the president's concluding
that Russia is complying with nonproliferation policies.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This sends a clear message to Russia that they must do more'' to stop the
flow of weapons and nuclear technology to Iran, said Senate Majority Trent Lott,
R-Miss., a chief sponsor of the bill with Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
	   Lieberman said the bill was also a message to the administration that
``relations with Russia are not more important than our national security.''
</P>
<P>
	   Russia has actively assisted Iran in its nuclear power program, which the
United States fears is being used to cover up secret efforts to build nuclear
weapons, and China and North Korea have helped Iran produce ballistic missiles
now thought to have a range of at least 800 miles.
</P>
<P>
	   After the 1998 veto, the administration moved on its own to announce
sanctions on seven Russian entities suspected of transferring weapons technology
to Iran. In 1999 three more Russian groups were added to the list.
</P>
<P>
	   But Lott said this had not done enough to stop the flow of weapons
technology. He said that with enactment of the bill, ``we hope the
administration will use it to our country's advantage and impose sanctions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1735 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0219 </DOCNO>
