<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Medicare Plan Attacked  </HEADLINE>
   By ALICE ANN LOVE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration renewed its criticism of a
Medicare overhaul plan favored by Senate Republicans, saying it would
substantially increase out-of-pocket costs for retirees.
</P>
<P>
	   The plan could drive Medicare premiums up by as much as 47 percent -- not
including extra charges for a new prescription drug benefit, according to a
letter from Health and Human Services Department actuary Richard Frost.
</P>
<P>
	   The letter, dated Feb. 23, arrived in time for Democratic lawmakers to
distribute it at a Senate Finance Committee hearing Thursday, where the
legislation was under discussion.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., cosponsor of the bill with Rep. John Breaux,
D-La., called the letter ``just a continuation of the administration's
disinformation campaign on Breaux-Frist, which is the only proposal that
provides both outpatient prescription drugs and true Medicare reform.''
</P>
<P>
	   Frist and Breaux served last year on a bipartisan Medicare reform
commission, where the plan they are now peddling did not win enough support from
Democrats to be formally recommended to Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton has since come out with his own Medicare plan, featuring a
new prescription drug benefit providing $1,000 worth of coverage annually at a
cost to retirees of $26 per month.
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans have criticized Clinton's plan as an attempt to score political
points for Democrats without seriously tackling the tough problems of curbing
Medicare costs, which are expected to balloon once baby boomers begin to retire
in about a decade.
</P>
<P>
	   The Breaux-Frist plan would seek to save the government money by making
Medicare more like the health benefits many younger Americans get from
employers.
</P>
<P>
	   Senior citizens would choose among pre-approved private health plans and
Medicare would pay a standard portion of the premium. Those choosing higher-cost
plans would pay more out-of-pocket, but supporters say competition among plans
would bring costs down for many.
</P>
<P>
	   A government-run Medicare option would continue to be available. But it
would have to compete under the same financial constraints as private plans.
</P>
<P>
	   For that reason, Foster said in his letter that staying in the
government-run plan -- which would be most similar to what retirees are used to
now -- could cost 25 percent more out-of-pocket.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, Foster's letter noted that the Breaux-Frist legislation calls
for money from premiums collected from Medicare beneficiaries to cover 12
percent of Medicare's total costs. Under current law, premiums are scheduled to
cover about 10 percent of costs in 2003, 11 percent by 2010, and in 2015, the
program would run short of cash.
</P>
<P>
	   A boost to premiums covering 12 percent of costs in 2003 would translate
into a 22 percent rise in premiums, Foster estimated. Monthly Medicare premiums
are currently $45.50 per month.
</P>
<P>
	   Those choosing new prescription drug coverage offered under the Breaux-Frist
proposal would pay an additional charge, which Foster estimated at about $57.50
per month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1736 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Durable Goods Orders Fall in Jan.  </HEADLINE>
    By JEANNINE AVERSA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Slackening demand for airplanes and electronics caused
orders for big-ticket goods to dip last month, but the fall isn't a big setback
for U.S. manufacturers, which continue to possess a lot of momentum, economists
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Orders to U.S. factories for durable goods -- items expected to last at
least three years -- slipped 1.3 percent in January to a seasonally adjusted
$214.8 billion, the Commerce Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Even with the decline, overall durable-goods orders last month were still
6.5 percent higher than January 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   "The real story is that American manufacturing interests are sustaining the
momentum of a freight train going full bore," said KeyCorp economist Ken
Mayland.
</P>
<P>
	   January's performance, not as weak as the 2 percent drop many analysts were
predicting, followed a breakneck 6.3 percent increase in December, the strongest
pace in seven years.
</P>
<P>
	   The Federal Reserve has nudged up interest rates four times since June to
slow the economy and keep inflation under control. Although that has made
borrowing more expensive for businesses and consumers, economists believe the
economy continues to grow at a too rapid pace that probably can't be sustained
without triggering inflation. Given that, many economists widely expect the
central bank to raise rates again March 21.
</P>
<P>
	   Fears of higher interest rates caused blue-chip stocks on Wall Street to
swoon. The Dow Jones closed down 133.10 points to 10,092.63.
</P>
<P>
	   "Higher interest rates have not yet tempered factory activity," said Merrill
Lynch economist Stan Shipley.
</P>
<P>
	   Strong business and consumer spending is stoking the sizzling economy. On
Friday, the government will release a revised estimate for the economy's growth
in the last three months of 1999 and many economists believe it will be much
stronger than the 5.8 percent rate the government initially estimated.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite January's decline in durable-goods orders, manufacturers have put
the darkest days of a global financial crisis that struck in 1997 behind them,
economists said. The crisis severely depressed foreign demand for U.S. goods.
</P>
<P>
	   But Gordon Richards, economist for the National Association of
Manufacturers, said January's report may be the first sign that the "long
awaited slow down in the economy is beginning to emerge."
</P>
<P>
	   The Commerce Department said orders for electronic and other electrical
equipment including semiconductors, circuit boards, telecommunications equipment
and home appliances, fell 13.2 percent, the steepest drop since July 1997. In
December, these orders rose by 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Transportation equipment orders declined by 3.6 percent as decreases in
shipbuilding, tanks, airplanes and aircraft parts more than offset increases in
orders for cars and railroad equipment. Transportation orders rose by a whopping
23.2 percent in December.
</P>
<P>
	   This category is often volatile from month to month because it includes such
big purchases as airplanes. Excluding transportation, overall orders fell last
month by 0.5 percent, the first decline since October.
</P>
<P>
	   Weaker demand for transportation and electronic products offset big gains
elsewhere in the report.
</P>
<P>
	   Orders for industrial machinery, including computers and machine tools,
jumped by 12.3 percent last month, the strongest pace since February 1985. In
December, these orders fell by 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Primary metal orders, the category that includes steel, increased by 1.7
percent in January, following a 0.5 percent decline the month before.
</P>
<P>
	   Shipments of big-ticket goods, a good signal of current demand, grew by a
solid 2.8 percent in January, marking the eighth increase in the last nine
months.
</P>
<P>
	   Separately, the number of Americans filing new claims for unemployment
benefits last week fell by 7,000 to 278,000, suggesting that employers continue
to have trouble finding workers to fill job openings.
</P>
<P>
	   In another report, the volume of help-wanted advertising in major U.S.
newspapers edged up in January, the Conference Board said. Its index, which is
used as a gauge of changes in job supply, rose to 89 from 86 and suggests that
the nation's unemployment rate could dip this spring below the current 30-year
low of 4 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1737 </TRAILER>
