<HEADLINE> CNN Expanding W. Coast Presence  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- CNN is expanding its presence on the West Coast, adding a
bureau in Seattle and forming partnerships with business publications, in an
attempt to more aggressively cover the high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
	   Perhaps the most visible change is the move of CNN "Moneyline" anchor Willow
Bay to Los Angeles. She will anchor the show there each night, while co-anchor
Stuart Varney stays in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Bay's husband, Robert Iger, just got a job as second-in-command at the
California-based Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
	   The cable financial news network CNNfn is creating a new economy unit with
reporters in Los Angeles, San Francisco and Seattle. It will launch a one-hour
weekday program, airing at 5 p.m. ET starting next month, called "The N.E.W.
(New Economy Watch) Show" to focus on the high-tech economy.
</P>
<P>
	   CNN will also work with new print partners The Industry Standard and
eCompany Now, both based in San Francisco, as well as Fortune and The Financial
Times, the network said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   "The commitment we are making is to intensify the coverage of the global
shift to the new economy," said Shelby Coffey, president of CNNfn and CNN
Business News. Coffey, a former editor at the Los Angeles Times, has a West
Coast background.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
