<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lott Opposes Jurist Nomination  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID ESPO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Judge Richard Paez, nearing an appeals court confirmation
vote after a four-year delay, drew the opposition of Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott on Thursday while Democrats said President Clinton will lobby
wavering Republicans on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
	   The twin disclosures underscored the stakes involved in the fate of the
Hispanic jurist, who has been at the center of a lengthy dispute involving
racial politics as well as a long-running struggle between the White House and
the GOP-controlled Senate. A vote is expected by March 15.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I will be voting against Judge Paez,'' Lott, R-Miss., told reporters in a
brief interview outside the Senate chamber. He said be believes the 9th Circuit
Court of Appeals does not need additional judges at this time.
</P>
<P>
	   Beyond that, he said he would oppose the nomination because ``some of his
rulings and some of his political activities while on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
	   Lott ``has voted against nominations before,'' countered Sen. Barbara Boxer,
D-Calif., who is leading the effort to confirm Paez in the Senate. ``The most
important thing is that we get the vote,'' she said, and predicted there would
be enough support to elevate Paez to the appeals court.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Every Democrat is already in favor'' of Paez, she said, and Clinton is
``concentrating on Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans hold a 55-45 majority in the Senate, meaning that Democrats must
win the votes of five Republicans to assure confirmation. Two GOP lawmakers,
Sen. Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania and Orrin Hatch of Utah, chairman of the
Judiciary Committee, voted for Paez when the panel approved his nomination last
summer.
</P>
<P>
	   The nomination has become exhibit A in the Democratic catalogue of
complaints that Republicans have dragged their feet on Clinton's judicial
appointments. In addition, it has become intertwined with Democratic attempts to
depict the GOP as hostile to the interests of Hispanics -- allegations that
Republicans protest.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Some people don't want these folks on the court,'' Clinton told an
audience of Hispanic leaders recently at the White House, referring to his
appointments of Paez and two other Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They don't want you to know they don't want them on the court, because
then you might not want them in the Senate,'' Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is not rocket science. This is what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
	   Paez' supporters note he won confirmation once before as a federal judge,
and point to numerous expressions of praise for his work from attorneys. He
holds a ``well-qualified'' rating from the American Bar Association, its highest
grade.
</P>
<P>
	   Conservatives argue that the 9th Circuit has become a haven for judicial
activism, which they oppose, and that Paez himself has made questionable rulings
and remarks.
</P>
<P>
	   Some conservatives cite a speech in 1995 that they claim was critical of a
ballot proposition relating to affirmative action and a separate issue relating
to federal assistance for illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
	   A ruling in a 1998 case also angered conservatives, who claim Paez became
the first judge in the country to hold that an American corporation doing
business overseas could be held liable for human rights abuses committed by a
foreign government.
</P>
<P>
	   Paez' supporters take issue with that interpretation and say he was simply
making a procedural ruling as required under a precedent established by the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
	   John Czwartacki, Lott's spokesman, said the majority leader was also opposed
to confirming any judges for the 9th Circuit Court, which he said had proved
itself to be outside the ``mainstream'' and was frequently overruled by the
Supreme Court. Paez, a federal district court judge, was first nominated to the
appeals court in January 1996. The Judiciary Committee held a hearing but no
action was taken, and the nomination expired when Congress adjourned at year's
end.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton renominated Paez in January 1997, and the Judiciary Committee
approved the appointment by voice vote in March 1998, although six Republicans
indicated their opposition. No Senate vote was taken, and again the nomination
expired when Congress adjourned at year's end.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton nominated Paez for a third time in January 1999. The Judiciary
Committee sent the nomination to the floor in July on a vote of 10-8.
</P>
<P>
	   Paez' appointment aside, the Senate took action during the day on two
uncontroversial nominations. By votes of 98-0, it confirmed George B. Daniels as
a District Judge for the Southern District of New York and Kermit Bye as U.S.
Circuit Judge of the Eighth Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
