<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Revive Economic Theme  </HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN GALVIN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Waxing nostalgic about eight years' worth of his fiscal
policies, President Clinton on Thursday courted support for his plan to keep the
economy rolling along on the strength of the Internet and expansion into new
markets.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton went to the University of Pennsylvania to lay out his vision for the
economy before about 800 students, faculty and business leaders. He said he will
gather economists, CEOs and other experts at the White House on April 5 to
explore ``the big cutting-edge economic issues still before us.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``I want to ask them to identify ways we can build on America's strengths
and deal with our continuing weaknesses,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
	   The president listed many factors for the nation's climb out of recession
during his time in office, such as low interest rates, falling unemployment,
increased private sector investments and consecutive years of balanced budgets.
But, he said, scientific and technological developments have been the biggest
factor behind economic growth.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It clearly would not have gone on as long as it has, and the way it has,
without the information technology revolution,'' Clinton said. ``So the next
question is, can we keep it going? And, if so, how? And can we spread the
benefits to people and places that have been left behind?''
</P>
<P>
	   As Clinton spoke, the Dow Jones industrial average tumbled below 10,000. The
Dow finished down 133.41 at 10,092.63 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   After speaking, Clinton traveled on to New York for a pair of fundraisers
for the Democratic National Committee. He was spending the night at his family
home in Chappaqua, N.Y., and returning to the White House on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   In Philadelphia, Clinton returned to the setting where he discussed his
economic ideas as a candidate in 1992, a time he said was marked by deficits,
stubborn rates of unemployment and otherwise lackluster economic measures, even
though the nation was actually coming out of a recession that year.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I had some pretty basic ideas that all boiled down to my conviction that
there was nothing wrong with America that couldn't be fixed by what's right with
this country,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said taking advantage of investments in science and technology was one of
his highest priorities at that time, and the country has accomplished that
through explosive growth of the Internet, ``an economic transformation as
profound as that of the Industrial Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
	   Otherwise, he pinned the nation's progress on the ``responsible fiscal
policies'' of his tenure. But he also credited the ``good monetary policy'' of
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, who he said has resisted knee-jerk
interest rate increases to stave off inflation.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Mr. Greenspan was able to look at the evidence of the new economy over the
traditional ideology,'' Clinton said. ``He was resisting that because he knew
something was going on, even though no economist could give him a model which
proved it.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton made a pitch for open trade, arguing for allowing China entry into
the World Trade Organization and broadening U.S. presence in markets in Africa,
the Caribbean and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
	   He also advocated expanding into forgotten markets on U.S. soil, areas where
unemployment has remained persistently high, such as inner cities and Indian
reservations in Western states.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In order to keep this economy growing, we have to find more and more new
customers,'' he said. ``If you can create new businesses, new business owners,
and new employees, who are also consumers, within our borders, that will grow
the economy without inflation. It will also fulfill our moral responsibility to
give everybody a shot at the American dream.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1755 </TRAILER>
