<HEADLINE> Quotes From the Rev. Louis Farrakhan  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Some quotes from the Rev. Louis Farrakhan.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Hitler was a very great man. He wasn't great for me as a black man but he
was a great German and he rose Germany up from the ashes of her defeat. ... Now
I am not proud of Hitler's evil towards Jewish people, but that's a matter of
record. ...
</P>
<P>
	   ``Now that nation called Israel never has had any peace in 40 years and she
will never have any peace, because there can be no peace structured on
injustice, thievery, lying and deceit and using the name of God to shield your
gutter religion under His holy and righteous name''
</P>
<P>
	   -- A 1984 radio broadcast in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
	   Of his remarks calling Hitler ``great'': ``Sure I called Hitler a great man,
but I added that he was a wicked man. ... The Bible calls Babylon great, but it
does not say Babylon was good.
</P>
<P>
	   Of his remarks calling Judaism a ``gutter religion,'' Farrakhan said he was
``referring to the actions of the state of Israel using God and religion as a
cover for what I said was lying, stealing, murder.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm a victim of bigotry. ... Any white has unmitigated gall to call a
victim of white racism a racist.''
</P>
<P>
	   -- A 1988 speech in Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I would hope and pray that after the vilification of Louis Farrakhan is
over and done ... you will see me as a human being who is passionately concerned
not just for black people, but I am passionately concerned for this nation.''
</P>
<P>
	   -- The Washington Post, 1990.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm not the ugly fellow you would like to make people think I am. It's
necessary for the garbage to be cleared away so that a new and better
relationship can be structured between blacks and Jews.''
</P>
<P>
	   -- Newsweek, 1993.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Their aim was and is to destroy the reputation and character of Louis
Farrakhan in the eyes of the world and ultimately to destroy the Nation of
Islam.''
</P>
<P>
	   -- Of the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith, in 1994.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't own Hollywood. Who writes the plays, the songs that make us look
less than human? Do you mean to tell me that Jews have never done any evil to
black people? And if I point it out, does that mean that I hate Jews? ...
</P>
<P>
	   ``Were they involved in the slave trade? Yes, they were ... and to the
extent that they were involved, somebody has to bring them to account. And I
believe that has fallen on me.''
</P>
<P>
	   -- Newsday, 1994.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The people who own the newspapers from which you work ... they have a
guiding principle that they skew the news.''
</P>
<P>
	   -- A 1996 speech to the National Association of Black Journalists in which
he called his audience ``slave writers, slave media people'' for not standing up
to white bosses.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think we've given the government of the United States enough time! We
don't owe America a damn thing! It owes us!''
</P>
<P>
	   -- A 1997 Savior's Day speech in Chicago in which he said blacks should form
their own nation.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In the halls of power, there is no Arab, there is no Muslim. Is it any
wonder Clinton leans towards Israel, not Arab and Muslim states?''
</P>
<P>
	   -- A November 1998 speech at Detroit's Islamic Center of America.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I desire for us to use the universal language of music to help us to rise
above the fray that has been created by the usage of words. Therefore, this
concert will be held in a Christian Church, Christ Universal Temple, hosted by
Rev. Dr. Johnnie Coleman.''
</P>
<P>
	   -- In The Nation of Islam's newspaper, The Final Call, in July 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
