<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chasing Pleasure in 'The Wild Party'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    An AP Entertainment Review By MICHAEL KUCHWARA AP Drama Critic
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Who knew decadence could seem like such hard work? That's
the case at "The Wild Party," a strenuous new musical which opened Thursday at
off-Broadway's Manhattan Theater Club.
</P>
<P>
	   The party guests expend a great deal of energy in the pursuit of sex, drugs,
liquor and other adult amusements. Their efforts make for an unrelenting musical
that celebrates the idea of debauchery for debauchery's sake with grim
determination. After a while, such single-mindedness proves monotonous, despite
several attractive performances and an adventurous song or two by composer
Andrew Lippa.
</P>
<P>
	   This "Wild Party" is the first of two versions to open in New York this
season, with another arriving on Broadway in April. Let's hope the second
relaxes a bit and offers its festivities with a bit more style.
</P>
<P>
	   There's a high-pitched sameness to the MTC evening that director Gabriel
Barre and choreographer Mark Dendy have done little to alleviate. That's
surprising since the musical is based on Joseph Moncure March's 1920s poem, an
edgy ode to a hard-boiled decade where sharp, cynical humor often masked a sense
of loneliness. It offers a parade of creatures from Manhattan's high and low
lives who are more than a little desperate.
</P>
<P>
	   Lippa, who also wrote the book, concentrates on just a quartet of those
unhappy characters and uses the other partygoers for tawdry atmosphere. The
musical starts promisingly enough with an introduction to Queenie, a femme
fatale who sets the party in motion.
</P>
<P>
	   "Queenie was a blonde, and her age stood still, and she danced twice a day
in vaudeville," go the first lines of poem, and the musical, setting the scene
quite nicely.
</P>
<P>
	   It's a bit disconcerting, though, to watch a group of dancers, dressed in
black, then swirl around the stage in what appears to be a bargain-basement
knockoff of the stuff choreographer Bob Fosse did so well.
</P>
<P>
	   With a minimum of movement, Fosse knew how to sell sex on stage. Dendy's
dancers, though proficient, resemble arty gymnasts rather than erotic revelers.
</P>
<P>
	   Queenie shares an apartment with Burrs, a vaudeville clown with a terrible
temper and a penchant for beating the women who love him. She decides to give
the party as a means of getting back at the guy.
</P>
<P>
	   Her best friend Kate arrives with a new beau, a gentlemanly fellow named
Black. Partner-switching and the inevitable tragic consequences ensue.
</P>
<P>
	   If the tone of the party is enforced gaiety, the drink of choice for its
main characters seems to be gin and bitters, judging from Lippa's score. It is
ambitious and far-ranging, moving from jazz to contemporary pop that doesn't
sound out of place in this 1920s milieu. Fortunately, the four leads display
enough lung power to refloat the Titanic.
</P>
<P>
	   Julia Murney makes a fetching Queenie, sexy yet vulnerable. Brian d'Arcy
James captures Burrs' pathological jealousy. He is compellingly creepy. A
strident Idina Menzel pushes too far as the desperate Kate, overselling several
songs including a second-act opener "The Life of the Party," that practically
begs for a round of applause.
</P>
<P>
	   Most successful is Taye Diggs, as Black, who displays a low-key confidence
as the good guy trapped in a situation not of his making.
</P>
<P>
	   There are several musical diversions by other partygoers that prolong the
show rather than push it forward, although Alix Korey scores points as an
aggressive lesbian, singing an "Oh, where is the girl for me?" number that gets
most of the musical's few laughs.
</P>
<P>
	   Designer David Gallo's almost expressionistic setting of a cramped Manhattan
apartment occasionally splits apart, letting the performers make full use of the
wide, unwieldly MTC stage. This "Wild Party" could use even more opening up.
It's a cramped, strident celebration that doesn't allow theatergoers to have
much fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1810 </TRAILER>
