<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Accused Spy Says Calls Were Innocent  </HEADLINE>
   By ALEX VEIGA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- A U.S. immigration official charged with spying for Cuba was
denied bond Thursday after he told a federal judge he relayed supposedly secret
information only to protect a friend.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. Magistrate Judge Barry Garber ordered Mariano Faget to await trial in
jail, citing the severity of the charges against him, the weight of evidence and
the fact that Faget admitted divulging information he believed to be classified.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors say that on Feb. 11, Faget, 54, was given bogus information that
a U.S.-based Cuban diplomat was set to defect. Within minutes, Faget allegedly
went to his office, called a business associate with ties to Cuba on his
cellular phone, and told him ``a person we both know (is) ... one of the ones
working with the Americans.''
</P>
<P>
	   Later, Faget called the man from home and discussed the case in more detail,
the FBI said.
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities say Faget has been under investigation for a year. According to
court papers, Faget met with Cuban intelligence officials in Miami on at least
two occasions and contacted officials with the Cuban diplomatic mission in
Washington. One has been ordered to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
	   Faget, a native of Havana who has been a U.S. citizen since 1963, is on paid
leave from his post as a supervisor in the Miami office of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I want to have my day in court to defend myself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Faget told the judge that he called the business associate to protect him.
The associate, Pedro Font, 57, is a New York publicist Faget has known since the
1950s. Font was an associate of Faget's father, the head of an anti-communist
agency in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
	   Faget and Font are also associates in America-Cuba, a company created to
promote business with Cuba once the U.S. trade embargo is lifted. Font hasn't
been charged with any crime.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal prosecutors said Faget had no reason to warn Font he was in danger
and asked him whether he told FBI agents of his concern for Font's life. Faget
said he did not.
</P>
<P>
	   Edward O'Donnell Jr., Faget's attorney, argued that Faget would not benefit
from supporting Fidel Castro's regime in Cuba, because as long as Castro remains
in power, America-Cuba can't broker business deals there.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutor Curtis Minor argued against bond for Faget. He said authorities
found six passports and other identification cards in Faget's desk drawer,
indicating he might try to avoid the trial.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He has lied to his employer, lied to the FBI, deceived the federal
government, repeatedly lied to federal agents,'' Minor said. ``He's continued to
submit falsehood after falsehood.''
</P>
<P>
	   The hearing came a day after an American couple who were part of a Cuban
ring that spied on U.S. military installations and exile political groups were
sentenced to seven years in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   Linda and Nilo Hernandez pleaded guilty last year to being unregistered
agents of a foreign government. Three other people charged with being part of
the ring have been sentenced to prison terms between 3 1/2 years and seven
years.
</P>
<P>
	   Five others are scheduled to go on trial in May, while four have never been
captured.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1813 </TRAILER>
