<HEADLINE> Prosecutor: Kohl Withheld Arms Files  </HEADLINE>
   By TONY CZUCZKA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BERLIN (AP) -- Helmut Kohl's government withheld records on an arms deal
under scrutiny for possible kickbacks, a German prosecutor told parliamentary
investigators Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The contract for tank sales to Saudi Arabia is among several deals being
examined by a parliamentary committee set up to determine whether political
donations influenced decisions under Kohl, who was German chancellor for 16
years until 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Winfried Maier, a prosecutor in the southern city of Augsburg, testified to
the panel that Kohl's government rejected his 1997 request for minutes of the
Federal Security Council, a Cabinet committee that approved the tank sale. Maier
said the government told him the material was confidential.
</P>
<P>
	   The tank sale is an element in the campaign finance scandal that has
engulfed Germany's Christian Democrats since Kohl admitted in December that he
accepted up to $1 million in off-the-books donations in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
	   His refusal to name donors has fed speculation that the donations prompted
political favors by his government -- something Kohl has hotly denied,
particularly in relation to the tank deal.
</P>
<P>
	   The scandal has grown to include covert accounts at the federal and state
levels, large sums of campaign money from unexplained sources and millions in
fines for the party for false financial reports.
</P>
<P>
	   The arms sale emerged as a possible link in November with reports that
businessman Karlheinz Schreiber gave $500,000 in cash to a Kohl aide in 1991,
allegedly in connection with the tanks.
</P>
<P>
	   Schreiber, now living in Canada, is being sought by Augsburg prosecutors on
tax evasion charges.
</P>
<P>
	   In another business deal that has come under question, the leader of the
parliamentary inquiry asserted Thursday that Kohl must have known that crucial
files vanished while he was in office.
</P>
<P>
	   Volker Neumann cast doubt on statements by Kohl and his former chief of
staff that they were unaware of irregularities in records on the privatization
of the Leuna refinery in former East Germany, sold to France's Elf Aquitaine in
1994.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Now that is hard to imagine,'' Neumann, a member of the governing Social
Democrats, said on German radio.
</P>
<P>
	   Lawmakers are looking at the deal because of long-running suspicions that
kickbacks flowed to clinch it, a prestige project for Kohl after German
unification.
</P>
<P>
	   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's government, which took over from Kohl, has
cited gaps in the chancellery files on Leuna and has appointed a special
investigator to track down what happened.
</P>
<P>
	   However, the top Christian Democrat legislator on the investigating
committee said Thursday that six folders of copied records on Leuna had been
stashed in a high-security part of parliament's archive. Kohl's former chief of
staff, Friedrich Bohl, has said he never destroyed any files or gave such an
order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
