<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Govt's False Claim Recoveries Rise  </HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Since the False Claims Act was amended in 1986 to
encourage private whistleblowers, more than $3.5 billion has been recovered from
companies that allegedly defrauded the government, almost half in the last 2 1/2
years.
</P>
<P>
	   Almost half of these false claims cases and more than half of the recovered
money involve health care fraud, which has burgeoned in recent years, the
Justice Department reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   During this period, the government has turned over $550 million of the total
recoveries to the private whistleblowers who first complained that their
companies were defrauding the taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
	   The False Claims Act allow private citizens, known as ``relators,'' to file
civil lawsuits on behalf of the United States alleging that private companies --
usually their employer -- have submitted fraudulent claims for government
payments.
</P>
<P>
	   The private whistleblowers who file these so-called qui tam lawsuits are
given 15 to 25 percent of any money won in settlement or judgment if the federal
government intervenes in the case and takes over as the plaintiff. The private
whistleblowers can be given up to 30 percent of the money recovered if the
government does not join the case, but they pursue it to victory on their own.
</P>
<P>
	   Private whistleblower provisions were first added to the False Claims Act in
1976, but in 1986, Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, and Rep. Howard L. Berman,
D-Calif., sponsored amendments that made it easier for whistleblowers to benefit
from their actions.
</P>
<P>
	   Before the 1986 amendments, there was no minimum in the law, like the
current 15 percent, for sharing the recovered money with the whistleblowers.
Judges set the amount and gave some whistleblowers nothing. The amendments also
relaxed a provision that had precluded whistleblowers from sharing in the
recovery if there had been any information whatsoever about the fraud in
government files before the lawsuit, even if it was not even information to act.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It took us 12 years -- the end of fiscal year 1998 -- to recover $2
billion in civil fraud cases brought under the whistleblower provisions,'' said
Acting Attorney General David W. Ogden, head of the department's civil division.
``We have reached the $3 billion mark just 16 months later.''
</P>
<P>
	   More than 3,000 such lawsuits have been filed since 1986, rising from 33 in
the year after the amendments to 483 in the last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the recoveries, more than $3.3 billion has come in cases the Justice
Department entered, and $211 million in cases tried by whistleblowers after the
department declined to enter.
</P>
<P>
	   The law's private whistleblower provisions ``have provided a remarkable
return for the taxpayers of this country,'' Ogden said. The department's
recovery of more than $3.3 billion ``demonstrates that the public-private
partnership encouraged by the statute works and is an effective tool in our
continuing fight against the fraudulent use of public funds.''
</P>
<P>
	   Recent recoveries include $375 million, the largest civil recovery in a
health care fraud case, from National Medical Care, now also known as Fresenius
Medical Care, North America, the largest provider of kidney dialysis services in
the nation. A private whistleblower alleged the company submitted false claims
for laboratory tests and conspired to pay illegal kickbacks.
</P>
<P>
	   Beverly Enterprises Inc., the nation's largest operator of nursing homes,
agreed to pay $170 million to settle allegations it defrauded Medicare by
fabricating records to make it appear nurses were devoting much more time to
Medicare patients than they actually did.
</P>
<P>
	   Olsten Corp. paid $40.9 million to settle allegations that it and
Columbia/HCA disguised unallowable acquisition costs as allowable management
fees when Columbia/HCA bought home health agencies in several states.
</P>
<P>
	   False claim whistleblowing is not confined to health care fraud. Recently,
Chevron Corp. agreed to pay $86.2 million to resolve allegations it and its
affiliates underpaid royalties for oil produced on leased federal and Indian
land since 1988. Mobil Oil Corp. agreed to pay $45 million, and Oxy-USA Inc.
paid $7.3 million to resolve similar royalty underpayment claims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
