<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bausch &AMP; Lomb Tries Laser Surgery  </HEADLINE>
    By BEN DOBBIN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Just as prices for laser-eye surgery look set to
tumble, Bausch &AMP; Lomb Inc. is jumping into the competitive U.S. market with a
vision-correction machine it boasts is better than those of industry leaders
Visx Inc. and Summit Technology Inc.
</P>
<P>
	   The world's biggest eye-care company said Thursday it has gotten approval
from the Food and Drug Administration to sell its Technolas 217 excimer-laser
system, which is already the market leader abroad for treating both
nearsightedness and farsightedness.
</P>
<P>
	   Its emergence on the domestic front seems likely to intensify a price war
among providers of laser-eye surgery equipment and contribute to the drop in
consumer prices. Analysts predict as many as 1.7 million Americans will undergo
laser eye surgery this year, up from about 900,000 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Douglas Christopher, an analyst with Crowell Weedon &AMP; Co. in Los Angeles,
said he expects the price of the surgery to drop from an average of $2,100 per
eye to about $1,500 per eye this year.
</P>
<P>
	   "Even if it went to $1,000 an eye, that's still a lot of money," he said.
"But I don't think Bausch &AMP; Lomb are in the market to become a low-price leader.
They're looking at it as a technological advancement, maybe more of a premium
product."
</P>
<P>
	   Laser eye surgery is rarely paid for by insurance because it isn't
considered medically necessary.
</P>
<P>
	   In the surgery, a beam of light is used as a scalpel to make the cornea
slightly flatter and allow light to focus on the image-sensing retina. The laser
removes minute layers of tissue with a dose of "cold" ultraviolet energy that
leaves surrounding tissue undamaged.
</P>
<P>
	   The Technolas 217 machines, which sell for $525,000 each, employ a more
precise laser beam that is just millimeters in diameter -- three times narrower
than standard broad-beam lasers, the company said.
</P>
<P>
	   In clinical studies, Bausch &AMP; Lomb said 99.7 percent of patients had their
vision improved to 20/40 or better, and 87.3 percent ended up with practically
perfect 20/20 vision or better.
</P>
<P>
	   The technology also diminishes the risk of patients ending up with
uncomfortable side effects, the company said. After surgery, some patients
experience a glare, which is described as long lines of light coming from a
point of light. Others see a halo, a ring around a point of light.
</P>
<P>
	   Bausch &AMP; Lomb said it will charge a $100 royalty fee for each use of its
system by doctors, matching the fee charged by Santa Clara, Calif.-based Visx
and Summit Technologies of Waltham, Mass. This week, Summit and Visx lowered the
per-procedure fee they charge doctors from about $250.
</P>
<P>
	   Bausch &AMP; Lomb said its laser-eye products account for about 10 percent of
its $1.8 billion in revenues. It said it commands about one-third of the
overseas market with 500 machines in place, and its next closest competitor is
Japan's Nidek Co. with 430 machines.
</P>
<P>
	   Visx operates an estimated 500 machines in the United States and 360
machines abroad, while Summit Technologies has 235 machines in this country and
170 abroad, it said.
</P>
<P>
	   Visx shares rose $2.44 to $18.75 on the Nasdaq Stock Market Thursday,
gaining back some of the heavy losses it incurred earlier in the week after
announcing the cut in its royalty fee.
</P>
<P>
	   Summit shares, which also fell earlier in the week, rose 19 cents to $8.
Both stocks are at or near 52-week lows. Shares of Bausch &AMP; Lomb gained 69 cents
to $59.19 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1833 </TRAILER>
