<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AstraZeneca's Operating Profit Down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LONDON (AP) -- Despite strong demand for its anti-ulcer drug Prilosec,
AstraZeneca's fourth quarter operating profit slipped 1 percent due to heavy
wholesaler stocking earlier in the prior quarter, the company said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Anglo-Swedish drugmaker had a fourth-quarter operating profit of $796
million, down from $806 million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Sales rose 9 percent to $3.9 billion from $3.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Prilosec, sold as Losec outside the United States, accounted for nearly 39
percent of sales in the quarter. Prilosec, the world's best selling prescription
drug, posted a 14 percent increase in sales in the quarter to 1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Sales of Prilosec, the world's biggest selling prescription drug, rose 24
percent in 1999 to $5.91 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   AstraZeneca was formed last April when Astra of Sweden merged with Britain's
Zeneca to form one of the world's largest pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
	   The company attributed the decline in fourth quarter sales to unusually
strong third-quarter sales, which took away some of the business normally seen
in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
	   	   One-time costs of the merger of Astra and Zeneca cost took more than $ 1
billion off of 1999 earnings. AstraZeneca's net profit for the year was $ 1.14
billion, down 54 percent from $2.47 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Strong growth in U.S. sales contributed to an 11 percent increase in annual
operating profit, but one-time merger costs dragged down the company's 1999
earnings.
</P>
<P>
	   Annual operating profit before unusual charges was $3.91 billion, up from
last year's pro-forma result of $3.51 billion, the company said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   AstraZeneca posted $18.45 billion in sales last year, up 4 percent from
$17.79 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Pharmaceutical sales in the United States, AstraZeneca's biggest market,
grew 23 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
	   However, the company's prospects are clouded by the expiration in October
2001 of the U.S. patent for Prilosec. It is not yet clear if AstraZeneca can
persuade enough doctors of the merits of Nexium, its next generation Losec. The
drug has not yet been approved in the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   "They've had a cracking year," said Peter Cartwright, an analyst at London
brokerage Williams de Broe. "Losec is in a huge growth phase, and one or two of
the other drugs are doing pretty well.
</P>
<P>
	   "But can this current growth be maintained, and can they successfully switch
(doctors) to Nexium?"
</P>
<P>
	   AstraZeneca chief executive Tom McKillop was optimistic that Nexium would
win converts.
</P>
<P>
	   "From the reports we're getting back, the doctors see very real benefits in
faster healing, higher percentages of patients healed and economic benefits," he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Swedish authorities dealt AstraZeneca a surprise setback by revoking its
patent for Losec in Sweden, the company confirmed Thursday. The company is
appealing.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. shares of AstraZeneca fell $2.62 1/2 cents to $31.50 in trading at 4:30
p.m. Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1834 </TRAILER>
