<HEADLINE> McCain supporter challenging closed primary structure  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A John McCain supporter who previously was an
independent New York voter has now sued to be able to vote in the state's closed
GOP primary, and a federal judge will hear her arguments next week.
<P>
	   If Wendy Van Wie of Columbiaville wins her action, an extra 2.2 million
independent voters would be able to participate in New York's "Super Tuesday"
Democratic and Republican primaries.
</P>
<P>
	   Most of Texas Gov. George Bush's supporters in New York, including state GOP
Chairman William Powers, have come out against opening the state primaries to
independent voters. "I think the Republican primary should be for Republicans,
not Democrats and independents," Powers said.
</P>
<P>
	   However, McCain got major help from independent and Democratic voters in his
victories in New Hampshire and Michigan. "If they get a favorable decision, I
think we'll sweep New York," said former Congressman Guy Molinari, McCain's New
York chairman.
</P>
<P>
	   Van Wie, 46, who previously had not registered for a political party in New
York, registered as a Republican after a federal judge on Feb. 4 ordered McCain
placed on the ballot statewide in New York. However, Van Wie, a recent Albany
Law School graduate, was told state law would keep her from voting in a New York
presidential primary until 2004.
</P>
<P>
	   Voters who switch parties or join parties after being uncommitted have to
wait until after a presidential election to participate in their new party's
primary. That means the first primary she would be able to vote in would be in
2004.
</P>
<P>
	   "I personally want to vote for John McCain," said Van Wie, who along with
Lloyd Wright of Dutchess County asked a federal judge to stop New York's
political parties from keeping independent voters out of their primaries. "I
don't really care who anyone else votes for, though. I just want people to be
able to vote."
</P>
<P>
	   Her lawyer, Susan Galvin, says unregistered voters in New York can wait
until at least 20 days before a primary and register for a party and vote in the
primary.
</P>
<P>
	   "The non-enrolled are treated clearly differently and in a discriminatory
manner from the way in which people who are not registered to vote at all in New
York are treated," she said. "If you haven't bothered to register or you haven't
bothered to exercise your right to vote in the past, you get preferential
treatment over somebody who is registered and has voted."
</P>
<P>
	   Molinari, Galvin and Van Wie all insisted Thursday that the McCain campaign
is not behind the lawsuit to get more independent support into the Republican
primary.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. District Judge David Hurd on Thursday issued a temporary restraining
order keeping political parties from rejecting primary applications of
registered independent voters. He will hold a hearing on Tuesday in Utica to
decide whether the restraining order should become permanent.
</P>
<P>
	   Named in the injunction are Powers, Democratic Party Chairwoman Judith Hope,
GOP Gov. George Pataki, the state Board of Elections, the Columbia County Board
of Elections and the Dutchess County Board of Elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
