<HEADLINE> EU, Latin American Nations Seek Ties  </HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT WIELAARD Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   VILAMOURA, Portugal (AP) -- The European Union and 18 Latin American nations
pledged Thursday to pursue closer economic and trade ties, concluding three days
of meetings highlighted by discussion of two upcoming free-trade accords.
</P>
<P>
	   In a joint statement, foreign and trade ministers from the EU and Latin
America said they want to see a fresh round of world trade liberalization talks
after the failure to reach agreements in Seattle last November.
</P>
<P>
	   Colombian Foreign Minister Guillermo Fernandez de Soto told reporters the
meeting produced ``a degree of consensus to strengthen the multilateral trading
system.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Europeans endorsed the view of Latin American nations that to avoid the
sort of mayhem in the streets that forced the collapse of the World Trade
Organization's talks in Seattle, less developed nations must have a bigger voice
in the WTO.
</P>
<P>
	   Both sides said they want to see a comprehensive round of trade
liberalization talks that also cover agricultural subsidies and the service
sector.
</P>
<P>
	   During the talks, the EU and Mexico nailed down final details of a free
trade accord to be signed by Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo on the sidelines
of a March 23-24 EU summit meeting in Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
	   The agreement will eventually give European companies access to the Mexican
market nearly matching the unfettered access U.S. and Canadian companies will
have by 2003 under the North American Free Trade Agreement. The accord with the
EU foresees free trade in industrial goods by 2007 and in farm products by 2010.
</P>
<P>
	   Representatives from the EU and the Mercosur nations of Argentina, Brazil,
Paraguay, Uruguay and Chile -- Latin America's best economic performers -- will
start negotiations in April for an association agreement that must eventually
include a free trade arrangement.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Developing our relationship with Latin America is a real priority,'' EU
External Affairs Commissioner Chris Patten told reporters after the EU's three
days of back-to-back talks with Mexico, Central and South American nations.
</P>
<P>
	   Jaime Gama, the Portuguese foreign minister and the meeting's host, said:
``We are stepping up our relationship. Since 1998, we (the EU) have been the
largest investor in Latin America, and we are the region's second biggest
trading partner.''
</P>
<P>
	   The EU and Latin American sides also agreed to cooperate more in
international organizations such as the United Nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
