<HEADLINE> Body of man found inside Manhattan restaurant  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - A man was found with his throat slashed Thursday inside
a Manhattan restaurant, a meat cleaver atop his body, and a 12-inch carving
knife at his side. Police were not certain if the items were used in the murder.
<P>
	   The scene was described as "pretty bloody" by Police Capt. Robert Iovino.
The victim had multiple stab wounds and was found in the rear of the restaurant,
in the kitchen area, he added.
</P>
<P>
	   No arrests had been made by Thursday evening and police did not comment on a
motive. Iovino said the victim had not yet been positively identified by family
members.
</P>
<P>
	   However, identification found on the victim showed that he was Nicola
Orobello, 62, of Flushing Queens, said a police source, speaking on condition of
anonymity. Business records showed that the Upper East Side restaurant - Erminia
- was owned by Orobello.
</P>
<P>
	   Two women identified by employees at the scene as Orobello's mother and wife
were described as hysterical as they entered the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
	   The victim was found at 11:30 a.m. when a linen delivery man discovered the
body as he pushed open an unlocked door at the East 83rd Street location, police
said.
</P>
<P>
	   It was not immediately known how long the victim had been dead. Police were
investigating whether he had been in the restaurant late Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Erminia, a 15-year-old restaurant, specializes in Italian cuisine. The
Zagat's restaurant guide describes it as a tiny, intimate hideaway with
excellent food "worth every penny for that much romance."
</P>
<P>
	   "At least one engagement" would occur per night, the guide added.
</P>
<P>
	   Stanley Poll, 60, was outside the restaurant Thursday and said he comes a
few times a year. He called Erminia a "romantic hideaway," and spoke highly of
Orobello.
</P>
<P>
	   "He made you feel like you were somebody special," Poll said.
</P>
<P>
	   -----
</P>
<P>
	   Restaurant location: 250 E. 83rd St., Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
