<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Medicare Plan Attacked  </HEADLINE>
   By ALICE ANN LOVE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration renewed its criticism of a
Medicare overhaul plan favored by Senate Republicans, saying it would
substantially increase out-of-pocket costs for retirees.
</P>
<P>
	   The plan could drive Medicare premiums up by as much as 47 percent -- not
including extra charges for a new prescription drug benefit, according to a
letter from Health and Human Services Department actuary Richard Foster.
</P>
<P>
	   The letter, dated Feb. 23, arrived in time for Democratic lawmakers to
distribute it at a Senate Finance Committee hearing Thursday, where the
legislation was under discussion.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., co-sponsor of the bill with Sen. John Breaux,
D-La., called the letter ``just a continuation of the administration's
disinformation campaign on Breaux-Frist, which is the only proposal that
provides both outpatient prescription drugs and true Medicare reform.''
</P>
<P>
	   HHS spokeswoman Melissa Skolfield defended Foster's analysis. While it may
serve the administration's position, she said that he serves in a
congressionally established office created to assess the financial condition of
Medicare and his conclusions are reached independently.
</P>
<P>
	   Frist and Breaux served last year on a bipartisan Medicare reform
commission, where the plan they are now peddling did not win enough support from
Democrats to be formally recommended to Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton has since come out with his own Medicare plan, featuring a
new prescription drug benefit providing $1,000 worth of coverage annually at a
cost to retirees of $26 per month.
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans have criticized Clinton's plan as an attempt to score political
points for Democrats without seriously tackling the tough problems of curbing
Medicare costs, which are expected to balloon once baby boomers begin to retire
in about a decade.
</P>
<P>
	   The Breaux-Frist plan would seek to save the government money by making
Medicare more like the health benefits many younger Americans get from
employers.
</P>
<P>
	   Senior citizens would choose among pre-approved private health plans and
Medicare would pay a standard portion of the premium. Those choosing higher-cost
plans would pay more out-of-pocket, but supporters say competition among plans
would bring costs down for many.
</P>
<P>
	   A government-run Medicare option would continue to be available. But it
would have to compete under the same financial constraints as private plans.
</P>
<P>
	   For that reason, Foster said in his letter that staying in the
government-run plan -- which would be most similar to what retirees are used to
now -- could cost 25 percent more out-of-pocket.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, Foster's letter noted that the Breaux-Frist legislation calls
for money from premiums collected from Medicare beneficiaries to cover 12
percent of Medicare's total costs. Under current law, premiums are scheduled to
cover about 10 percent of costs in 2003, 11 percent by 2010, and in 2015, the
program would run short of cash.
</P>
<P>
	   A boost to premiums covering 12 percent of costs in 2003 would translate
into a 22 percent rise in premiums, Foster estimated. Monthly Medicare premiums
are currently $45.50 per month.
</P>
<P>
	   Those choosing new prescription drug coverage offered under the Breaux-Frist
proposal would pay an additional charge, which Foster estimated at about $57.50
per month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1906 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lott Opposes Jurist Nomination  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID ESPO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Judge Richard Paez, nearing an appeals court confirmation
vote after a four-year delay, drew the opposition of Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott on Thursday while Democrats said President Clinton will lobby
wavering Republicans on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
	   The twin disclosures underscored the stakes involved in the fate of the
Hispanic jurist, who has been at the center of a lengthy dispute involving
racial politics as well as a struggle between the White House and the
GOP-controlled Senate. A vote is expected by March 15.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I will be voting against Judge Paez,'' Lott, R-Miss., told reporters in a
brief interview outside the Senate chamber. He said be believes the 9th Circuit
Court of Appeals does not need additional judges at this time.
</P>
<P>
	   Beyond that, he said he would oppose the nomination because ``some of his
rulings and some of his political activities while on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
	   Lott ``has voted against nominations before,'' countered Sen. Barbara Boxer,
D-Calif., who is leading the effort to confirm Paez in the Senate. ``The most
important thing is that we get the vote,'' she said, and predicted there would
be enough support to elevate Paez to the appeals court.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Every Democrat is already in favor'' of Paez, she said, and Clinton is
``concentrating on Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans hold a 55-45 majority in the Senate, meaning that Democrats must
win the votes of five Republicans to assure confirmation. Two GOP lawmakers,
Sen. Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania and Orrin Hatch of Utah, chairman of the
Judiciary Committee, voted for Paez when the panel approved his nomination last
summer.
</P>
<P>
	   The nomination has become exhibit A in the Democratic catalogue of
complaints that Republicans have dragged their feet on Clinton's judicial
appointments. In addition, it has become intertwined with Democratic attempts to
depict the GOP as hostile to the interests of Hispanics -- allegations that
Republicans protest.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Some people don't want these folks on the court,'' Clinton told an
audience of Hispanic leaders recently at the White House, referring to his
appointments of Paez and two other Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They don't want you to know they don't want them on the court, because
then you might not want them in the Senate,'' Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is not rocket science. This is what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
	   Paez' supporters note he won confirmation once before as a federal judge,
and point to numerous expressions of praise for his work from attorneys. He
holds a ``well-qualified'' rating from the American Bar Association, its highest
grade.
</P>
<P>
	   Conservatives argue that the 9th Circuit has become a haven for judicial
activism, which they oppose, and that Paez himself has made questionable rulings
and remarks.
</P>
<P>
	   Some conservatives cite a speech in 1995 that they claim was critical of a
ballot proposition relating to affirmative action and a separate issue relating
to federal assistance for illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
	   A ruling in a 1998 case also angered conservatives, who claim Paez became
the first judge in the country to hold that an American corporation doing
business overseas could be held liable for human rights abuses committed by a
foreign government.
</P>
<P>
	   Paez' supporters take issue with that interpretation and say he was simply
making a procedural ruling as required under a precedent established by the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
	   John Czwartacki, Lott's spokesman, said the majority leader was also opposed
to confirming any judges for the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals whom he felt would
not return the panel ``to the mainstream.'' He said 9th Circuit opinions have
frequently been overruled by the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
	   Paez, a federal district court judge, was first nominated to the appeals
court in January 1996. The Judiciary Committee held a hearing but no action was
taken, and the nomination expired when Congress adjourned at year's end.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton renominated Paez in January 1997, and the Judiciary Committee
approved the appointment by voice vote in March 1998, although six Republicans
indicated their opposition. No Senate vote was taken, and again the nomination
expired when Congress adjourned at year's end.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton nominated Paez for a third time in January 1999. The Judiciary
Committee sent the nomination to the floor in July on a vote of 10-8.
</P>
<P>
	   Paez' appointment aside, the Senate took action during the day on two
uncontroversial nominations. By votes of 98-0, it confirmed George B. Daniels as
a District Judge for the Southern District of New York and Kermit Bye as U.S.
Circuit Judge of the Eighth Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
