<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SEC OKs E-Exchange's Bid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Securities and Exchange Commission has approved a
request by the International Securities Exchange, a proposed electronic exchange
for trading options on stocks of U.S. companies, to become the first exchange to
register with the SEC since 1973.
</P>
<P>
	   In announcing its approval Thursday, the SEC said that although the ISE
hasn't started operating, it already has had a "positive impact" on the options
market. Since the exchange filed its application a year ago, the nation's
options exchanges have reduced their transaction fees, the SEC said.
</P>
<P>
	   Options give their holders the right to buy or sell stock at a specified
price before a specified date.
</P>
<P>
	   The ISE will not have a physical trading floor as the other options
exchanges do. It will become a self-regulatory organization, overseeing and
enforcing participants' compliance with its own rules and federal securities
laws.
</P>
<P>
	   Several new electronic stock-trading networks, called electronic
communications networks or ECNs, have applied to the SEC to be put on the same
legal footing as traditional exchanges such as the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   The last exchange to become officially registered was the Chicago Board
Options Exchange in 1973.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
