<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Critics Seek To End HUD Program  </HEADLINE>
   By PAUL SHEPARD Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Accusing the Department of Housing and Urban Developing
of losing $1.9 million through an administrative blunder, a frequent critic of
the agency called Thursday for abolishing its Community Builders program.
</P>
<P>
	   Senator Christopher Bond, R-Mo., who is chairman of the Senate
Appropriations Committee's panel on veterans affairs, HUD and independent
agencies, said the embattled program championed by the Clinton Administration
and designed to increase outreach to HUD clients was a failure.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Community Builders program was designed as a public relations tool
that does not provide community builders with the needed expertise or
understanding of HUD housing...,'' Bond said.
</P>
<P>
	   A HUD spokesman later denied there was a $1.9 million loss, saying the
figure represents housing subsidies the government continued to cover but listed
on its books as ``holding costs'' after foreclosing on a landlord.
</P>
<P>
	   The Community Builders program was created in 1997 to separate ``customer
service'' and public outreach functions in HUD from the department's operation,
monitoring, enforcement and policing of dozens of housing programs.
</P>
<P>
	   The politically partisan nature of the dispute was in evidence Thursday as
Democratic senators on Bond's subcommittee voiced support for the program while
Republicans criticized it.
</P>
<P>
	   About 40 percent of the department's Community Builders are paid between
$75,000 and $100,000 a year, and they often duplicate work done through other
HUD programs, both factors that critics contend have eroded morale at the
agency.
</P>
<P>
	   The program has been touted by the Clinton administration as one of Housing
Secretary Andrew Cuomo's achievements in overhauling the department. But
problems with it first came to light last September when auditors in the
department concluded in a report that is poorly conceived, poorly run,
overpoliticized and a waste of money.
</P>
<P>
	   In the report, HUD's independent inspector general's office called the
Community Builders program an ``overly expensive'' endeavor that exacerbates the
department's long-standing management problems.
</P>
<P>
	   In one case cited Thursday, Bond said a community builder interfered with a
sale of a property and cost HUD $1.9 million in additional holding costs. Bond
also said five Community Builders were fired for ethical and conduct violations
while five others were identified with probable ethics problems.
</P>
<P>
	   Deputy HUD Secretary Saul N. Ramirez Jr. didn't address the issue of the
$1.9 million loss during the hearing.
</P>
<P>
	   In an interview after the hearing, however, HUD spokesman Douglas Kantor
called Bond's statement ``factually inaccurate,'' saying the delay in selling
the foreclosed property didn't cost any additional taxpayer funds. Kantor said
the $1.9 million ``holding costs'' represents rent subsidies that HUD would have
covered for the building's tenants whether or not it had sold the property
earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   Ramirez told the Senate panel many at HUD are ``puzzled'' why the program
has been criticized so harshly and defended it as helping the agency become ``a
model for federal customer relations.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ramirez also said several independent consulting firms, including Ernst &AMP;
Young, have praised the program as innovative and effective.
</P>
<P>
	   About half of the Community Builders were transferred into the program from
other divisions within HUD. The other half were hired from the outside and are
working under two-year contracts.
</P>
<P>
	   Bond said he fears that the administration will try to put those 400 people
on the government's permanent payroll if the program is terminated next
September, as critics hope.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1912 </TRAILER>
