<HEADLINE> Euro Slips Below Parity With Dollar  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- The euro slipped back below parity with the dollar Thursday
after spending much of the trading day above the $1 level. The dollar edged
lower against the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
	   In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at 99.33 cents, down from
$1.0029 late Wednesday. The decline came just two days after the European
currency regained the $1 level for the first time in nearly a month.
</P>
<P>
	   Traders said they viewed the setback as temporary, with sentiment toward the
year-old European unit gaining some strength over the past several weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar gave back some of its recent gains against the yen, two days
after touching a six-month high against the Japanese currency. The dollar was
quoted at 111.06 yen in late trading, down from 111.30 yen Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar also was quoted at 1.6202 Swiss francs, up from 1.6071, and
1.4559 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4618. The British pound fell to $1.6000
from $1.6028.
</P>
<P>
	   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no longer
traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. Based on Thursday's
euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.9695 German marks, up from 1.9504; 6.6055
French francs, up from 6.5413; and 1,949.82 Italian lire, up from 1,930.86.
</P>
</TEXT>
