<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Closing arguments begin in drug conspiracy case of two accused drug  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - Both sides in the drug conspiracy trial of two men
accused of running the largest drug ring in Camden's history began their final
push Thursday to make their case to a jury.
<P>
	   Jose "J.R." Rivera, 40, a Camden businessman, is on trial as the alleged
financier and procurer for the multimillion dollar cartel. Luis "Tun" Figueroa,
was the enforcer, prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
	   Both are charged with drug conspiracy. Rivera is charged with two counts of
money laundering. If convicted, both face life in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   The two are among 15 people charged in the case in 1998 when prosecutors
toppled the drug ring that had operated in Camden for nearly a decade. The
others pleaded guilty.
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities say the drug organization used violence - even murder - to
control a lucrative drug trade. It was so entrenched, authorities say, it took
years to break up the organization.
</P>
<P>
	   The jury, which heard seven weeks of testimony, is expected to begin
deliberating next week after U.S. District Judge Joseph H. Rodriguez instructs
the panel on the law.
</P>
<P>
	   In closing arguments in federal court Thursday, Assistant U.S. Attorney
Kevin Smith methodically summarized the prosecution case, which included
testimony by admitted drug dealers who once worked for the drug organization.
</P>
<P>
	   "You don't have to like these people as witnesses," Smith told the jury of
12 women and three men. But he added, "your disgust does not make them liars."
</P>
<P>
	   However, defense attorney Carlos Martir, who represents Figueroa, said
prosecutors "made a pact with devils" who were willing "to lie, to fabricate, to
give the government what it wants."
</P>
<P>
	   "Nothing has matched the snow job that the government has presented here,"
Martir said in his closing arguments. "There is no excuse for the government's
handling of this case."
</P>
<P>
	   At least nine convicted drug dealers testified against Rivera and Figueroa,
detailing how the organization distributed hundreds of kilos of cocaine in
Camden through two open-air drug markets.
</P>
<P>
	   Figueroa - described by the prosecutor as "the man with the gun" - was also
implicated by witnesses in the 1993 execution-style slaying of a rival drug
dealer. He will be tried later in state court on a murder charge.
</P>
<P>
	   Martir noted that the prosecution's key witness, Juan Marquez, a former drug
dealer-turned informant, did not record any conversations with Figueroa. He
called Marquez "a psychological study in paranoia, fabrication and lies."
</P>
<P>
	   "He fabricated and he exaggerated," said Martir, who will continue his
closing arguments when the trial resumes Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
	   The testimony during the trial included allegations that Camden Mayor Milton
Milan bought kilo shipments of cocaine in 1993, before he was elected. Witnesses
also alleged that Milan tipped off drug dealers after he became mayor in 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   Milan, who has acknowledged Rivera as a boyhood acquaintance, has denied the
allegations. He is not charged in the case and has not been accused of any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities have said the drug ring flourished because of its high-ranking
connections. Witnesses said law enforcement officers shook down drug dealers for
bribes and tipped them off about upcoming raids.
</P>
<P>
	   The drug organization raked in profits from a thriving business, using the
money to purchase homes, cars, businesses and a boat, Smith said. They made so
much cash that it was difficult to hide the money, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Rivera, who owns a gym and auto store in Camden, held money for drug dealers
and exchanged their small bills - usually for one hundred dollar bills, Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Smith described Rivera as "the money man," an advisor and counselor to the
drug organization. He presided at meetings and settled disputes among members,
he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "J.R. had risen in the Camden drug world to a level of power," Smith said
during his closing arguments that lasted more than four hours. "No one will mess
with J.R."
</P>
<P>
	   Investigators eventually closed in on the drug organization, and one-by-one
13 codefendants in the case pleaded guilty and many agreed to testify against
Rivera.
</P>
<P>
	   According to Smith, when Rivera was arrested he said, "so you finally got
me."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
