<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EPA Said Lagging on Arsenic Rules  </HEADLINE>
   By H. JOSEF HEBERT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Environmental Protection Agency was accused Thursday
of not moving quickly enough to strengthen a 58-year-old standard that
determines how much arsenic should be allowed in drinking water.
</P>
<P>
	   The Natural Resources Defense Council said it will soon file a lawsuit
forcing the EPA to update the old arsenic standard, maintaining that it allows
thousands of people to be exposed to unhealthy levels of the cancer-causing
chemical.
</P>
<P>
	   Nearly a year ago, a report by the National Academy of Sciences recommended
more stringent controls on arsenic in drinking water. While the report
acknowledged there are uncertainties about how arsenic exposure triggers cancer,
it said the current EPA regulation ``does not sufficiently protect public
health.''
</P>
<P>
	   The EPA agreed with the report's findings, and officials said a new arsenic
standard for drinking water was being developed. The agency had hoped to get a
new standard out by January, but did not meet the deadline. Officials still
hoped for a new standard this year.
</P>
<P>
	   The NRDC said it was planning to file the lawsuit to nudge the EPA toward
action. The group wants the maximum arsenic content in water to be no more than
3 parts per billion. Currently the EPA standard, dating back to 1942, is 50
parts per billion and the international standard -- which the EPA is considering
-- is 10 parts per billion.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What will it take the EPA to do something about this enormous health
risk?'' said Erik Olson, a water quality specialist at the NRDC, a leading
environmental advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
	   He said Congress told the EPA to update its arsenic regulation, put in place
in 1942, in the mid 1970s and again in the 1980s, and then set a Jan. 1, 2000
deadline.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, the NRDC said that the EPA's own data shows that more than 34
million people in at least 6,900 communities drink tap water from water supply
systems containing arsenic at average levels that pose a health risk.
</P>
<P>
	   The NRDC said it examined the results, from the EPA, of more than 100,000
water samples from 24,000 public water systems in 25 states.
</P>
<P>
	   The American Water Works Association, representing private experts on
drinking water quality, has endorsed the call for stricter standards for
arsenic.
</P>
<P>
	   But the group said if the international standard of 10 micrograms per liter
is adopted, it could cost more than $1 billion. The group estimated 2,200 of the
56,000 U.S. water supply systems would be affected by such a rule change.
</P>
<P>
	   The EPA has estimated that a 5 parts per billion standard would cost $686
million a year to implement and that a 2 parts per billion standard would cost
$2.1 billion a year, according to the NRDC report.
</P>
<P>
	   Inorganic arsenic, the form most likely to cause cancer, occurs naturally in
the earth and is released into ground water that travels through rocks and soil.
The highest exposure to arsenic is in drinking water from wells as opposed to
areas, including most urban areas, that get drinking water from lakes and
streams, officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1917 </TRAILER>
