<HEADLINE> Gravano's old enemies: We told you so  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Back in Sammy Gravano's hometown, his old enemies
shouted a chorus of "I told you so" Thursday after the Mafia killer was arrested
in Arizona on drug charges.
<P>
	   As for friends of "The Bull" ... well, they weren't saying much.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruce Cutler, attorney for jailed mob boss John Gotti, can be counted among
the enemies. He was easy to locate, and eager to condemn Gravano as "the great
impostor, a liar, a coward."
</P>
<P>
	   That was in the first minute of his news conference, when Cutler was just
warming up. Later, he condemned the former Gambino family underboss as "a
Tasmanian devil, full of lies."
</P>
<P>
	   "I was waiting for this," Cutler continued in his Manhattan office. "You
can't change the nature of a man ... He is a reprobate, a craven liar. Gravano
is motivated only by greed. I guess he didn't steal enough before."
</P>
<P>
	   That's before he entered the federal witness protection program, which the
Brooklyn-born Gravano did in the spring of 1995 after testifying against Gotti
in a trial that ended with the Dapper Don being sentenced to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   Gravano, who admitted killing 19 people, wound up with just a 5-year jail
sentence because of his deal with the government. His testimony eventually led
to the convictions of three dozen mobsters, including Genovese family boss
Vincent "The Chin" Gigante.
</P>
<P>
	   Attorney Ron Kuby, who represents the families of Gravano's 19 murder
victims in an ongoing civil suit, said there was no surprise that career
criminal had allegedly returned to his illegal ways.
</P>
<P>
	   "All of that nonsense about Gravano being reformed, repudiating his criminal
ways, was just another scam to get over, just as Sammy Gravano has done
successfully his entire adult life," Kuby said.
</P>
<P>
	   The families of Gravano's murder victims filed suit under the state's "Son
of Sam" law, looking to seize profits from the killer's biography, "Underboss."
The law prevents criminals from making a profit on their crimes.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal authorities who helped Gravano get a deal - letting him serve
barely two months for each murder - had little to say Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The FBI, which cut the deal, had no comment, said spokesman Joe Valiquette.
Former U.S. Attorney Andrew Maloney, whose office prosecuted Gotti, did not
return a phone call.
</P>
<P>
	   Cutler said he planned to call Gotti at the federal prison in Marion, Ill.,
to pass on word of Gravano's arrest - hopefully in the next week. But Cutler
predicted that the ex-head of the Gambino family would not delight in the fall
of his nemesis.
</P>
<P>
	   "The only concern John Gotti would have about this," Cutler said with a
straight face, "is concern about the teenagers who were buying those pills."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
