<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands Protest Austrian Govt.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Blowing whistles and banging drums, thousands of
people marched through the capital Thursday to protest the inclusion of Joerg
Haider's party in Austria's ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
	   About 12,000 people had joined the peaceful demonstration within an hour of
its start, said Vienna police spokesman Martin Stradel.
</P>
<P>
	   The march followed a Saturday demonstration in which tens of thousands of
Austrians and other Europeans gathered in the heart of Vienna to rally against
the new government, led by Wolfgang Schuessel of the conservative People's Party
and including Haider's far-right Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
	   Afterwards, demonstration organizers called for protests to continue every
Thursday until the government steps down.
</P>
<P>
	   Anti-government rallies have become a near-daily practice in Vienna since
the new government coalition took office Feb. 4. The European Union, Israel and
the United States have taken measures to isolate Austria diplomatically.
</P>
<P>
	   The outrage stems from Haider's opposition to both immigration and rapid EU
expansion. He has also been criticized for previous statements praising some
Nazi policies, but he has since apologized for those.
</P>
<P>
	   In an interview broadcast Thursday on Slovak state television STV, Schuessel
dismissed demonstrators' power to bring about a change of government, but said
he had nothing against peaceful protests.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There are many of those who do not agree with us, but there are even more
who do agree with the new government,'' he said. ``The protests will surely not
bring an end to this government.''
</P>
<P>
	   Schuessel reiterated his criticism of the EU sanctions.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The way the EU presented them is not correct,'' he told STV. ``The
sanctions were applied without any dialogue, which is unusual and it contradicts
the spirit of European agreements.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
