<DOCNO> APW20000224.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Police Intercept Mail Bombs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Authorities have intercepted eight booby-trapped video
cassettes, the latest in a recent wave of attempted mail bombings targeting
journalists and politicians, police said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Four of the intended targets included a news director and a reporter from
the tabloid newspaper La Hora, the assistant director of the newspaper Hoy, and
a television anchor from Channel 4.
</P>
<P>
	   Police refused to identify the other intended recipients, or to say when
they found the eight bombs.
</P>
<P>
	   The explosives were the same type sent both to a top evangelical Indian
leader, who became suspicious of the package and summoned police on Monday, and
to Channel 10 news director Rafael Cuesta, the only known person to be injured
in the terror campaign. He suffered minor wounds on his hands and face.
</P>
<P>
	   Police said that bomb was designed to frighten and not to cause serious
injury. But they have said nothing about how powerful the other bombs were.
</P>
<P>
	   It was unclear what the motive was for the attacks. At least some of the
mail bombs were preceded by written threats, but news agencies and authorities
refused to reveal the contents of those threats.
</P>
<P>
	   Groups calling themselves the National Liberation Army of Ecuador and the
People's Combatants Group have both claimed responsibility for mailing the
explosives.
</P>
<P>
	   Ecuador's 123-member Congress received special seminars on Monday and
Tuesday on how to detect mail bombs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1944 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disney Tops First Lady's Donors  </HEADLINE>
   By SHANNON McCAFFREY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mickey Mouse's pockets are deep for Hillary Rodham
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
	   Walt Disney executives and their families donated $56,500 to Clinton's U.S.
Senate campaign, more than any other company. But as an industry, lawyers topped
the list, giving the Yale Law School graduate $666,879, according to an analysis
of her campaign reports by the Center for Responsive Politics. The entertainment
industry was next, donating $439,740, the nonpartisan center said.
</P>
<P>
	   The analysis also showed that 56 percent -- or $3.4 million -- of the $6
million Clinton has raised from individuals came from outside New York.
Donations poured in from 45 other states and the District of Columbia, the
center found. Clinton raised a total of $8.1 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You can see that this really is a national race,'' said Larry Makinson,
executive director of the center that studies money and political campaigns.
``She's successfully tapping traditional Democratic donors, like lawyers. The
twist is how well she's connected to Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton drew $668,779 from California, topping all states except New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the $2.7 million raised in New York, $2.2 million came from the New York
City metropolitan area, mostly from wealthy neighborhoods on Manhattan's Upper
East Side.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton received just $13,250 from her new hometown of Chappaqua, the
Westchester County town where she and the president recently bought a $1.7
million home.
</P>
<P>
	   Other heavy givers to Clinton were Massachusetts ($382,600), Texas
($312,824), District of Columbia ($276,940), and Illinois ($229,700), the center
found.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton has been fighting the perception that she is a carpetbagger in New
York, where she had not lived or work until launching her Senate bid. The
campaign of her GOP rival, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, also has been
receiving large numbers of out-of-state contributions.
</P>
<P>
	   But Bruce Teitelbaum, Giuliani's campaign manager, criticized the first lady
Thursday for ``running a campaign based out of California, Illinois and
Massachusetts with money from wealthy trial lawyers and movie producers.''
</P>
<P>
	   He said less than half of Giuliani's $11.5 million campaign warchest has
come from outside New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Aside from lawyers and entertainment executives, the analysis also showed
Clinton was popular with the securities and investment industry. Her
second-largest single donor company was Goldman Sachs Co., where executives and
their families donated $39,120. Other top donors also are in the financial
services industry: Deloitte and Touche ($28,750); Patton Boggs ($25,500) and
Citigroup ($22,000).
</P>
<P>
	   Corporations cannot give money to candidates directly, political action
committees they create may contribute, along with their employees.
</P>
<P>
	   Makinson said he expected to conduct a similar analysis of the mayor's fund
raising when the data becomes available electronically from the Federal Election
Commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 1945 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0279 </DOCNO>
