<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State officials try to explain Newark school budget shortfall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Contrite New Jersey education officials Thursday
appeared before lawmakers to try to explain how a $58 million surplus turned
into a $58 million deficit in the five years since the state took over the
beleaguered Newark school district.
<P>
	   State-appointed Newark school officials rarely followed mandatory fiscal
controls such as uniform accounting practices and monthly financial reports. In
turn, state officials did not enforce them, Education Commissioner David Hespe
told a joint meeting of the Senate and Assembly education committees.
</P>
<P>
	   Hespe, who said the financial mess is "ultimately my responsibility,"
released department memos showing that former Commissioner Leo Klagholz was
aware of the magnitude of the problem as early as February 1998 but took no
corrective action.
</P>
<P>
	   "It seems like everybody thought they were off the hook by sending a memo.
They could say, don't blame me, I told them," said Senate Committee Chairman
Robert J. Martin, R-Morris.
</P>
<P>
	   Klagholz and former school Superintendent Beverly Hall, on whose watch the
budget problems occurred, did not attend the hearing. Both issued written
statements blaming budget shortfalls on city political influence prior to the
July 1995 state takeover and saying they did their best to remedy them.
</P>
<P>
	   Martin called the hearing because the state will have to come to the school
district's rescue to close the budget gap. The state already provides about 80
percent of the district's $555 million budget in state aid. The district, the
state's largest with 40,000 pupils, is among the state's 30 so-called special
needs districts. It is also one of three districts taken over by the state due
to academic failure and fiscal mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
	   "Before we provide any more money, we have to ascertain what went wrong,
where has the money gone and who is at fault," Martin said.
</P>
<P>
	   According to a Department of Education report released at the hearing, the
district's surplus gradually dwindled, beginning in 1995, the year of the state
takeover, as school officials regularly spent money they did not have.
</P>
<P>
	   "Who was doing the budget analysis at this time?" Martin asked Hespe. "No
business would operate with a checkbook and not know what was in their account."
</P>
<P>
	   State officials, meanwhile, became aware of a looming fiscal crisis, the
report shows.
</P>
<P>
	   In a February 1998 memo, Klagholz was briefed about "the lack of internal
controls in Newark's central office" and a "poor" communication between school
and state officials. The memo writer, one of Klagholz's top lieutenants, asked
the commissioner to personally intervene with Hall.
</P>
<P>
	   A year later Klagholz wrote a memo to Hall warning her that unresolved
budget problems "are becoming an unacceptable vulnerability both for you and the
department." But by that point, both the commissioner and the superintendent had
both submitted their resignations.
</P>
<P>
	   Hespe said state officials crafted solutions but did not act upon them.
</P>
<P>
	   The state could have withheld state aid, ordered corrections, or fired
school officials, but did not, the commissioner said.
</P>
<P>
	   The commissioner could not rule out possible criminal behavior. He said the
full dimensions of the budget mess won't be known until the final audits are
complete later this spring.
</P>
<P>
	   Democrats railed against the department's record of inaction.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is memo after memo of people covering themselves instead of taking
action," Assemblyman Rudy Garcia, D-Hudson, said of the report.
</P>
<P>
	   Republican leaders, meanwhile, called on the state auditor to conduct a
thorough review of the school district's finances.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is February. They were going to do it in July. I said speed it up,"
said Assembly Speaker Jack Collins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
