<HEADLINE> Some Poll Results on Campaign 2000  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Some results of state polls on the presidential race. When results don't
total 100 percent, the remainder supported other candidates, didn't know or
refused to answer.
</P>
<P>
	   New York (March 7)
</P>
<P>
	   Asked of likely Republican primary voters
</P>
<P>
	   If the next presidential primary were held today, who would you support if
the candidates were:
</P>
<P>
	   George W. Bush
</P>
<P>
	   -- 45 percent (Manhattanville College)
</P>
<P>
	   -- 43 percent (CBS-New York Times)
</P>
<P>
	   John McCain
</P>
<P>
	   -- 35 percent (Manhattanville College)
</P>
<P>
	   -- 36 percent (CBS-New York Times)
</P>
<P>
	   Alan Keyes
</P>
<P>
	   -- 4 percent (Manhattanville College)
</P>
<P>
	   -- 4 percent (CBS-New York Times)
</P>
<P>
	   Undecided
</P>
<P>
	   -- 14 percent (Manhattanville College)
</P>
<P>
	   -- 17 percent (New York Times
</P>
<P>
	   (Bush led McCain in the state by as much as 40 points as recently as
December)
</P>
<P>
	   Asked of likely voters in the Democratic primary
</P>
<P>
	   -- Al Gore, 59 percent
</P>
<P>
	   -- Bill Bradley, 28 percent
</P>
<P>
	   (Bradley led Gore in some New York polls as recently as November.)
</P>
<P>
	   Florida (March 14)
</P>
<P>
	   Asked of likely voters in the Republican primary
</P>
<P>
	   -- George W. Bush, 52 percent
</P>
<P>
	   -- John McCain, 34 percent
</P>
<P>
	   Asked of likely voters in the Democratic primary
</P>
<P>
	   -- Al Gore, 57 percent
</P>
<P>
	   -- Bill Bradley, 30 percent
</P>
<P>
	   The Mason-Dixon poll of potential voters in Florida was taken Tuesday and
Wednesday of 421 likely voters in the Democratic primary and 407 likely voters
in the Republican primary and each sample has an error margin of plus or minus 5
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
	   The CBS-New York Times poll of 374 likely voters in the New York Republican
primary and 542 likely voters in the Democratic primary has an error margin of
plus or minus 4 percentage points for Democrats and 5 percentage points for
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
	   The Manhattanville College poll of 305 likely voters in the New York
Republican primary was taken Monday and Tuesday and has an error margin of plus
or minus 6 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
