<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 US Muslim Groups Expected To Meet  </HEADLINE>
   By KEN KUSMER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PLAINFIELD, Ind. (AP) -- Leaders of two orthodox Muslim groups long at odds
with Louis Farrakhan's Nation of Islam are expected to attend Farrakhan's annual
gathering this weekend, raising the prospect that the religion's fractured U.S.
followers may eventually unite.
</P>
<P>
	   Mainstream Islamic leaders from other nations also planned to attend the
Nation of Islam Saviour's Day events in Chicago and will look for signs that
Farrakhan's group is embracing orthodox Islamic beliefs, a leader of the key
immigrant Muslim group in this country said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They want to watch this transformation,'' said Sayyid Syeed, secretary
general of the Islamic Society of North America. ``They will be disappointed if
that transformation does not take place. There should at least be some
commitment in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, Farrakhan and W. Deen Mohammed, the son of Nation of Islam
founder Elijah Muhammad and head of the black and orthodox Muslim American
Society, have scheduled a joint news conference Friday. The Islamic Society and
other mainstream Muslims recognize Mohammed's group as orthodox.
</P>
<P>
	   Farrakhan and other Nation of Islam leaders did not return calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
	   However, an article posted Feb. 16 on the Nation of Islam's Web site quoted
Ishmael Muhammad, an assistant to Farrakhan, as saying a ``mega-highlight'' of
the Saviour's Day weekend would be the unification of the Nation of Islam with
followers of W. Deen Mohammed.
</P>
<P>
	   Mohammed, who confirmed that he planned to attend the gathering, said the
three groups would not be uniting under one name. He said he would be taking
particular note of Farrakhan's speech on Sunday, and hoped Farrakhan steers
clear of anti-white and anti-Semitic comments.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We expect a different Farrakhan,'' Mohammed, 66, said Thursday from his
office in Calumet City, Ill. ``And if he's not and he comes out the wrong way
Sunday, I think he's really going to finish things for himself. Nobody will ever
trust him again.''
</P>
<P>
	   About a month ago, Mohammed met with Farrakhan, who was battling prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
	   Farrakhan, 66, said last December that a ``near-death experience'' earlier
in the year had left him a changed man. Since then he has stressed unity for all
races and religions.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't know if it was his fear of dying or a combination of things ...
that have really caused him to be very sincere about the unity of Muslims -- at
least one voice, a language of unity that does not conflict the picture of
Muslims in America,'' Mohammed said.
</P>
<P>
	   Mohammed said his organization has more than 2 million followers. The Nation
of Islam, which does not release membership figures, is estimated to have about
200,000.
</P>
<P>
	   Syeed acknowledged the Nation of Islam would need time, perhaps years, to
completely move away from Elijah Muhammad's original doctrines, including a
belief that whites are ``devils.''
</P>
<P>
	   However, he said moves in recent years to observe the Friday prayers and to
fast during the holy month of Ramadan had left him encouraged the Nation of
Islam would fully embrace orthodoxy within four or five years.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have noticed a desire on his part to introduce his followers to
mainstream Islam. We understand that these things cannot happen overnight,''
Syeed said in an interview Wednesday at the Islamic Society's headquarters in
Plainfield, near Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
	   Syeed said he will speak Saturday on fundamental principles of Islam and the
need for the Nation of Islam to join a universal Islamic alliance in the United
States. His society says it represents 4 million Muslims in the United States,
most of them immigrants from Muslim countries.
</P>
<P>
	   Orthodox leaders are eager for Farrakhan's group to embrace conventional
beliefs as fast-growing Islam seeks to join the American mainstream. Syeed said
normalization would bolster the image of the religion, which many Americans
associate chiefly with terrorist acts by Muslim activists abroad.
</P>
<P>
	   Anti-white and anti-Semitic statements from Farrakhan and the Nation of
Islam did nothing to help that public relations problem, Syeed said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Demonization has been our major challenge in America,'' said Syeed, who
directs the day-to-day activities of the Islamic Society, an umbrella
organization of 500 Islamic groups.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nation of Islam has held its own interpretation of the Muslim creed,
``There is no god but God and Mohammed is his prophet.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Farrakhan group has believed that God became incarnate in W.D. Fard of
Detroit, who was Elijah Muhammad's teacher, and that Muhammad is the final
prophet to mankind. Orthodox Muslims believe the final prophet was Mohammed of
Mecca, who founded Islam in the seventh century.
</P>
<P>
	   Elijah Muhammad led the Nation of Islam for decades, but after his death in
1975 his son W. Deen led the movement toward orthodoxy. Farrakhan then
re-established the Nation of Islam in 1978 and followed Muhammad's original
doctrines.
</P>
<P>
	   Farrakhan's initiatives brought a cautious reaction from Marilyn Mayo of the
Anti-Defamation League, a Jewish organization based in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have to be skeptical because Farrakhan really is a master of words. We
have to see if he follows through with deeds,'' she said. ``In the past he has
talked about atonement many times but at various events has still fueled the
crowd with anti-Semitic and racist rhetoric.''
</P>
<P>
	   Mayo also noted that the Nation of Islam Web site provides links to other
sites that post anti-Semitic material.
</P>
<P>
	   Professor Lawrence Mamiya of Vassar College, who is completing a major
survey of black Islamic groups, said he had doubts about Farrakhan's willingness
to completely embrace orthodox Islam.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I believe that he would like the orthodox Muslim world to accept his group
as a sect of Islam, with its own peculiarities and practices, but many orthodox
Muslims are very critical of his attempt to keep remnants of the old Nation,''
Mamiya said. ``It's a question how far he's willing to go. I doubt that he will
make the change completely.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   AP Religion Writer Richard N. Ostling contributed to this story from New
York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
