<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Won't Pull Back Diplomat in US  </HEADLINE>
   By ANITA SNOW Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HAVANA (AP) -- Marking an important date in Cuba's independence fight, a
senior communist official on Thursday defiantly declared that a Washington-based
diplomat targeted for expulsion will remain in the United States as long as
possible.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite U.S. allegations of spying, the diplomat, Jose Imperatori, has done
nothing wrong, said Ricardo Alarcon, the president of Cuba's National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He will remain,'' said Alarcon, who is President Fidel Castro's top
official on Cuba-U.S. affairs. ``We have not pulled him back and we are not
going to pull him back.''
</P>
<P>
	   Alarcon challenged U.S. State Department officials to ``present their
alleged proof'' and to ``not fear debate'' on the matter. ``They have the chance
to rectify and ask for forgiveness,'' Alarcon said.
</P>
<P>
	   In Washington, Immigration and Naturalization Service spokeswoman Maria
Cardona said that, if the diplomat has not left the United States by 1:30 p.m.
EST on Saturday, ``the appropriate agencies will take appropriate action as
necessary.'' She would not say what that action might be.
</P>
<P>
	   State Department officials said earlier that Imperatori's diplomatic
immunity could be terminated if he was not recalled, making him subject to U.S.
law and possible arrest.
</P>
<P>
	   The Cuban ceremony marking the 105th anniversary of the ``Grito de Baire''
-- the Battle Cry of Baire -- was broadcast live on state television from the
town of Baire in eastern Cuba.
</P>
<P>
	   Issued in Baire on Feb. 24, 1895, the cry marked the beginning of Cuba's
second and last major war of independence against Spanish colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, Cuba finds itself immersed in another kind of battle -- this time
against Cuban-Americans in the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   For three months, the communist government has waged a national campaign
pressing for the return of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez, who has been staying with
relatives in Miami since he was rescued off the coast of Florida on Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
	   The boy's mother and others died when their boat sank during an attempt to
reach U.S. shores.
</P>
<P>
	   While Elian's father in Cuba is demanding his parental rights to the child,
the Miami relatives are fighting to keep the boy in the United States, saying
they can give him a better life off the communist island.
</P>
<P>
	   The INS has ruled that Elian should be returned to his father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, but the custody dispute has dragged on while the Miami relatives try
different legal maneuvers aimed at keeping Elian in the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   In Cuba the fight has become a symbol of Castro's decades-long ideological
war against what he calls ``the Miami mafia'' -- Cuban-born Americans who oppose
him and his government.
</P>
<P>
	   Alarcon called the spying charges the result of ``the desperation of the
kidnappers,'' a term used here to describe Elian's relatives and others who
support keeping the boy in the United States. Cuba insists that the boy has been
``kidnapped'' and is being ``held hostage.''
</P>
<P>
	   Cuban authorities say they believe the move to expel Imperatori from
Washington, and the related arrest of a Cuban-born INS official on spying
charges, are aimed at blocking Elian's return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
	   The State Department on Saturday ordered Imperatori to leave the country
within seven days because of alleged links with Mariano Faget, an INS supervisor
recently arrested in Miami on charges of spying for Cuba.
</P>
<P>
	   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said this week that it would be
highly unusual for a state to refuse to remove a diplomat under these
circumstances. Under the Vienna Convention on diplomatic relations, he said,
Cuba must either recall the diplomat in question or terminate his functions.
</P>
<P>
	   However, the Cuban government has said its diplomatic mission in Washington
has not engaged in intelligence activities since it opened in 1977. And on
Thursday, the head of the mission, Fernando Remirez, officially informed the
State Department that Imperatori would not be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
	   Remirez was told ``in no uncertain terms'' that the U.S. government expects
him to leave and that he would lose his diplomatic privileges if he remains, an
administration official said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 2027 </TRAILER>
