<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Fall in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- The Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index inched lower early
Friday, largely unaffected by a decline on Wall Street. The dollar was higher
against the yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 15.17 points, or 0.08
percent, to 19,556.27 in the first 30 minutes of trading. On Thursday, the
average closed up 51.89 points, or 0.27 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar bought 111.32 yen, up 0.26 yen from late Thursday in Tokyo and
also above its late New York level of 111.06 yen.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, the Nikkei moved in a narrow range between negative and
positive territory amid caution about the direction of U.S. stocks.
</P>
<P>
	   Traders said the Tokyo market's downside was supported on hopes for buying
from newly established investment trust funds and the record close in the
technology-rich Nasdaq composite index in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   On Thursday, the Dow Jones industrial average closed down 133.10 at
10,092.63 amid worries about rising interest rates. At one point it briefly fell
below 10,000 points.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nasdaq, however, finished up 67.32 to 4,617.65, reaching a new closing
high for the second day in a row.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was up 5.97 points, or 0.35 percent, to 1,696.02. The TOPIX closed up
22.81 points, or 1.37 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency dealings, the dollar moved slightly higher early Friday in Asia
amid no major market-moving news.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 110.26 yen, down from 110.84 yen
late Thursday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell to 1.8550
percent from Thursday's finish of 1.8700 percent. Its price rose 0.12 point to
99.53.
</P>
</TEXT>
