<HEADLINE> Thursday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press Note: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Environmental Groups Unlikely To Back Endangered-Species Legislation
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- Not a single environmental group is expected to endorse
federal endangered-species legislation about to be introduced by Environment
Minister David Anderson.
</P>
<P>
	   Environmentalists who had hoped Anderson's appointment signalled a new
seriousness on environmental issues on the part of the Liberal government say
privately their hopes have been dashed.
</P>
<P>
	   Canadian activists have restricted themselves to relatively subdued comments
on the record.
</P>
<P>
	   The frontal attack came from U.S. activists, invited to Ottawa by Canadian
allies, at a news conference Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The bill claims to be an endangered species law but there's not one word
in it which requires any Canadian official to protect even one single animal --
ever,'' said Brock Evans, executive director of the U.S. Endangered Species
Coalition, representing more than 400 U.S. environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
	   Evans said U.S. efforts to preserve biodiversity are being undermined by
weak protection for endangered species, from Monarch butterflies to grizzly
bears, when they cross the border into Canada.
</P>
<P>
	    First Indo-Canadian Provincial Leader Sworn in As British Columbia Premier
</P>
<P>
	   VICTORIA, British Columbia (AP) -- A self-described poor boy from India's
Punjab made Canadian history Thursday when he was sworn in as British Columbia's
33rd premier.
</P>
<P>
	   Ujjal Dosanjh smiled from ear to ear as he took an oath of office from
Lt.-Gov. Garde Gardom at Government House.
</P>
<P>
	   Dosanjh, elected New Democratic Party leader last Sunday, is the first
Indo-Canadian premier in Canadian history.
</P>
<P>
	   ``When I started my journey on Dec. 31, 1964, leaving India at the age of
17, little did I know, think or imagine that I would stand here before you today
being called Premier Dosanjh.''
</P>
<P>
	   Dosanjh replaces Dan Miller, who served as interim premier following former
premier Glen Clark's resignation last August.
</P>
<P>
	   Clark resigned after it was revealed he was part of an ongoing police
gambling probe.
</P>
<P>
	    Spending Taps on Full blast in Alberta's Pre-Election-Year Budget 2000
</P>
<P>
	   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- The spending taps will be on full blast in
Alberta's pre-election year 2000 -- continuing a trend of binge-spending made
possible by rocketing revenues.
</P>
<P>
	   The provincial budget tabled Thursday promised pots more money to hire
teachers, doctors and nurses, fix roads and schools, and help seniors and
students.
</P>
<P>
	   Tax changes mean a two-parent family with $50,000 in income and two kids
will pay $907 less in provincial tax as of Jan. 1. And 132,000 low-income
earners will pay no provincial income tax at all.
</P>
<P>
	   User fees are being cut immediately by $60 million a year for everything
from court fees to land title searches. For those buying a $150,000 house with a
$140,000 mortgage, it used to cost $365 in fees to do the legal paperwork. As of
this morning, it costs $133.
</P>
<P>
	   Alberta will spend a record $17.7 billion this year. But it expects to take
in $19.1 billion, thanks to an economy hitting on all cylinders with high oil
and gas prices, a burgeoning manufacturing and high-tech sector and a population
that will hit three million this spring.
</P>
<P>
	    Ottawa, Provinces Announce $400 Million Farm Relief Package
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- Another $400 million in emergency aid for Prairie grain
farmers was denounced Thursday by protesting producers as a ``joke'' that falls
short of their needs.
</P>
<P>
	   Several accused Saskatchewan Premier Roy Romanow of selling out farmers,
only minutes after he joined his Manitoba counterpart Gary Doer and Prime
Minister Jean Chretien to announce the federal-provincial aid package.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're an endangered species, we're a species extinct, we're gone,'' said
Arlynn Kurtz, who farms near Stockholm in southeastern Saskatchewan.
</P>
<P>
	   ''(Romanow) says we need . . . $3 billion and he sold us out for $1 billion
and some of it is already in programs that are in effect,'' added Kurtz.
</P>
<P>
	   Saskatchewan farmers will receive a total of about $1 billion this year
through such programs as crop insurance and the Agriculture Income Disaster
Assistance program, said Romanow.
</P>
<P>
	   Manitoba farmers will receive $100 million in payments that could amount to
between $8,000 and $11,000 per farm family by early spring, said Doer.
</P>
<P>
	    Coroner's Jury Finds Little Girl's Death a Homicide
</P>
<P>
	   TORONTO (AP) -- The death of a little girl who went to hospital suffering
nothing more than pain from a leg broken six months earlier has been ruled a
homicide.
</P>
<P>
	   But while a coroner's jury found the world-renowned Hospital for Sick
Children caused 10-year-old Lisa Shore's death on Oct. 22, 1998, that doesn't
necessarily mean the hospital is criminally culpable.
</P>
<P>
	   A verdict of homicide by a coroner's jury is considered a finding of fact,
not fault or legal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
	   Toronto police said Thursday they must still review the jury's findings
before deciding whether to lay charges.
</P>
<P>
	   Lisa's mother Sharon, who wept as the jury's finding was read aloud
Thursday, immediately demanded a police investigation, the dismissal of hospital
staff involved in her daughter's care and a public inquiry.
</P>
<P>
	   The family's lawyer wants to know why Shore's young daughter, with morphine
pumping into her body, did not have her vital signs checked hourly, as her
doctor had instructed.
</P>
</TEXT>
