<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Urges Strengthening of Will  </HEADLINE>
   By JIM HEINTZ Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MOSCOW (AP) -- In an ``open letter'' to his country, acting President
Vladimir Putin laments Russia's faltering will and failure to confront problems.
</P>
<P>
	   In the letter, to be published Friday in the newspaper Izvestia, Putin says
Russian authorities are increasingly losing face, according to excerpts
published by the news agency Interfax.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The state machinery is difficult to hold together; its engine, the
executive branch, creaks and sneezes whenever one tries to get it going,'' he
writes.
</P>
<P>
	   But some of Putin's challengers in the March 26 election have criticized him
for failing to propose solutions to Russia's severe and complex economic
problems. Putin has said an economic plan is being prepared, and will likely be
made public Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Putin was largely unknown to Russians before becoming prime minister in
August. Since taking the presidency on Dec. 31 after the surprise resignation of
Boris Yeltsin, he has made few specific policy statements.
</P>
<P>
	   Instead, his statements have generally appealed to patriotism and morale.
``The moral fundamentals that one learns in his family and make up the core of
patriotism are important to the Russian citizen,'' his letter says.
</P>
<P>
	   Recent polls show Putin getting as much as 60 percent of the votes in the
11-candidate race. His support apparently reflects wide public approval of his
tough line on the offensive in Chechnya, where he has insisted that rebels must
be wiped out.
</P>
<P>
	   ``A whole republic, a Russian region, Chechnya, was taken over by the
criminal world and turned into a fortress. But we attacked the gangsters and
defeated them,'' his letter says.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This was the first step toward the pre-eminence of the law, to the
dictatorship of a law that treats everyone equally,'' it says.
</P>
<P>
	   Putin's nearest challenger is Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov, shown
in recent polls to have the support of 20 percent or less of voters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 2052 </TRAILER>
