<HEADLINE> Exiled Professor Returns to Georgia  </HEADLINE>
   By ELLIOTT MINOR Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, Ga. (AP) -- As the choir sang freedom songs and mourners shouted
amens, Preston King dabbed his eyes during a funeral service Thursday for his
oldest brother.
</P>
<P>
	   The exiled professor who fled Georgia 39 years ago to avoid imprisonment for
draft evasion had missed the funerals of his parents and three other brothers.
But a presidential pardon allowed him to return to the United States from
England to bury his brother, Clennon W. King Jr.
</P>
<P>
	   Friends remembered Clennon King, 79, also a college professor, as a complex
man who was willing to stand up for his convictions.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He was a debater, a fighter,'' said Lois Jones, who was a classmate of
Clennon King. ``He was so stubborn, you couldn't change his mind.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clennon King, who died Feb. 12 after a three-year battle with prostate
cancer, was the first black person to apply for admission to the all-white
University of Mississippi. Instead of being considered, he was certified insane.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The governor felt that any African-American who would have enough nerve to
apply to go to Ole Miss must be crazy,'' Carol King, a family spokeswoman, told
The Albany Herald for his obituary.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1972, Clennon King ran for president. Then just days before the 1976
presidential election, he tried to desegregate Jimmy Carter's all-white Baptist
church in Plains, Ga. With the congregation split on the issue, Carter and his
supporters formed another church.
</P>
<P>
	   Preston King, 63, returned to the United States from England on Wednesday,
four decades after refusing induction into the Army in the 1960s because the
all-white draft board wouldn't address him as ``Mr.''
</P>
<P>
	   He fled his Albany home in 1961 to avoid an 18-month prison sentence for
draft evasion. President Clinton pardoned him Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   King plans to return Saturday to England, where he is a political science
professor at Lancaster University and his daughter is a member of Parliament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 2102 </TRAILER>
