<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lobbyists spent $17.9 million to influence legislation in 1999  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Spending by lobbyists seeking to sway lawmakers
reached record levels again in 1999, according to reports released Thursday by
the state Election Law Enforcement Commission.
<P>
	   The reports show special interests spent $17.9 million in the effort to get
laws passed or block proposed legislation. That's up 9 percent from the $16.4
million they spent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   The lobbying efforts include $69,617 in "passing benefits" to public
officials. That includes dinners, conferences, golf outings, tickets to ball
games and other perks. This figure is down from the $107,197 that public
officials received in 1998. Except for 1998, the figure has consistently dropped
as lawmakers become more wary of public reports showing such gifts.
</P>
<P>
	   These reports show how much big lobbying firms took in and spent during
1999, but do not include which bills they fought over in a year marked by
battles over open space preservation, school construction, auto insurance, and
energy deregulation.
</P>
<P>
	   However, along with the big firms that serve as hired guns for issues,
several single-issue groups appear on the lists, including ones representing
hospitals, builders, phone companies, lawyers and teachers.
</P>
<P>
	   Frederick Herrmann, executive director of the Election Law Enforcement
Commission, said the cost of influencing lawmakers rises every year. He said
that's not the case with "benefit passing" - the perks to lawmakers, aides and
other public officials.
</P>
<P>
	   "Basically, the trend since 1982, when we started keeping records, is that
it keeps going up," Herrmann said. "However, the benefit passing part is flat.
We don't make value judgments, but the purpose of a disclosure law is to let the
public know if there's undue influence or not. People can conclude it's a good
thing when benefit passing is flat or goes down."
</P>
<P>
	   Tops on the list of "benefit passing" is Sen. Gerald Cardinale, who, along
with his wife, attended a conference in Puerto Rico courtesy of the New Jersey
Bankers Association, according to the report. That accounted for about $2,700 of
the $3,611 Cardinale received in benefits, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
	   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, R-Salem, was fourth on the list with benefits
worth $1,274. These included several golf outings and dinners courtesy of a wide
range of interests, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
	   Collins said he paid "for a number of trips" and said he is "very
comfortable in how I do my job."
</P>
<P>
	   "My role as speaker is to meet with people and discuss various issues,"
Collins said. "If they are over lunch or a round of golf or whatever else, the
same kinds of discussions take place. Obviously, if I thought there was a
problem with it, I would not do it. It is part of the process. If there are
those who think that is negative, they have a right to that."
</P>
<P>
	   Senate President Donald DiFrancesco, who, like Collins, is eyeing a
gubernatorial run, is near the bottom of the list. The report shows he accepted
one trip worth $334, but then paid the lobbyist back for the expenses. The one
perk DiFrancesco accepted without paying back: a $45 trip to Yankee Stadium,
courtesy of Pfizer Inc.
</P>
<P>
	   Jerry Flanagan, legislative coordinator for the New Jersey Public Interest
Research Group, said the latest report shows "big money continues to play a
major role in the legislative process."
</P>
<P>
	   "Unless we're able to curtail that role, democracy will be curtailed and New
Jersey citizens' issues will not be heard," Flanagan said. "Special interests
that can hire high-priced lobbying organizations allow them to have special
access to legislators. The issues and concerns of New Jersey citizens get a
second tier importance."
</P>
<P>
	   However, Hazel Gluck, partner of Gluckshaw, a lobbying firm ranked third in
New Jersey in terms of spending and receipts, said lobbyists are "fair game" for
what she says are unfair charges.
</P>
<P>
	   "Everyone seems to hate lobbyists and used car salesmen," said Gluck. "But
PIRG doesn't have any idea what happens. We have a lot of not-for-profits that
come in, and we charge them very little money. Sometimes we do it pro-bono. We
represent groups like the National Breast Cancer Coalition, food banks, real
people doing wonderful things. We do a lot of that work. I can't tell you the
number of times people call here and ask for help and we check things out for
them, point them in the right direction and never charge them a dime."
</P>
<P>
	   The reports showed the top-spending lobbying firm of 1999 was Public
Strategies Impact, at $1.6 million. The second highest was Princeton Public
Affairs Group, Inc., at $1.2 million, followed by Gluckshaw, at $716,875.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-24-00 2110 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Blacks on TV Are Segregated  </HEADLINE>
    By LYNN ELBER AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Black characters on TV are strong in number but tend to
be segregated in certain sitcoms and on fledgling networks UPN and WB, according
to a Screen Actors Guild study released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Conducted by University of Southern California sociology professor Darnell
M. Hunt, the study examined all comedy and drama series that aired on ABC, CBS,
NBC, Fox and the two newer networks during five weeks in 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   The report comes shortly after the NAACP and other civil rights groups
wrapped up agreements with the four major networks to commit to more ethnically
diverse programming and hiring. A nearly all-white slate of fall 1999 new series
prompted the groups to act.
</P>
<P>
	   Hunt said his findings were important because the way TV includes or
excludes groups of people reflects "unresolved questions about power imbalances
in our society."
</P>
<P>
	   In the SAG-commissioned study, Hunt found that blacks were numerically well
represented. Blacks make up 12.2 percent of the U.S. population but accounted
for nearly 16 percent of the characters seen on the six networks during the
period reviewed.
</P>
<P>
	   But about half of all black characters appeared in comedies, compared with
less than a third, 30 percent, of all white characters, the study found.
</P>
<P>
	   The black characters were concentrated on UPN and WB, which produced less
than a third of the episodes aired, 29.4 percent, but accounted for more than 44
percent of all black characters seen in prime time.
</P>
<P>
	   Seven predominantly black sitcoms airing Monday and Friday nights on UPN and
WB represent nearly two-thirds of all black prime time characters who appear for
a substantial amount of time, more than 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
	   The study "seems to go right to the heart of what our effort has been all
about," said Frank L. Berry, Western region executive director of the NAACP.
Blacks "are being steered, for whatever reason, into comedies."
</P>
<P>
	   Berry said blacks need to branch out not only into dramatic acting roles,
but into writing and directing jobs to ensure their experience is accurately
portrayed.
</P>
<P>
	   While every show on UPN featured a black series regular, less than half of
WB's shows had blacks as regular characters. That suggests "the WB lineup is
largely segregated into 'black' and 'white' shows," according to the study.
</P>
<P>
	   The statistics reflect the tendency of newer networks to go after
underserved minority audiences to build viewership, a tactic Fox once used as a
young network.
</P>
<P>
	   But now blacks are underrepresented at Fox, the study found, and at NBC as
well: Less than 10 percent of the characters on Fox and about 11 percent of
those on NBC were black, and most were not central to story lines.
</P>
<P>
	   Nearly 15 percent of all characters in ABC series and 13 percent of CBS
characters were black.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 2116 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   A high pressure system brought some record high temperatures to parts of the
southern Plains and Southeast on Thursday, while up to a foot of snow fell in
parts of the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
	   A disturbance that pushed through the Great Lakes brought mostly cloudy
skies and scattered showers to the Northeast and upper Midwest. Showers fell in
Ohio, Michigan, New York, Pennsylvania, northern Indiana, and New England.
Temperatures were mild, with 50s throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
	   Farther south, high pressure brought partly cloudy skies and dry conditions
to the Southeast and mid-Atlantic states. Several cities in the Southeast and
southern Plains recorded new record high temperatures in the 70s and 80s.
</P>
<P>
	   Winds gusted to near 30 mph in Texas, Oklahoma, and Kansas. Thunderstorms
started developing over the Texas and Oklahoma panhandles late Thursday, with at
least one storm classified as severe.
</P>
<P>
	   The Rockies got moderate to heavy snowfall, with South Fork, Colo.,
reporting 12 inches of accumulation.
</P>
<P>
	   Conditions were mostly dry in Washington, Oregon and Nevada, but another
Pacific disturbance brought more showers to California.
</P>
<P>
	   The highest temperature reported in the continental United States on
Thursday was 86 degrees in Cotulla, Texas. The low was 5 degrees in Truckee,
Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
