<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Damaging Testimony in Gov.'s Case  </HEADLINE>
   By NATALIE GOTT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- A former casino consultant tearfully told a federal
jury Thursday that he funneled hundreds of thousands of dollars in payoffs to
former Gov. Edwin Edwards and his son Stephen -- before and after Edwards left
office in 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   Ricky Shetler's testimony, backed by Shetler's own ledgers and conversations
secretly recorded by the FBI, was the most damaging to date in Edwards'
seven-week-old federal racketeering trial -- and in the 40-year public life of
the scandal-plagued four-term governor.
</P>
<P>
	   By his own count, Edwards, 72, has been the subject of almost two dozen
state or federal investigations going back to his days as a congressman in the
'60s. In 1985, he was acquitted on federal racketeering charges involving health
care investments.
</P>
<P>
	   Known for his deadpan wit, Edwards has maintained a confident air throughout
this trial, despite a growing body of evidence against him. He has been
restrained from commenting on the evidence by the judge's gag order.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal prosecutors say Edwin and Stephen Edwards and five other men took
part in a series of schemes to manipulate the licensing of riverboat casinos.
The ex-governor could face 350 years in prison and $7.2 million in fines if
convicted. Stephen could get 305 years.
</P>
<P>
	   As governor, Edwards appointed the now-defunct Louisiana Riverboat Gaming
Commission, which granted preliminary approval for riverboat licenses. And he
appointed the head of State Police, which issued the licenses.
</P>
<P>
	   Shetler, a lifelong friend of Stephen Edwards, turned on the Edwards family
in 1998, pleading guilty to extortion conspiracy charges and agreeing to
cooperate with federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
	   He fought back tears on the witness stand Thursday as federal prosecutor
Peter Strasser asked him how he felt about testifying against his friends.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Terrible,'' Shetler replied in a shaky voice while Stephen Edwards looked
on stoically. ``I feel terrible.''
</P>
<P>
	   Shetler said he gave the Edwardses cash, cars, furniture, appliances and
vacations in return for their help in getting state approval for two Players
riverboat casinos at Lake Charles and for hindering competition.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors reviewed ledgers with Shetler in which he had detailed his
payments to Stephen and Edwin Edwards. And they played tapes of conversations
secretly recorded in Edwin Edwards' law office in 1997 -- when Edwards allegedly
was continuing to accept payoffs for things he did before leaving office the
year before.
</P>
<P>
	   In one conversation, on Jan. 9, 1997, Stephen Edwards tells his father:
``I've got to get with Shetler because he still owes you the big check from
November and all of December. That should be six, seven, eight, nine thousand
dollars.''
</P>
<P>
	   In a Feb. 25 conversation in the same office, Edwards appears to be making
sure he does not have to deal directly with the money.
</P>
<P>
	   Stephen Edwards: ``Shetler's been calling me. I think I should just stay in
and meet with him. He's coming in with your money.''
</P>
<P>
	   Edwin Edwards: ``I'd rather you do that.''
</P>
<P>
	   Federal prosecutors have portrayed Players executives as the victims of
extortion rather than participants in a bribery scheme, although some former
executives testified under grants of immunity.
</P>
<P>
	   The case brought pressure on Louisiana gambling regulators to revoke the
company's licenses for its two Lake Charles riverboats. The company eventually
agreed to pay the state $10.8 million and get out of Louisiana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
