<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush, McCain Ad War Escalates  </HEADLINE>
   By SCOTT LINDLAW Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SACRAMENTO (AP) -- As the political ad war escalates in California, Gov.
George W. Bush is under fire from his rival, Sen. John McCain, and from the
Sierra Club. The Texas governor, meanwhile, is stepping up his own advertising
with two new spots, including one in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
	   The Sierra Club ad lambastes Bush's environmental record, charging Texas
with leading the nation in the number of factories violating clean water
standards, and in carcinogens and toxins released. It says he has accepted more
than $1 million in campaign contributions from ``Texas' worst polluters.''
</P>
<P>
	   The ad airing in San Jose and Sacramento mirrors spots the Sierra Club ran
against Bush in New Hampshire and Michigan. The group raised similar questions
about McCain's commitment to the environment in his home state of Arizona, but
is silent on McCain in its California spot.
</P>
<P>
	   Mike Paparian, a Sierra Club spokesman, declined to say who had the poorer
record. The organization, which has not endorsed a candidate in either major
party, went after Bush because he has more latitude to effect change as chief
executive, he said. McCain is a U.S. senator
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're trying to send a message that if he cares about national leadership,
he'd better take care of some environmental leadership back home,'' Paparian
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush's campaign said that since 1995, Texas has reduced the release and
disposal of harmful toxic pollution by 43 million pounds, leading the nation.
And 97.7 percent of Texas wastewater discharge facilities meet state and federal
clean water standards, the campaign said.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, meanwhile, launched an ad in Los Angeles comparing himself to
conservative icon Ronald Reagan. The ad comes as McCain and Bush seek to burnish
their conservative images.
</P>
<P>
	   It touts McCain's priorities, but also takes a dig at Bush's support from
the GOP officials, saying: ``You can't turn on your TV without seeing an ad from
the establishment trying to fool you about me.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush fired back with a press release, replying: ``Senator, you're no Ronald
Reagan.'' McCain is no more interested in tax cuts that President Clinton, the
campaign charged.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush was preparing two ads to begin Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Spanish-language ad shows him in a classroom and features images of
American flags. It touts Bush as ``positive'' and ``inclusive.'' ``George W.
Bush is a family man who shares our conservative values,'' an announcer says.
Looking into the camera, Bush says in Spanish: ``It's a new day.''
</P>
<P>
	   The second ad will promote his record on various issues, his campaign said.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Democratic side, Vice President Al Gore also is running ads in
Spanish.
</P>
<P>
	   About 15 percent of the California electorate is Hispanic. While Bush has
attracted large numbers of them in Texas, California Republicans have fared
poorly with the group in recent years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 2125 </TRAILER>
