<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kellogg Making Private Brand Cereal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    DETROIT (AP) -- Kellogg Co. has agreed to supply cereal to a German discount
supermarket chain under the store's own brand name.
</P>
<P>
	   The Battle Creek-based cereal maker will supply Aldi Group with five
breakfast cereals under the Gletscher Krone brand, the company said late
Thursday, confirming a report on the Web site of London's Financial Times.
</P>
<P>
	   The agreement with Aldi is part of a strategy of cutting costs and using
production capacity across Europe, according to a written statement from
Kellogg.
</P>
<P>
	   The cereal maker said it previously has manufactured under private labels on
a very limited basis in other markets and under very specific market conditions.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is not a major U-turn by the company," said Alan Harris, president of
Kellogg Europe. "It's very much a test. It's limited to Aldi, it's limited to
Germany, and of our total sales in Europe, it will probably account for about 2
percent this year."
</P>
<P>
	   Harris said the Aldi products -- to be called Schoko Chips, Schoko Flakes,
Honey Nut Flakes, Honey Balls and White Flakes -- would be made with a different
recipe from Kellogg's branded products.
</P>
<P>
	   Once the biggest U.S. cereal maker, Kellogg has fallen behind
Minnesota-based General Mills for the first time in decades. Kellogg's market
share of cereal sales for the year ending Jan. 2 was 30.7 percent, compared with
32.2 percent for General Mills, according to Chicago-based Information Resources
Inc.
</P>
<P>
	   The Financial Times reported Kellogg agreed to the deal after Aldi
threatened to give the private-brand business to a German supplier.
</P>
<P>
	   Kellogg spokeswoman Chris Ervin told The Associated Press she had not heard
of any such threat.
</P>
<P>
	   "This was at the request of Aldi as a valued customer of Kellogg," she said
Thursday. "This is for them exclusively."
</P>
<P>
	   Private-brand products accounted for 18.6 percent of cereal sales in Germany
in 1998, up 1.9 percentage points from the year before, according to A.C.
Nielsen, a market research company.
</P>
<P>
	   Kellogg had 1999 earnings of $338.3 million on sales of $6.98 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
