<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NY Senate Race Turns Negative Early  </HEADLINE>
   By MARC HUMBERT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- One of her friends says he looks like a Pez candy
dispenser. He tells potential donors she is guilty of ``hostility toward
America's religious traditions.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Senate race between Hillary Rodham Clinton and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
has turned negative early, much earlier than usual even for normally nasty New
York.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Minus the TV ads, it's like October already,'' pollster Lee Miringoff,
head of Marist College's Institute for Public Opinion, said. ``They're already
doing the hypocrite-liar routine.''
</P>
<P>
	   Already, there are some ads. This month, the New York City mayor began
airing a radio spot attacking the first lady's husband for refusing to tap the
nation's strategic oil reserves to help push down rapidly rising home heating
oil prices.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Mr. President, why don't you feel our pain?'' the mayor asked in what
Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson called ``the first negative ad of the
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
	   That's tame compared with some of the exchanges.
</P>
<P>
	   The first lady has accused the mayor of running a campaign based on insults,
being angry all the time and ill-suited to the collegial Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   At a dinner Sunday night in Albany she advised more than 1,000 blacks and
Hispanics that they should ask the candidates ``will you work to unite people or
will you try to bring more conflict by insulting and demeaning people? ... I
reject the politics of division, revenge and retribution.''
</P>
<P>
	   The mayor has been quick to jump on apparent, but seemingly minor campaign
gaffes by the first lady, including her failure to leave a tip for a waitress at
a restaurant in rural Albion just west of Rochester. She was taken to task for
the playing of Billy Joel's ``Captain Jack,'' a song that deals with drug use,
as part of the warmup music at her formal campaign announcement. Her aides said
they hadn't selected the music.
</P>
<P>
	   The state Democratic Committee has begun putting out a ``City Hall Scandal
Sheet'' that catalogues anything negative written about the mayor. The
Republican National Committee uses its fax machines to bash the first lady at
every opportunity.
</P>
<P>
	   The mayor has a Web site whose address is ``HillaryNo.com'' and regularly
jokes about the ``vast right-wing conspiracy'' that she once blamed for the
Monica Lewinsky sex scandal that led to the president's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
	   For the record, both deny running negative campaigns. It's the other guy,
they say.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're not going to let the Clintons blow into town, set up shop here and
conduct the same kind of very nasty personal campaigns they've done in the
past,'' Giuliani campaign manager Bruce Teitelbaum said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Noting that Clinton campaign adviser James Carville had called Giuliani's
team ``goons'' and ``thugs,'' Teitelbaum said, ``We're not suckers and we won't
be played for suckers ... This is New York. This is a different kind of campaign
and we're not going to be a punching bag.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``There seems to be a charge a day coming from the other side and of course
you have to respond to that,'' Clinton said Tuesday during a Buffalo-area stop.
``But I think New Yorkers want this election to be about their future and that's
what I'm going to try to keep it focused on.''
</P>
<P>
	   Recent polls have shown Giuliani with a slight lead over Clinton and few
undecided voters. That, says GOP political consultant Jay Severin, explains the
negative tactics.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is a race in which both candidates are fairly well known, so there
aren't a lot of ways to get people to love or like you more,'' said Severin, who
is not involved in the Senate race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 2128 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
