<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Principal Arrested for Forgery  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH ANDOVER, Mass. (AP) -- A former elementary school principal already
facing federal heroin possession charges was arrested again Thursday, this time
for allegedly forging a prescription.
</P>
<P>
	   Margaret Loder-Healy, who recently admitted on ABC's ''20/20'' to being a
heroin addict for years, was nabbed by a plainclothes policeman after leaving a
pharmacy counter, where she picked up two prescriptions. Police said she called
the pharmacy Wednesday, pretending to be a nurse from a doctor's office who was
requesting painkillers and an antibiotic.
</P>
<P>
	   She was arrested on charges of a forged prescription and shoplifting.
Authorities said she swiped a packet of candy-coated almonds on her way to the
pharmacy counter.
</P>
<P>
	   She pleaded innocent to the charges Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Loder-Healy, 46, was first charged after police broke up a heroin ring in
October. At the time, she was principal of Memorial Elementary School in Newton,
N.H., where she had earned distinction for helping the small-town school become
the state's best. She resigned in November.
</P>
<P>
	   After initially pleading innocent, she recently struck a deal with federal
prosecutors to plead guilty to heroin-related charges. She faces up to a year in
jail and $100,000 in fines on those charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
