<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senegal Heads Off Election Violence  </HEADLINE>
   By GLENN McKENZIE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DAKAR, Senegal (AP) -- Police and soldiers patrolled sleepy suburbs and
bustling markets Thursday amid scattered political violence just days before
Senegal's most contentious presidential elections in decades.
</P>
<P>
	   At least six people were seriously injured and two homes stoned and torched
Wednesday evening in fighting between opposition and ruling party activists in
Rufisque, about 15 miles east of the capital, Dakar, political officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is all a grave sign for democracy in Senegal,'' said Rufisque Mayor
Mbaye Jacques Diop, a senior ruling party member who owns the two destroyed
homes.
</P>
<P>
	   The fighting spread Thursday to the town of Thies, about 40 miles to the
east. Two more homes, owned by a ruling party official and a political rival,
were burned, the independent radio station Sud FM reported. It was not
immediately clear if there were casualties.
</P>
<P>
	   Relatives and supporters were sweeping up the charred remains of furniture
Thursday, as armored vehicles full of troops guarded the premises.
</P>
<P>
	   Some observers predicted Sunday's vote to be the most difficult in years for
President Abdou Diouf, whose Socialist Party has ruled this West African nation
since independence from France in 1960.
</P>
<P>
	   Opposition leader Abdoulaye Wade and six other candidates are bidding to
oust Diouf. If there is no clear winner on Sunday, the top candidates will
square off in a second round.
</P>
<P>
	   Aides to Diouf, a 62-year-old career politician who first became president
in 1981, confidently predicted an easy first round win.
</P>
<P>
	   Senegal has long been one of Africa's most developed and stable nations,
whose business leaders are often European-educated and renowned for their global
trading savvy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
