<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Thursday, Feb. 24, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Betty Lou Beets Executed in Texas
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- Texas Governor George W. Bush rejected her
last-ditch appeal and Betty Lou Beets was executed tonight for killing her fifth
husband nearly 17 years ago. Beets, 62, had no last remarks before the lethal
injection. Death penalty opponents and domestic violence organizations had urged
Bush to grant Beets a 30-day delay, arguing it would be consistent with his
description of himself as a "compassionate conservative" in his GOP presidential
bid. Beets and her lawyers insisted the former bartender-waitress was the victim
of years of domestic abuse and should be allowed to live.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N.Y.'s Closed Primary Challenged
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A supporter of Sen. John McCain who had been an
independent voter is suing for the right to vote in New York's closed Republican
presidential primary March 7. Currently, only voters registered with the party
may vote in its primary. Wendy Van Wie, 46, had been independent but registered
as a Republican after a federal judge ordered that McCain be placed on the
ballot statewide. But she was told that state law would keep her from voting in
a New York presidential primary until 2004. Voters who switch or join parties
after being uncommitted must wait until after a presidential election to
participate in the new party's primary.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Maine Plans Medicaid Benefits for HIV
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is allowing Maine to provide
Medicaid payments to people who are HIV-positive, but do not yet have AIDS, as
part of an experiment that could expand federal health benefits for HIV and AIDS
victims. Previously, patients could not qualify until they had full-blown AIDS.
Health Secretary Donna Shalala said today that Maine would be the first state to
offer such a plan. The state's five-year demonstration project begins in
September. To be eligible, a participant must be HIV-positive and have an income
of less than about $25,000, which is three times the federal poverty level.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Senegal Heads Off Election Violence
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DAKAR, Senegal (AP) -- Police and soldiers patrolled sleepy suburbs and
bustling markets Thursday amid scattered political violence just days before
Senegal's most contentious presidential elections in decades. At least six
people were seriously injured and two homes stoned and torched Wednesday evening
in fighting between opposition and ruling party activists in Rufisque, about 15
miles east of the capital, Dakar, political officials said. Senegal has long
been one of Africa's most developed and stable nations, whose business leaders
are often European-educated and renowned for their global trading savvy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report: Police Arranged Deportations
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Officers in the police precinct at the heart of a
massive corruption scandal had federal immigration agents deport at least 160
suspected gang members and witnesses to police abuse, the Los Angeles Times
reported today. The Rampart Division's elite anti-gang unit violated a
21-year-old policy by seeking the deportations, the Times reported, citing
senior Immigration and Naturalization Service officials. Allegations that
Rampart CRASH officers beat, framed and shot innocent people have led to the
suspension of 20 officers and reversal of 40 criminal convictions.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Group Finds Candles Containing Lead
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Couples who light candles for a romantic dinner -- or
because the power goes out -- could put enough lead into the air to endanger
small children, said a study released today by a consumer advocacy group. Of 285
candles bought in the Washington area, the cotton wicks in 86 of them were
stiffened with metal and nine of those used high amounts of lead, the Public
Citizen study said. The cotton wick of a candle is woven around a narrow
stiffener, which may be metal or paper. When the candle burns, the metal melts
and releases a residue into the air. U.S. candle makers agreed in 1974 to stop
using lead.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average on Friday
shed 15.17 points to 19,556.27 in early trading. On Thursday, the Dow Jones
industrial average closed down 133.10 at 10,092.63 amid worries about rising
interest rates. At one point it briefly fell below 10,000 points.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pacers Beat Bulls 100-83
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Jalen Rose had 22 points and the Indiana Pacers
overcame a season-high 38 points from Chicago rookie Elton Brand to defeat the
Bulls 100-83 tonight for their 21st straight home victory. Six Indiana players
scored in double figures as Indiana used its balance and depth to improve the
league's best home record to 24-2. Reserves Austin Croshere and Derrick McKey
made crucial contributions, Croshere with 17 points and eight rebounds while
McKey had a season-high 14 points while matching his season-high of 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by PAULINE M. MILLARD
</P>
</TEXT>
