<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Finance Reformer Under Fire  </HEADLINE>
    By KOZO MIZOGUCHI Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- The chief of Japan's financial reform program said Friday he
would not resign despite mounting criticism over his remarks suggesting that
bank inspections would be lenient.
</P>
<P>
	   Michio Ochi, the head of the Financial Reconstruction Commission, told
reporters waiting outside his Tokyo home Friday morning that he was sorry for
causing a stir.
</P>
<P>
	   "But I have no intention to resign," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The furor began Saturday when Ochi told a crowd of officials from credit
unions and other financial institutions in a town north of Tokyo that he would
give them "utmost consideration" during inspections of their businesses.
</P>
<P>
	   The remarks were interpreted to mean that such inspections would be lenient.
</P>
<P>
	   The comments are controversial in Japan because the government has pumped
massive amounts of public money into the banks to help them bounce back from a
bad loan crisis. The crisis has been blamed on bad management and poor oversight
by government regulators.
</P>
<P>
	   The Financial Reconstruction Commission is the government body overseeing
efforts to clean up the industry, and inspections of the institutions are to be
conducted from March to July.
</P>
<P>
	   The opposition has jumped on Ochi's comments, calling for his resignation
and using the scandal to pummel Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
	   Three opposition parties stormed out of a Budget Committee meeting in the
lower house of Parliament on Friday morning in protest.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's time for you to resign," Democrat Kazuhiro Haraguchi railed at Ochi,
accusing him of pandering to the banking industry. Opposition members then
walked out of the conference room.
</P>
<P>
	   Obuchi's government acknowledged Ochi's comments were troublesome.
</P>
<P>
	   "It is undoubtedly true that (his remarks) have caused misunderstanding
among the Japanese people, and that is regrettable," said Chief Cabinet
Secretary Mikio Aoki, who met with Ochi on Friday morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 2206 </TRAILER>
