<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Operation Launched To Aid Ethiopians  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The U.N. World Food Program is launching a $137
million operation Friday to feed more than 2.3 million people drought victims in
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is the hope that by acting now we can prevent a human catastrophe from
developing in the near future,'' U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   A recent food and crop assessment by the Rome-based World Food Program and
the Food and Agriculture Organization indicated that millions of Ethiopians are
in need of food aid.
</P>
<P>
	   For two decades, there has been a shortage of food in Ethiopia, caused
largely by unfavorable weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year's rains were late, and when they finally came, they were unusually
heavy and stormy. As a result, many farms were waterlogged and long-cycle crops,
like corn and sorghum, were destroyed, the WFP and FAO said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
