<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Higher at Midday  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks moved slightly higher Friday morning, largely
unaffected by a decline on Wall Street. The dollar slipped against the yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 14.15 points or 0.07
percent, to 19,585.59 at the end of the morning session. On Thursday, the
average closed up 51.89 points, or 0.27 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar bought 110.74 yen, down 0.32 yen from late Thursday in Tokyo and
also below its late New York level of 111.06 yen.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, the Nikkei fluctuated in a narrow range between
negative and positive territory amid caution about the direction of U.S. stocks.
</P>
<P>
	   But buying of some high technology issues and major department store stocks
pushed the index into positive territory before the end of the morning session.
</P>
<P>
	   Traders said the market's downside was supported by hopes for buying from
newly established investment trust funds and the record close in the
technology-rich Nasdaq composite index in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   On Thursday, the Dow Jones industrial average closed down 133.10 points to
10,092.63 amid worries about rising interest rates. At one point it briefly fell
below 10,000 points.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nasdaq, however, finished up 67.32 points at 4,617.65, reaching a new
closing high for the second day in a row.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was up 26.71 points, or 1.58 percent, to 1,716.76. The TOPIX closed up
22.81 points, or 1.37 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency dealings, traders said the dollar moved lower Friday morning as
some investors covered short, or oversold yen positions. They said there was no
major market-moving news.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 110.92 yen, up from 110.84 yen
late Thursday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.8850
percent from Thursday's finish of 1.8700 percent. Its price fell 0.13 point to
99.28.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
