<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain, Bradley banking on Washington state  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   SEATTLE (AP) - Sen. John McCain and Bill Bradley are looking for a
campaign bounce from independent-minded voters in Washington state, known more
as the home of Microsoft, Starbucks and grunge rock than for any tradition of
being a political player.
<P>
	   McCain spent Wednesday in the state, fresh from his big wins in Republican
presidential primaries in Michigan and Arizona. Bradley, a Democrat, arrived
later for a six-day stay.
</P>
<P>
	   Both presidential candidates say they hope to get some traction with their
maverick, reformist messages, which they believe the voters of Washington state
will embrace next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The campaigns also are looking for a slingshot effect that will influence
balloting in California, New York and other states holding primaries and
caucuses a week later on March 7.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is the first time Washington has had a chance to send a message to the
country. It's an important moment in Washington history, and we think we can do
well here," Bradley said Thursday after a campaign stop in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain and Bradley aren't the only ones with their sights set on the state.
</P>
<P>
	   Democrat Al Gore, a frequent visitor to Washington, is due on Saturday, and
Republican Gov. George W. Bush is confirmed for Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   For the Democrats, Tuesday's primary is no more than a popularity contest,
since none of the 75 delegates to the national convention will be selected until
caucuses the following week. And Republicans are picking only 12 of their 37
delegates through the primary.
</P>
<P>
	   So why all the attention?
</P>
<P>
	   The calendar and the maverick character of Washington's electorate.
</P>
<P>
	   Both Bradley and McCain - who campaigned Wednesday in Spokane, Seattle and
aboard a chartered boat that plied the waters of Puget Sound - have said the
state's quirky political impulses and tradition of picking insurgents could be
of great benefit to their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
	   And Bradley, who is still searching for his first primary victory, said his
campaign has nothing to lose.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're so far behind. The expectation is we're not going to be able to do
anything," he said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're looking for a slingshot effect. If we win this primary or have a
very, very strong showing, the Washington caucus-goers will be reluctant to
reject the will of the people," said Mo Elleithee, a Bradley spokesman. "It will
be a signal to California and the rest of the country that he is viable and this
thing is not wrapped up."
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley plans to stress abortion rights, the environment, campaign finance
reform and education - all popular causes in this Democratic-leaning state.
</P>
<P>
	   But state Democratic Chairman Paul Berendt, who supports Gore for the
party's presidential nomination, said Bradley's focus smacks of desperation.
Most of the state's Democratic establishment, including popular Gov. Gary Locke,
are in the vice president's corner.
</P>
<P>
	   "He has to win someplace or his campaign will die," said Berendt, who urged
Bradley in a letter to abandon "your negative personal attacks" against Gore.
"It is high risk what he's doing, but what choice does he have?"
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley, though, points to Washington primary victories by insurgents like
Gary Hart, Paul Tsongas and Jerry Brown over establishment favorites in previous
years. The Rev. Jesse Jackson also did well here, as did Reform Party founder
Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's state spokesman, Brian Jones, said, "It is very important for us to
win the primary and we're confident we will be able to do that."
</P>
<P>
	   State GOP Chairman Dale Foreman sees Bush as the likely winner of the
caucuses, given his superior organization. But the primary seems up for grabs,
he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "It ain't over here," Foreman said. "McCain comes here with a big bounce. He
recognizes he has to do well in this state, and he should do well."
</P>
<P>
	   Stuart Elway, an independent pollster, said Bradley and McCain seem to be
courting the same unaffiliated voters, but that McCain seems to be winning that
battle.
</P>
<P>
	   His latest poll - following the trend in the Republican race - showed McCain
leading among independents, but trailing Bush among self-identified Republicans.
Gore had a strong lead over Bradley among Democrats, but was running
neck-and-neck among independents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
