<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Thursday, Feb. 24, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Betty Lou Beets Executed in Texas
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- Betty Lous Beets, the Texas woman convicted of
killing her fifth husband, was executed today by lethal injection after her
11th-hour request for reprieve was rejected. She gave no final statement as she
lay strapped to the death chamber gurney. She made no eye contact with the
victim's family, but smiled at her attorney and a spiritual adviser watching
through a window at her side. She continued smiling as she slipped into
unconsciousness. Beets and her lawyers insisted the former bartender-waitress
was the victim of years of domestic abuse and should be allowed to live.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McCain Bids for GOP Votes in Calif.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Calling himself "a proud Reagan Republican," John
McCain touted his endorsement by San Diego's GOP mayor today and underlined
conservative credentials in a new ad airing in primary states from California to
New York. After winning in New Hampshire and Michigan with an appeal to
Democrats and independents as well as Republicans, McCain is seeking to gain on
rival George W. Bush among registered Republicans here. Republicans alone will
determine which candidate is awarded all 162 of the state's GOP presidential
delegates in the March 7 primary.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Violence Mars Johns Hopkins Protest
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BALTIMORE (AP) -- A demonstration by Johns Hopkins University students and
local labor leaders erupted into violence today as some protesters tried to
force their way into the university's administration building. The rally was
held to underscore demands that the school extend its "living wage" policy to
independent contractors. About seven protesters wrestled with security guards
for about five minutes as they tried to enter the building through a side door.
One guard was bloodied and at least one student received a black eye. Members of
the Student Labor Action Committee want the university to require vendors that
provide services for the school to pay workers the $7.75 hourly wage that
university employees and contract workers are paid.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ex-Principal Arrested for Forgery
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NORTH ANDOVER, Mass. (AP) -- A former elementary school principal already
facing federal heroin possession charges was arrested again today, this time for
allegedly forging a prescription. Margaret Loder-Healy, who recently admitted on
ABC's "20/20" to being a heroin addict for years, was nabbed by a plainclothes
policeman after leaving a pharmacy counter, where she picked up two
prescriptions. Police said she called the pharmacy Wednesday, pretending to be a
nurse from a doctor's office who was requesting painkillers and an antibiotic.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Senegal Heads Off Election Violence
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DAKAR, Senegal (AP) -- Police and soldiers patrolled sleepy suburbs and
bustling markets Thursday amid scattered political violence just days before
Senegal's most contentious presidential elections in decades. At least six
people were seriously injured and two homes stoned and torched Wednesday evening
in fighting between opposition and ruling party activists in Rufisque, about 15
miles east of the capital, Dakar, political officials said. Senegal has long
been one of Africa's most developed and stable nations, whose business leaders
are often European-educated and renowned for their global trading savvy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Study: Blacks on TV Are Segregated
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Black characters on TV are strong in number but tend to
be segregated in certain sitcoms and on fledgling networks UPN and WB, according
to a Screen Actors Guild study released today. Conducted by University of
Southern California sociology professor Darnell M. Hunt, the study examined all
comedy and drama series that aired on ABC, CBS, NBC, Fox and the two newer
networks during five weeks in 1999. The report comes shortly after the NAACP and
other civil rights groups wrapped up agreements with the four major networks to
commit to more ethnically diverse programming and hiring.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Stocks Higher at Midday
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 14.15
points at the end of the morning session. On Thursday, the Dow Jones industrial
average closed down 133.10 at 10,092.63 amid worries about rising interest
rates. At one point it briefly fell below 10,000 points.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lightning Beat Senators 5-4
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Mike Johnson scored two goals and added an assist as the
Tampa Bay Lightning beat the Ottawa Senators 5-4 on tonight. Nils Ekman, Steve
Martins and Mike Sillinger also scored to help the Lightning win consecutive
games for the second time this season. Zac Bierk made 33 saves in his second
start of the season. Bierk, recalled from Detroit of the IHL on Tuesday, stopped
30 shots in a 4-1 victory over Philadelphia on Nov. 22. Vaclav Prospal had two
goals for Ottawa, which remains three points behind first-place Toronto in the
Northeast Division.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by PAULINE M. MILLARD
</P>
