<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lautenberg endorses Corzine over Florio in U.S. Senate race  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - U.S. Sen. Frank Lautenberg is endorsing fellow
self-made millionaire Jon Corzine as the Democratic nominee to replace him on
Capitol Hill.
<P>
	   The endorsement will give Corzine a prized edge in his race against former
Gov. Jim Florio in the Democratic Party primary for Lautenberg's seat.
Lautenberg last year announced his retirement after 18 years of representing New
Jersey in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   Lautenberg said he made the endorsement in the hope of ending the bickering
between the two that many fear is damaging the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think this is a point in time when it's important for us to kind of
declare ourselves. A poll shows him way behind," Lautenberg said of Corzine.
"He's got an imminently good chance of taking the front place in this race, and
I want to help him do it."
</P>
<P>
	   "I want to try to eliminate as much as we can what kind of conflict or
contest we're going to have here," the senator said. "I want to get out of a
squabble as much as is possible."
</P>
<P>
	   The Corzine campaign said Lautenberg's backing would give their candidate
"an enormous stamp of credibility among core Democrats."
</P>
<P>
	   The Florio campaign regretted and dismissed the endorsement. "We are of
course disappointed, but it hasn't changed our strategy, which is not to play
the endorsement game," said Michael Murphy, a cochairman of the Florio campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   Murphy said Florio maintains his appeal with rank-and-file party members
among whom Corzine is unknown. He said, "Standing next to Frank Lautenberg does
not automatically overcome a difficult disadvantage, and a virtually
insurmountable one, which is: 'Jon Who?' "
</P>
<P>
	   Lautenberg made his endorsement formal with a public statement at the Bergen
County Democratic Party convention Thursday night in Hackensack.
</P>
<P>
	   In choosing the political newcomer over one of New Jersey's most
battle-scarred veterans, Lautenberg also is turning his back on a former
congressional colleague. Florio was in the House of Representatives when
Lautenberg arrived in Washington, and the two cosponsored key environmental
measures such as the Superfund cleanup law. Florio left the House in 1990 to
become governor.
</P>
<P>
	   "My regard is high for Jim Florio," Lautenberg said. "I think the times have
changed, and it is now time to look forward."
</P>
<P>
	   Lautenberg said he would back Florio vigorously, should he win the
nomination over Corzine on June 6.
</P>
<P>
	   Democratic political consultant Pat Politano said he could be taken at his
word. "U.S. senators have a tendency to make friends very fast," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Jennifer Duffy, who analyzes Senate politics for the Cook Political Report
in Washington, said Lautenberg's move "is fascinating."
</P>
<P>
	   "It breaks with tradition, certainly, of members who stay out of contested
primaries for people who are vying to succeed them," Duffy said. "Finally they
are admitting publicly what we know has been going on behind the scenes: The
establishment backs Jon Corzine."
</P>
<P>
	   Duffy disagrees with Murphy that Corzine's anonymity is a threat. "With or
without Lautenberg, he could probably do it in sheer dollars for ads and phone
banks and mail."
</P>
<P>
	   Like Corzine, Lautenberg was a millionaire executive who had climbed the
corporate ladder from a working-class background and who late in his career
stepped away from the business world to run for national office.
</P>
<P>
	   Corzine was chairman of Goldman Sachs and is largely funding his own
campaign. Neither he nor Lautenberg had been elected to any office prior to
pursuing a U.S. Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
	   "He is the perfect one to carry it out. We share our views. He is a
self-made man," Lautenberg said. "There is a commonality of view when a business
person comes into the picture."
</P>
<P>
	   Steve Goldstein, co-manager of the Corzine campaign and former aide to
Lautenberg, said the retiring senator's endorsement was "the honor of a
political lifetime" because "he is one of the two or three great senators of the
last 40 years in this country."
</P>
<P>
	   On the Republican side, U.S. Rep. Bob Franks, R-New Providence; state Sen.
William Gormley, R-Atlantic; Essex County executive Jim Treffinger; and former
Libertarian candidate for governor Murray Sabrin have announced plans to run.
Gov. Christie Whitman had been an early favorite in the contest before
withdrawing her name in September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-24-00 2308 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
