<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MLS Trial To Start Sept. 18  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    BOSTON (AP) -- A federal judge set a Sept. 18 trial date Thursday in the
antitrust suit Major League Soccer players filed against the league more than
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Players claim the league violates federal antitrust laws. Rather than have
individual franchises create a league, MLS formed as a single entity and signed
all players to contracts with the league itself, then assigned them to teams.
</P>
<P>
	   The case, filed on Feb. 13, 1997, had been in the discovery phase for many
months.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. District Judge George A. O'Toole Jr. made several procedural rulings
during a conference Thursday and set the trial date.
</P>
<P>
	   "While Major League Soccer believes it unfortunate that the players continue
to refuse to seek to resolve their differences with the league through
traditional collective bargaining, MLS looks forward to presenting its case at
trial and remains confident that it will prevail," MLS chief operating officer
Mark Abbott said.
</P>
<P>
	   In a 1996 decision involving the NFL, the U.S. Supreme Court prohibited
labor unions from filing antitrust suits, one of the reasons MLS players have
never formed a union.
</P>
<P>
	   The suit was filed as a class action by Sean Bowers, Paul Caligiuri, Mark
Dodd, Mark Dougherty, Iain Fraser, Rhett Harty, Tim Martin, Mark Semioli, Steve
Trittschuh and David Scott Vaudreuil.
</P>
<P>
	   Jeffrey Kessler is the leading lawyer for the players. Kessler and his firm
have been involved in antitrust cases involving the NFL and NBA.
</P>
<P>
	   He also represented Bill Belichick in his attempt to get an injunction
against the NFL. After losing, Belichick became coach of the New England
Patriots after the team worked out a deal with the New York Jets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 2321 </TRAILER>
