<HEADLINE> Balloonist Tries 2nd Solo Voyage  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- The man who hopes to become the first hot air balloonist to
circle the globe alone was slowly making his way toward Puerto Rico on Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
	   Kevin Uliassi was cruising at roughly 25 mph in his 160-foot balloon at an
altitude of about 21,000 feet. He successfully maneuvered around thunderstorms
storms as he flew over the Dominican Republic but was headed for more, said Todd
Little, who was at Uliassi's the flight's command center in suburban Chicago.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is unlikely they will have serious implications for the balloon,''
Little said.
</P>
<P>
	   Uliassi had planned to climb to a higher altitude Friday to catch stronger
winds that would carry him to Africa, where he hoped to be in seven days.
</P>
<P>
	   Uliassi, 36, who quit his job three years ago to make the flight, lifted off
early Tuesday from a stone quarry near Rockford, Ill. He hopes to complete the
flight in 14 to 20 days.
</P>
<P>
	   Uliassi is communicating with his wife and friends by computer and
telephone, and occasionally chats with pilots of passing airliners.
</P>
<P>
	   It is the second attempt for Uliassi, who lives in Scottsdale, Ariz. In
December 1997, the bottom of his balloon ruptured over O'Hare International
Airport, forcing Uliassi down in Indiana not long after he took off from the
Chicago area.
</P>
</TEXT>
