<HEADLINE> Miss. Has Black Student Body Head  </HEADLINE>
   By PAUL PAYNE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- The University of Mississippi, which has struggled
for decades to overcome its reputation of racial discrimination, on Thursday
elected its first black student body president.
</P>
<P>
	   Nic Lott, a political science major, beat Scott Walker, a white business
major, 1,056 votes to 922 votes.
</P>
<P>
	   Lott, president of the statewide College Republicans, said race played no
role in the election.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I haven't made an issue of it,'' Lott said. ``I'm running to represent all
Ole Miss students.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ole Miss gained notoriety in 1962 when students rioted in protest of the
registration of James Meredith, the school's first black student. Now blacks
make up about 12 percent of the university's 10,000 students.
</P>
<P>
	   Lott campaigned for the establishment of a House of Representatives in
student government. Ole Miss has only a Senate. Walker's campaign focused on
moving the Ole Miss band to a different location at football games.
</P>
<P>
	   Black student leaders at Ole Miss said Lott's election could help mend race
relations, which became strained this month after a brick that had a note
containing racial epithets attached was thrown through a dormitory director's
window.
</P>
<P>
	   After that, a flier about Black History Month was torn down and replaced
with a computer-generated graphic showing a monkey eating an apple, racial slurs
and a Confederate flag.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 2326 </TRAILER>
