<DOCNO> APW20000224.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NTSB Recommends Changes to Boats  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID A. LIEB Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The National Transportation Safety Board on
Thursday urged owners of amphibious tourist boats to install backup flotation
devices because of risks that the vessels could sink rapidly.
</P>
<P>
	   The recommendation comes in response to the sinking of the Miss Majestic, a
World War II-vintage boat that sank last May in Hot Springs, killing 13 people.
</P>
<P>
	   The Coast Guard concluded that a dislodged seal allowed water to flood the
hull of the Miss Majestic, and the boat's bilge pump failed to work.
</P>
<P>
	   The NTSB said boat operators should not rely on the pumps only, recommending
the installation of backup flotation devices -- watertight bulkheads, buoyant
materials inside the hull or flotation attachments on the outside of the boat.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The safety board concludes that the potential exists for another
life-threatening accident similar to the sinking of the Miss Majestic, unless
the vulnerability to flooding and sinking is addressed,'' the NTSB said in a
letter to the industry.
</P>
<P>
	   Nationwide, more than 250 amphibious passenger boats are in service.
</P>
<P>
	   At least 18 amphibious boats had accidents -- six involving some degree of
flooding -- between March 6, 1991, and May 1, 1999, according to Coast Guard
data. None was fatal.
</P>
<P>
	   The safety board said it has learned of at least nine other incidents
involving significant flooding that were not reported to the Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
	   Some tourist boat owners said the NTSB suggestions may not be necessary. The
NTSB asked the industry to respond to the recommendations within 90 days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 2328 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0359 </DOCNO>
