<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Baby Dies After No Transplant  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- An 18-month old Japanese girl considered too ill to survive a
heart-lung-liver transplant in the United States died the day after returning to
Japan, a hospital official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Akari Saino, who was born with a severe congenital heart defect, died on
Thursday in northern Japan, said Shinichi Torii, spokesman for Sapporo Medical
College.
</P>
<P>
	   The girl's parents brought her to Lucile Salter Packard Children's Hospital
at Stanford University in California in late January to be put on a waiting list
for a heart-lung transplant.
</P>
<P>
	   But doctors found that she would also need a liver transplant, and
determined that she was too weak to survive the surgery. Only 10
heart-lung-liver transplants have been performed, all on adults.
</P>
<P>
	   The family returned to Japan on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Transplants are extremely rare in Japan, where certain transplant procedures
were illegal until recently. Many Japanese still travel to the United States for
transplants that are difficult or impossible at home.
</P>
<P>
	   Japan outlaws heart-lung transplants for patients under 15.
</P>
<P>
	   The case has drawn attention in Japan, where the Save Akari Foundation set
up by her parents had raised over 100 million yen (dlrs 900,000) to pay for the
girl's travel to the United States and treatment, Kyodo News agency reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 2330 </TRAILER>
