<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bombing Suspect Shot by Police  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DINWIDDIE, Va. (AP) -- A man suspected of planting bombs that exploded
beneath two pickup trucks and outside a business was shot and wounded Thursday
by police after he was discovered hiding under a church.
</P>
<P>
	   Luis Cristobal, a 47-year-old Cuban citizen, had been sought since Feb. 7.
Police said he planted bombs under trucks owned by Cristobal's brother-in-law
and a man acquainted with Cristobal's estranged wife. The third bomb was placed
outside a building where Cristobal used to work.
</P>
<P>
	   The acquaintance of Cristobal's wife suffered a leg injury. The
brother-in-law was uninjured. No one was hurt at the business bombing.
</P>
<P>
	   After getting tips from several people, a police officer found Cristobal in
a crawl space beneath Dinwiddie Church of Christ, where the suspect is a member.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He crawled in there just as an exploratory search,'' state police
spokeswoman Corinne Geller said. ``He crawled in there expecting to see cobwebs,
and instead found Cristobal pointing a gun at him.''
</P>
<P>
	   The fugitive was asked to put down the gun and would not, so the officer
fired, Geller said. Cristobal was in stable condition from the shooting.
</P>
<P>
	   Bomb squads found an explosive device, an assault rifle with a large amount
of ammunition and a sleeping bag in the crawl space, Geller said.
</P>
<P>
	   Cristobal faces attempted murder and explosives charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
