<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Rips Wizards' Dedication  </HEADLINE>
    By JOSEPH WHITE AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Michael Jordan wasn't able to pull off a deal to help his
awful team. Then he watched his players get beat badly and ripped them for
lacked of dedication.
</P>
<P>
	   Jordan explored whether he could unload one of the Washington Wizards
overpriced threesome -- Juwan Howard, Rod Strickland or Mitch Richmond -- but
nobody wanted to take on their high salaries and mediocre stats. Shortly after
the 6 p.m. EST trading deadline passed, Jordan retreated to the owners' box and
watched the Wizards fall behind early and lose 92-83 to the Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't think it's a lack of talent," said Jordan, who became the team's
president of basketball operations and a part-owner last month.
</P>
<P>
	   "They need dedication for each and every game that you step on the
basketball court. That's an area of improvement for this team, and I will demand
it. Until I walk away from this position, each and every time you step on the
court you bring forth the same effort."
</P>
<P>
	   Howard, Strickland and Richmond are making $35 million this year, which
already puts the Wizards over the salary cap, and their contracts run for at
least two more seasons. Howard and Richmond are having the worst seasons of
their careers, and Strickland isn't doing much better. The Wizards are 16-39.
</P>
<P>
	   And, with a new luxury tax due on the horizon for teams that are well over
the cap, the Wizards are in a bind Jordan can't fix.
</P>
<P>
	   "Right now we have three situations, three contracts that put us right in
the area that you have to deal with the luxury tax," Jordan said. "If it's a
successful situation and they're producing and we're winning, I'm not afraid and
I'm pretty sure the management will forfeit some of the luxury tax.
</P>
<P>
	   "But if it's within a losing situation where we're not really successful,
then quite naturally we have to evaluate and move some of those big contracts."
</P>
<P>
	   Jordan said some of the inquiries he had give him encouragement that a deal
could be made in the offseason. Meanwhile, he's dealing with a lot of losing.
Firing coach Gar Heard and hiring Darrell Walker hasn't helped the won-loss
record.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a little frustrating," Jordan said. "It's something I won't get used
to. It's OK that we're going through a transitional period with the coaching
change with not really the continuity among this team, but very soon I will
demand some type of compromise amongst the talent on this team."
</P>
<P>
	   Jordan also said he supported general manager Wes Unseld, who has accepted a
five-year contract extension that was on the table before Jordan arrived. The
extension appears to go against Jordan's initial pledge that everyone was
expendable while he evaluated the organization.
</P>
<P>
	   "He adds a lot of knowledge to this team," Jordan said. "He adds a lot of
knowledge to me."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-24-00 2349 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000224.0369 </DOCNO>
