<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Charged in Package Bomb Death  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVERETT, Mass. (AP) -- A man accused of stalking a woman who was killed last
month by a package bomb was charged in her death Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Steven Caruso, 44, was the initial suspect in the Jan. 20 killing of Sandra
Berfield, 32, who had sought a restraining order against him.
</P>
<P>
	   He has been in jail on probation violations and weapons charges since police
investigating the bombing found four unlicensed guns, a stun gun and ammunition
at his house.
</P>
<P>
	   District Attorney Martha Coakley said investigators also found evidence
consistent with the bomb and papers showing that he had a motive to kill her,
although she wouldn't describe the papers.
</P>
<P>
	   Caruso's lawyer, Elliott Levine, did not immediately return a message.
</P>
<P>
	   Berfield, a waitress, sought court protection against Caruso in 1998 after
she said he was stalking her at work. Friends said she was so afraid of him that
she slept with a knife and installed a surveillance camera at her home.
</P>
<P>
	   In May, Caruso was sentenced to six months in jail after being convicted of
malicious destruction of property on Berfield's car. He was released in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
